<DIV1 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000018.tif" N="xvi">

<PB REF="00000019.tif" N="[1]">
<HEAD>Hymns to the Virgin, Christ, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>Veni, Coronaberis.</HEAD> 
<HEADNOTE><P>(A SONG OF GREAT SWEETNESS FROM CHRIST TO HIS DAINTIEST DAM.) (<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 1.)</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SUrge mea sponsa, swete in si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And se &thorn;i sone &thorn;ou &yogh;afe souke so scheene;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt abide with &thorn;i babe so bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="4">And in my glorie be callide a queene.</L>
<L>Thi mammillis, moder, ful weel y meene,</L>
<L>Y had to my meete &thorn;at y my&yogh;t not mys;</L>
<L>Aboue alle creaturis, my moder clene,</L>
<L N="8">Veni, coronaberis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Come, clenner &thorn;an cristal, to my cage;</L>
<L>Columba mea, y &thorn;ee calle,</L>
<L>And se &thorn;i sone &thorn;at in seruage</L>
<L N="12">For mannis soule was made a &thorn;ralle.</L>
<L>In &thorn;i palijs so principal</L>
<L>I pleyde priuyli wi&thorn;oute mys;</L>
<L>Myn hi&yogh; cage, moder, haue &thorn;ou schal;</L>
<L N="16">Veni, coronaberis.
<PB REF="00000020.tif" N="2"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For macula, moder, was neuere in &thorn;ee;</L>
<L>Filia syon, &thorn;ou art &thorn;e flour;</L>
<L>Ful sweteli schalt &thorn;ou sitte bi me,</L>
<L N="20">And bere a crowne with me in tour,</L>
<L>&para; And alle my seintis to &thorn;in honour<MILESTONE N="2" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Schal honoure &thorn;ee, moder, in my blis,</L>
<L>&THORN;at blessid bodi &thorn;at bare me in bowur,</L>
<L N="24">Veni, coronaberis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tota pulcra &thorn;ou art to my plesynge,</L>
<L>My moder, princes of paradijs,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> a watir ful weel gan sprynge</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at schal a&yogh;en alle my ri&yogh;tis rise;</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e welle of mercy in &thorn;ee, moder, lijs</L>
<L>To bringe &thorn;i blessid bodi to blis;</L>
<L>And my seintis schulen do &thorn;ee seruice,</L>
<L N="32">Veni, coronaberis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Veni, electa mea, meekeli chosen,</L>
<L>Holi moder &amp; maiden queene,</L>
<L>On sege to sitte semeli bi him an hi&yogh;,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;i sone and eek &thorn;i childe.</L>
<L>&para; Here, moder, wi&thorn; me to dwelle,</L>
<L>With &thorn;i swete babe &thorn;at sitti&thorn; in blis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere in ioie &amp; blis &thorn;at schal neuere mys,</L>
<L N="40">Veni, coronaberis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Veni, electa mea, my moder swete,<MILESTONE N="3" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;ou bad me, babe, be ful stille,</L>
<L>Ful goodli oure lippis &thorn;an gan mete,</L>
<L N="44">With bri&yogh;t braunchis as blosmes on hille.</L>
<L>&para; Fanus distillans it wente with wille,</L>
<L>Oute of oure lippis whanne we dide kis,</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, moder, now ful stille,</L>
<L N="48">Veni, coronaberis.
<PB REF="00000021.tif" N="3"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Veni de libano, &thorn;ou loueli in launche,</L>
<L>&THORN;at lappid me loueli with liking song,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schalt abide with a blessid braunche,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at so semeli of &thorn;i bodi sprong.</L>
<L>&para; Ego, flos campi, &thorn;i flour, was solde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at on calueri to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> cried y-wys:</L>
<L>Moder, &thorn;ou woost &thorn;is is as y wolde;</L>
<L N="56">Veni, coronaberis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Pulcra vt luna, &thorn;ou berist &thorn;e lamme,</L>
<L>As &thorn;e sunne &thorn;at schine&thorn; clere,</L>
<L>Veni in ortum meum, &thorn;ou deintiest damme,</L>
<L N="60">To smelle my spicis<NOTE PLACE="foot">Compare "Awake, O north wind, and come, thou south; blow upon my garden, <I>that</I> the spices thereof may flow out. Let my beloved come into his garden, and eat his pleasant fruits." <I>Solomon's Song</I>, ch. iv. 16. "My beloved is gone down into his garden, to the beds of spices, to feed in the gardens, and to gather lilies." vi. 2.</NOTE> &thorn;at here ben in fere.</L>
<L>My palijs is pi&yogh;t for &thorn;i pleasure,<MILESTONE N="4" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Ful of bri&yogh;t braunchis &amp; blosmes of blis;</L>
<L>Come now, moder, to &thorn;i derling dere!</L>
<L N="64">Veni, coronaberis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quid est ista so vertuose</L>
<L>&THORN;at is euere lastyng for her meekenes?</L>
<L>Aurora consurgens graciouse,</L>
<L N="68">So benigne a ladi, of such bri&yogh;tnes,</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is is &thorn;e colour of kinde clennes,</L>
<L>Regina celi &thorn;at neuere dide mys;</L>
<L>&THORN;us eendi&thorn; &thorn;e song of greet swettnes,</L>
<L N="72">Veni, coronaberis.<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Quia Amore Langueo</I>, or "In a tabernacle of a tour," and its continuation "In a valey of &thorn;is restles mynde," printed in <I>Politi|cal, Religious, and Love Poems</I>, pp. 148-150, follow here. Then "Ihesu, &thorn;i swetnes," p. 8, and "Ihesus &thorn;at sprong," p. 12, of this volume.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000022.tif" N="4">
<HEAD>Hail, Blessed Mary!</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P><I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 24.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HEil be &thorn;ou, marie, &thorn;e modir of crist,</L>
<L>Heil &thorn;e blessidist &thorn;at euere bare child!</L>
<L>Heil &thorn;at conceyuedist al wi&thorn; list</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e sone of god bo&thorn;e meeke &amp; mylde!</L>
<L>&para; Heil maide sweete &thorn;at neuere was filid!</L>
<L>Heil welle and witt of al wijsdome!</L>
<L>Heil &thorn;ou flour! heil fairest in feeld!</L>
<L N="8"><B>Aue regina celorum!</B></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil comeli queene, coumfort of care!</L>
<L>Heil blessid lady bothe fair &amp; bri&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Heil &thorn;e saluour of al sore!</L>
<L N="12">Heil &thorn;e laumpe of lemys li&yogh;t!</L>
<L>&para; Heil &thorn;ou blessid beerde in whom [crist] was pi&yogh;t!<MILESTONE N="25" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Heil ioie of man bothe al and sum!</L>
<L>Heil pinacle in heuene an hi&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="16"><B>Mater regis angelorum!</B></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil crowned queene, fairest of alle!</L>
<L>Heil &thorn;at alle oure blis in bradde!</L>
<L>Heil &thorn;at alle wommen on doon calle</L>
<L N="20">in temynge whanne &thorn;ei ben hard bistadde!</L>
<L>&para; Heil &thorn;ou &thorn;at alle feendis dredde,</L>
<L>And schulen do til &thorn;e day of doome!</L>
<L>With maidens mylk &thorn;i sone &thorn;ou fedde,</L>
<L N="24"><B>O maria, flos virginum.</B>
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="5"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil fairest &thorn;at euere god foond,</L>
<L>Whiche chees &thorn;ee to his owne bour!</L>
<L>Heil &thorn;e lanterne &thorn;at is ay li&yogh;thond!</L>
<L N="28">To &thorn;ee schulen loute bo&thorn;e riche &amp; poore.</L>
<L>&para; Heil spice swettist of sauour!</L>
<L>Heil &thorn;at al oure ioye of come!</L>
<L>Heil of alle wommen fruyt &amp; flour!</L>
<L N="32"><B>Velud</B><NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>velud; l, u</I>, and <I>d</I> rubbed]</NOTE> <B>rosa vel lilium.</B></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil be &thorn;ou goodli ground of grace!<MILESTONE N="26" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Heil blessid sterre upon &thorn;e see!</L>
<L>Heil of coumfortis in euery caas!</L>
<L N="36">&para; Heil &thorn;e cheeuest of charitee!</L>
<L>Heil welle of witt and of merci!</L>
<L>Heil &thorn;at bare ihesu, goddis sone!</L>
<L>Heil tabernacle of &thorn;e trynyte!</L>
<L N="40"><B>Funde preces ad filium.</B></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil be &thorn;ou virgyne of virgins!</L>
<L>Heil blessid modir! heil blessid may!</L>
<L>Heil norische of sweete ihesus!</L>
<L N="44">Heil cheefest of chastite, forso&thorn;e to say!</L>
<L>&para; Lady, kepe vs so in oure last day</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may come to &thorn;i kingdom!</L>
<L>For me &amp; alle cristen &thorn;ou pray,</L>
<L N="48"><B>Pro salute fidelium.</B></L>
<TRAILER>Amen.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000024.tif" N="6">
<HEAD>Aue Maria.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 26. <I>Partly written without breaks.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HEil be &thorn;ou marie, cristis moder dere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at art queene of heuen, fair and sweete of chere,</L>
<L>&THORN;at art sterre of heuen schinynge bri&yogh;t &amp; clere!</L>
<L N="4">Helpe me, lady <MILESTONE N="27" UNIT="page">ful of my&yogh;t, &amp; heere my praiere</L>
<L><B>Aue maria.</B></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil blessid marie, mylde queene of heuen!</L>
<L>Blessid be &thorn;i name, ful good it is to nempne:</L>
<L N="8">To &thorn;ee, lady, y make my moone; I praie &thorn;ee heere my steuen,</L>
<L>And let me neuere die in noon of &thorn;e synnis seuene.</L>
<L><B>Aue maria.</B></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil be &thorn;ou marie &thorn;at art flour of alle,</L>
<L N="12">As roose in eerbir so reed!</L>
<L>To &thorn;ee, ladi, y clepe and calle,</L>
<L>To &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> y make my beed;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou be in stide &amp; in stalle</L>
<L N="16">Whanne y schal drawe to deed,</L>
<L>And lete me neuere falle</L>
<L>in boondis of &thorn;e queed!</L>
<L><B>Aue maria.</B></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="20">Heil be &thorn;ou, marie, &thorn;at hi&yogh; sittist in troone!</L>
<L>Y biseche &thorn;ee, sweete lady, graunte me my boone,
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>Ihesu to loue &amp; drede, &amp; my lijfe to ameende soone,</L>
<L>And bring me to &thorn;at blis &thorn;at neuere schal be doone.</L>
<L N="24"><B>Aue maria.</B></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Heil be &thorn;ou marie, gloriouse moder hende!</L>
<L>Meeknes &amp; honeste, with abstynence, me sende,</L>
<L>With chastite &amp; charite into my lyues eende,</L>
<L N="28">And &thorn;at &thorn;oru&yogh; &thorn;i praier, lady, I mote to heuen blis weende!</L>
<L><B>Aue maria.</B><NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Oratio Magistri Richardi de Castre</I>, p. 15, below, follows here.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000026.tif" N="8">
<HEAD>Poems to Christ.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem">
<HEAD>The Sweetness of Jesus.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 14.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IHesu, &thorn;i swetnes, who-so my&yogh;te it se,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erof haue a cleere knowynge,</L>
<L>Al er&thorn;eli loue bittir schulde be</L>
<L N="4">Saue &thorn;in a-loone without leesinge.</L>
<L>I praie &thorn;ee, lord, &thorn;at lore leere me,</L>
<L>Aftir &thorn;i loue to haue longynge,</L>
<L>And sadli to sette myn herte on &thorn;ee,</L>
<L N="8">In &thorn;i loue to haue most liking.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>So likinge loue in er&thorn;e noon is;</L>
<L>In soule who-so coude him so&thorn;eli se,</L>
<L>Him to loue were mykil blis,</L>
<L N="12">For king of loue callid is he.</L>
<L>&para; With true loue, y wolde &thorn;is,</L>
<L>So faste to him bounde be,</L>
<L>&THORN;at myne herte were holli his</L>
<L N="16">So &thorn;at no &thorn;ing likid me but he.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IF y for kyndenes schulde loue my kyn,<MILESTONE N="15" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;an me &thorn;enki&thorn; in my &thorn;ou&yogh;te</L>
<L>Bi kyndeli skile y schulde bigynne</L>
<L N="20">At him &thorn;at ha&thorn; me maade of nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; His lijknes he sette my soule with-inne,</L>
<L>And al &thorn;is world for me ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>As fadir he fondid my loue to wynne,</L>
<L N="24">For to heuene he ha&thorn; me brou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="9"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>As moder of him, y make now mynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;at bifore my bir&thorn;e to me toke hede,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en with baptym waischi&thorn; &thorn;at kynde</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;at foulide was &thorn;oru&yogh; adams dede.</L>
<L>&para; With noble mete he norischi&thorn; oure kynde,</L>
<L>For with his fleisch he doo&thorn; us fede,</L>
<L>A betere fode may no man fynde,</L>
<L N="32">To lastynge lijf it wole us lede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oure bro&thorn;er &amp; sustir he is bi skile,</L>
<L>For he so seide, &amp; lerid us &thorn;at lore</L>
<L>&THORN;at who so wrou&yogh;te his fadris wille</L>
<L N="36">Bri&thorn;eren &amp; sustren to him &thorn;ei wore.</L>
<L>&para; Mi kinde also he took &thorn;er-tille,<MILESTONE N="16" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Ful truli truste y him &thorn;erfore</L>
<L>&THORN;at he wole neuere lete me spille,</L>
<L N="40">But wi&thorn; his mercy salue my sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The loue of him passi&thorn;, certis,</L>
<L>Al er&thorn;eli loue &thorn;at may ben here;</L>
<L>God &amp; man, my spouse he is,</L>
<L N="44">Weel ou&yogh;te y, wrecche, to loue him dere.</L>
<L>&para; Bo&thorn;e heuen and er&thorn;e holli is his,</L>
<L>He is lord of greet powere,</L>
<L>Callid he is &thorn;e kyng of blis,</L>
<L N="48">His loue me longi&thorn; for to leere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aftir his loue me &thorn;enki&thorn; long</L>
<L>For he ha&thorn; myne ful dere y-bou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Whanne y was wente fro him with wrong,</L>
<L N="52">From heuen to er&thorn;e he me sou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; Mi wrecchid kynde for me he fonge,</L>
<L>And al his nobley he sette as nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Pouert he suffride, &amp; peynes stronge,</L>
<L N="56">A&yogh;en to blis or he me brou&yogh;te.
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="10"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne y was &thorn;ral, to make me fre,<MILESTONE N="17" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Mi loue fro heuene to er&thorn;e him ledde,</L>
<L>My loue aloone haue wolde he,</L>
<L N="60">For &thorn;erfore he leide his lijf to wedde.</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; my foo he fau&yogh;te for me,</L>
<L>Woundid he was, and bittirli bledde,</L>
<L>His preciouse blood ful greet plente</L>
<L N="64">Ful piteuouseli for me was schedde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hise sidis bloo and blodi were</L>
<L>&THORN;at sumtyme were ful bri&yogh;t of blee;</L>
<L>His herte was persid wi&thorn; a spere,</L>
<L N="68">Hise ruli woundis were ru&thorn;e to se.</L>
<L>&para; Mi raunsum forso&thorn;e he paied &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>And &yogh;af his lijf for gilt of me,</L>
<L>His dee&thorn; schulde be to me ful dere,</L>
<L N="72">And perse myn herte for pure pitee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For pitee myn herte schulde breke on two,</L>
<L>To his kyndenes if y took hede;</L>
<L>Encheson y was of al his woo,</L>
<L N="76">He suffride ful harde for my mis-dede.</L>
<L>&para; To lastyng lijf &thorn;at y schulde go,<MILESTONE N="18" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>He suffride dee&thorn; in his manhede;</L>
<L>And whanne his wille was to lyue also,</L>
<L N="80">A&yogh;en he roos &thorn;oru&yogh; his godhede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To heuen he wente with myche blis</L>
<L>Whanne he ouercome his bataile,</L>
<L>His baner ful brode displaied is</L>
<L N="84">Whanne so my fo wole me assaile.</L>
<L>&para; Weel ou&yogh;te y, wrecche, to ben his,</L>
<L>He is &thorn;at freend &thorn;at neuere wole faile:</L>
<L>No &thorn;ing desiri&thorn; he &thorn;at is,</L>
<L N="88">But true loue a&yogh;en for his trauaile.
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="11"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus wolde my spouse for me fi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And for me was woundid sore,</L>
<L>For my loue his dee&thorn; was di&yogh;t;</L>
<L N="92">What loue my&yogh;te he ki&thorn;e more?</L>
<L>&para; To &yogh;elde his loue haue y no my&yogh;te</L>
<L>But loue him hertili &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L>And worche weel with werkis ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;at he ha&thorn; lerid me with loueli lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; loueli lore his werkis to fille,<MILESTONE N="19" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Weel ou&yogh;te y, wrecche, if y were kynde,</L>
<L>Ny&yogh;t &amp; day to worche his wille,</L>
<L N="100">And euere haue &thorn;at lord in mynde.</L>
<L>&para; But goostli foos greuen me ille,</L>
<L>And my freel fleisch maki&thorn; me blinde;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore his mercy y take me tille,</L>
<L N="104">For betere bote can y noon fynde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Betere bote is noon to me</L>
<L>&THORN;an to his mercy truli me take</L>
<L>&THORN;at with his fleisch ha&thorn; made me free,</L>
<L N="108">And me, wrecche, his childe wole make.</L>
<L>&para; I praie &thorn;at lord for his pitee</L>
<L>&THORN;at he for synne me not forsake,</L>
<L>But &yogh;eue me grace fro synne to flee,</L>
<L N="112">And him to loue let me neuere slake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, for &thorn;e swetnes &thorn;at in &thorn;ee is,</L>
<L>Have mynde of me whan y hens wende,</L>
<L>With stidfast tru&thorn;e my wittis &thorn;ou wis,</L>
<L N="116">And, lord, &thorn;ou scheelde me from &thorn;e feende!</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;i mercy for&yogh;eue me my mys,<MILESTONE N="20" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;at wickid werk my soule neuere schende,</L>
<L>And lede me, lord, in-to &thorn;i blis,</L>
<L N="120">With &thorn;ee to wone withoute eende.</L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000030.tif" N="12">
<HEAD>Be my Coumfort, Crist Ihesus!</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1400 A.D., <I>page</I> 20.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IHesus &thorn;at sprong of iesse roote,</L>
<L>As us ha&thorn; prechid &thorn;i prophete,</L>
<L>Flour and fruyt bo&thorn;e softe and sote,</L>
<L N="4">To mannis soule of sauour sweete;</L>
<L>Ihesu! &thorn;ou brou&yogh;tist man to boote</L>
<L>Whanne gabriel gan marie greete,</L>
<L>To felle oure foomen vndir foote,</L>
<L N="8">In hir &thorn;ou si&yogh; a semeli sete:</L>
<L>&para; A mayden was &thorn;i modir meete,</L>
<L>Of whom &thorn;ou took fleisch for us;</L>
<L>As &yogh;e may bo&thorn;e my balis beete,</L>
<L N="12">So be my coumfort, crist ihesus.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;ou art wijsdom of witt</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i fadir ful of my&yogh;t!</L>
<L>Mannys soule, to saue it,</L>
<L N="16">In poore aparaile &thorn;ou were pi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; Ihesu! &thorn;ou were in cradil knyt,<MILESTONE N="21" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>In wede wrappid bo&thorn;e day &amp; ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In bethleem born, as &thorn;e gospel writt,</L>
<L N="20">With aungelis song and heuene li&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Barn y-born of a beerde bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ful curteis was &thorn;i comeli cus;</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; uertu of &thorn;at sweete si&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="24">So be my coumfort, crist ihesus.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at were of &yogh;eeris &yogh;ong,</L>
<L>Fair and sresch of hide and hue,
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="13"></L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;ou were in &thorn;raldom &thorn;rong,</L>
<L N="28">And turmentid with many a iewe,</L>
<L>&para; Whanne blood and watir were out wrong,</L>
<L>For beetinge was &thorn;i bodi blewe;</L>
<L>As a clot of clay &thorn;ou were for-clonge,</L>
<L N="32">So deed in &thorn;rou&yogh; &thorn;anne men &thorn;ee &thorn;rewe.</L>
<L>&para; But grace of &thorn;i graue grew;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou roos up quik coumfort to us.</L>
<L>For hir loue &thorn;at &thorn;is councel knewe,</L>
<L N="36">So be my coumfort, crist ihesus.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, soo&thorn;fast god and man,<MILESTONE N="22" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Two kindis knyt in oon persone,</L>
<L>&THORN;e wondir werk &thorn;at &thorn;ou bigan</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;ou hast fulfillid in fleisch &amp; bone.</L>
<L>&para; Out of &thorn;is world wi&yogh;tli &thorn;ou wan,</L>
<L>Liftynge up &thorn;i silf a-loone;</L>
<L>For my&yogh;tili &thorn;ou roos, &amp; ran</L>
<L N="44">Strei&yogh;t vnto &thorn;i fadir in trone.</L>
<L>&para; Now dare man make no more moone;</L>
<L>For man it is &thorn;ou wrou&yogh;te &thorn;us,</L>
<L>And god wi&thorn; man is maade at oone,</L>
<L N="48">So be my coumfort, crist ihesus.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu crist, holi and hende,</L>
<L>&THORN;at beerde was blessid &thorn;at bare &thorn;ee,</L>
<L>Aftir hir whanne &thorn;ou gan sende,</L>
<L N="52">In heuene blis wi&thorn; &thorn;ee to bee.</L>
<L>&para; Out of &thorn;is worlde whanne sche wende,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e bodi &amp; soule were sett in see</L>
<L>Hi&yogh;er &thorn;an ony of<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>of</I> in margin.</NOTE> aungelis kinde,</L>
<L N="56">In troone a-fore &thorn;e trynyte.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ere may &thorn;e sone his modir se<MILESTONE N="23" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>In heuene an hi&yogh; to helpen us;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou peerless princes, praie for me!</L>
<L N="60">And be my coumfort, crist ihesus.
<PB REF="00000032.tif" N="14"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, my souereyne sauyour,</L>
<L>Almy&yogh;ti god, &thorn;ere ben no moo:</L>
<L>Crist, &thorn;ou be my gouernour,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;i sei&thorn; lete me not fallen fro.</L>
<L>&para; Ihesu, my ioye and my socoure!</L>
<L>In my body and soule also,</L>
<L>God, &thorn;ou be my strengist fode,</L>
<L N="68">And wisse &thorn;ou me whan me is wo.</L>
<L>&para; Lord, &thorn;ou makist freend of foo,</L>
<L>Lete me not lyue in langour &thorn;us,</L>
<L>But se my sorowe, &amp; seie now 'ho,'</L>
<L N="72">And be my coumfort, crist ihesus.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, to &thorn;ee y crie and greede;</L>
<L>Prince of pees, to &thorn;ee y praye;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou woldist bleede for mannis nede,</L>
<L N="76">And suffre manye a feerdful fray.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou me fede in al my drede<MILESTONE N="24" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; pacience now and ay</L>
<L>Mi lijf to lede in word &amp; dede</L>
<L N="80">As is moost plesaunt to &thorn;i pay,</L>
<L>&para; And to deie weel whanne it is my day.</L>
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at deied on tree for us,</L>
<L>Lete me not be &thorn;e feendis pray,</L>
<L N="84">But be my coumfort, crist ihesus!<NOTE PLACE="end">[The two Hymns to the Virgin, "Heil be &thorn;ou, Marie," printed on pages 4-7 of this Text, follow here.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000033.tif" N="15">
<HEAD>Richard de Castre's Prayer to Jesus.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS</I>. 853, <I>ab</I>. 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 28, <I>written without breaks</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<HEAD>Oratio magistri Richardi de castre, quam ipse posuit.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IHesu, lord, &thorn;at madist me,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; &thorn;i blessid blood hast bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For&yogh;eue &thorn;at y haue greued &thorn;ee</L>
<L N="4">With worde, with wil, &amp; eek with &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu, in whom is al my trust,</L>
<L>&THORN;at deied upon &thorn;e roode tree,</L>
<L>Withdrawe myn herte from fleischli lust,</L>
<L N="8">And from al wordli vanyte!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu, for &thorn;i woundis smerte</L>
<L>On feet &amp; on &thorn;in hondis two,</L>
<L>Make me meeke &amp; low of herte,</L>
<L N="12">And &thorn;ee to loue as y schulde do!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu, for &thorn;i bitter wounde</L>
<L>&THORN;at wente to &thorn;in herte roote,</L>
<L>For synne &thorn;at ha&thorn; myn herte bounde,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;i blessid bloode mote be my bote.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And ihesu crist, to &thorn;ee y calle</L>
<L>&THORN;at art god ful of my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>Kepe me cleene, &thorn;at y ne falle</L>
<L N="20">In deedli synne nei&thorn;er be day ne ny&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="16"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu, graunte me myne askinge,</L>
<L>Perfite pacience in my disese,</L>
<L>And neuere mote y do &thorn;at &thorn;ing</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;at schulde &thorn;ee in ony wise displese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu, &thorn;at art oure heuenli king,</L>
<L>Soo&thorn;efast god, &amp; man also,</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue me grace of good eendinge,<MILESTONE N="29" UNIT="page"></L>
<L N="28">And hem &thorn;at Y am holden vnto.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu, for &thorn;e deedly teeris</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou scheeddist for my gilt,</L>
<L>Here &amp; spede my praiers,</L>
<L N="32">Aud spare me &thorn;at y be not spilt.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu, for them y &thorn;e biseche</L>
<L>&THORN;at wra&thorn;&thorn;en &thorn;ee in ony wise,</L>
<L>With-holde from hem &thorn;in hond of wreche,</L>
<L N="36">And lete hem lyue in &thorn;i seruice.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu, moost coumfort for to se</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i seintis euerychoone,</L>
<L>Coumfort hem &thorn;at careful been,</L>
<L N="40">And helpe hem &thorn;at ben woo bigoon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu, keepe hem &thorn;at been goode,</L>
<L>And ameende hem &thorn;at han greued &thorn;ee,</L>
<L>And sende hem fruytis of er&thorn;eli fode</L>
<L N="44">As ech man nedi&thorn; in his degree.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu, &thorn;at art with-outen lees</L>
<L>Almy&yogh;ti god in trynyte,</L>
<L>Ceesse &thorn;ese werris, &amp; sende us pees</L>
<L N="48">Wi&thorn; lastinge loue &amp; charitee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at art &thorn;e goostli stoon</L>
<L>Of al holi chirche in myddil er&thorn;e,
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="17"></L>
<L>Bringe &thorn;i fooldis &amp; flockis in oon,</L>
<L N="52">And rule hem ri&yogh;tli with oon hirde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu, for <MILESTONE N="30" UNIT="page">&thorn;i blessidful blood,</L>
<L>Bringe, if &thorn;ou wolt, &thorn;o soulis to blis</L>
<L>For<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? <I>for</I> Fro]</NOTE> whom y haue had ony good,</L>
<L N="56">And spare &thorn;at &thorn;ei han do a-mys.<NOTE PLACE="end">["Who-so wilne&thorn;," printed on pp. 11-12 of <I>The Babees Book</I>, &amp;c., follows here, on p. 30 of the MS.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>AMEN.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000036.tif" N="18">
<HEAD>Do Merci bifore thi Iugement.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 583, <I>ab.</I> 1340 A.D., <I>page</I> 54, <I>written without breaks</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>There is no creatour<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. 'creature,' but a later hand has written <I>our</I> over the <I>ure</I> of 'creature,' and dotted the <I>ure</I> out.</NOTE> but oon,</L>
<L>Maker of euery creature,</L>
<L>God a-loone, &amp; euer more oon,</L>
<L N="4">And &thorn;re in oon alway to endure.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;at lord we make oure moone</L>
<L>To whom al coumfort is, &amp; cure,</L>
<L>To &thorn;inke how freel we ben echoon.</L>
<L N="8">In &thorn;is world is hard auenture:</L>
<L>&para; Who-so &thorn;erof is moost ensure,</L>
<L>Sunnest schal he be schamed and schent.</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ou &thorn;e world with fier pure,</L>
<L N="12">Do merci bifore &thorn;i iugement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord, do mercy or &thorn;at &thorn;ou deeme,</L>
<L>Lest &thorn;ou dampne &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast wrou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>What ioie were it a feend to qweme,</L>
<L N="16">To &yogh;eue him &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast dere bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; Out of &thorn;i si&yogh;t if &thorn;ou us fleme,</L>
<L>We ben dampned ri&yogh;t as nou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;i passioun make us bri&yogh;t &amp; schene</L>
<L N="20">In wil, in worde, in dede &amp; &thorn;ou&yogh;t!
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="19"></L>
<L>&para; For whi, synne ha&thorn; us &thorn;oru&yogh; sou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-fore ameende &thorn;ou oure entent</L>
<L>To &thorn;e doom or we bee brou&yogh;t!</L>
<L N="24">Do mercy bifore &thorn;i iugement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>We axe &thorn;i mercy, &thorn;ou heuenli king,<MILESTONE N="55" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>For &thorn;ou art lord of ech degre;</L>
<L>Of er&thorn;e &thorn;ou madist oure bigynnynge,</L>
<L N="28">And aftir with spirit enspirid us free.</L>
<L>&para; Wi&thorn; trees and gras &thorn;ou &yogh;af us growinge,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; beestis, feelinge lijf haue we,</L>
<L>And with aungils we haue vndirstondinge,</L>
<L N="32">And &thorn;erbi we schulden know &thorn;ee.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou baddist &thorn;at alle schulde multiplie,</L>
<L>But we ben fals &amp; necligent:</L>
<L>For we may not hide us from &thorn;in i&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="36">Do merci bifore &thorn;i iugement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou baddist us axe merci, &amp; we schulden haue;</L>
<L>It doo&thorn; us coumfort on &thorn;ee to calle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou hast ordeined man to saue,</L>
<L N="40">For &thorn;i merci passi&thorn; &thorn;i werkis alle.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;i herte blood for us &thorn;ou &yogh;aue,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou madist us free where we were &thorn;ralle:</L>
<L>Lete neuere &thorn;e feend oure soulis craue</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at waischen was in &thorn;in holi welle!</L>
<L>&para; Oure fleisch is freel, it maki&thorn; us falle,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; grace<MILESTONE N="56" UNIT="page"> we risen &amp; schulen repente;</L>
<L>And in hope of &thorn;ee we schal:</L>
<L N="48">Haue merci to-fore thi iugement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>We axe mercy bi ri&yogh;twijsnes,</L>
<L>For &thorn;i biheest is al oure ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And of &thorn;i greet kindenes</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;ou hast mercy to us bihi&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>&para; We ne be but er&thorn;e watirlees,</L>
<L>&THORN;at to springe vertu ha&thorn; no my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;is worldis likerose bittirnes</L>
<L N="56">Bireue&thorn; us discrecioun &amp; oure si&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e feend, &thorn;e fleisch, &thorn;e worlde, wi&thorn; us ay fi&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;us be we taken in turment;</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore, lord, or &thorn;i doom be di&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="60">Do merci bifore &thorn;i iugement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wi&thorn; synne we han defoulid oure kinde,</L>
<L>And kinde may we not eschewe;</L>
<L>To wra&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;ee, god, we ben vnkinde;</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;ou kindeli king, we ben vntrewe!</L>
<L>&para; A&yogh;ens &thorn;is can no clerk skile fynde;</L>
<L>Graciose god, upon us rewe;</L>
<L>Take not oure trespase in to mynde,</L>
<L N="68">But in &thorn;i doom lete merci sue!<MILESTONE N="57" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;ou&yogh; we wolden from &thorn;ee remewe,</L>
<L>In ech place &thorn;ou art present;</L>
<L>Or we were born, lord, &thorn;ou us knewe;</L>
<L N="72">Do merci bifore &thorn;i iuggement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lord! oure soule, oure spirit, oure lijf,</L>
<L>Into &thorn;in hondis, lord, we bitake;</L>
<L>Out of temptacioun and strijf,</L>
<L N="76">Lord, kepe us whe&thorn;er we slepe or wake.</L>
<L>&para; Ihesu, for &thorn;i woundis fyue,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;i [blessid] modir sake,</L>
<L>&THORN;e feend away from us &thorn;ou dryue</L>
<L N="80">Whanne dee&thorn; with us maistrie schal make,</L>
<L>&para; And suffre him not oure soule away to take</L>
<L>For whiche on roode &thorn;ou were to-rent;</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;i doom we tremble &amp; quake;</L>
<L N="84">Do merci tofore &thorn;i iugement!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God, &thorn;ou deeme us ri&yogh;twijsli,</L>
<L>Medele &thorn;ou merci with execusioun,
<PB REF="00000039.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>For we han forfetid wrongfulli;</L>
<L N="88">Take hede to oure contricioun!</L>
<L>&para; We &yogh;eelde us synful &amp; sory</L>
<L>By <MILESTONE N="58" UNIT="page">Knowliche &amp; confessioun;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. confessoun.</NOTE></L>
<L>&THORN;i passioun &amp; &thorn;i mercy</L>
<L N="92">We take to oure entensioun.</L>
<L>&para; Bileeue is oure saluacioun,</L>
<L>With keping of &thorn;i comaundement.</L>
<L>God, putte &thorn;in holi passioun</L>
<L N="96">Bitwixe us &amp; &thorn;i iugement!<NOTE PLACE="end">["As y gan wandre," printed below, follows here.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>Amen.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000040.tif" N="22">
<HEAD>The Love of Jesus.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>(<I>Pages</I> 90-102, <I>written without breaks.</I>)</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOue is lijf &thorn;at lasti&thorn; ay</L>
<L>&THORN;ere it is in crist made fest,</L>
<L>Whanne wele ne wo it slake may,</L>
<L N="4">As writen han men wisest.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e ny&yogh;t it turne&thorn; in-to day,</L>
<L>Traueile it turne&thorn; in to rest:</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou wolt do as y &thorn;ee say,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;ou schalt &thorn;anne be with &thorn;e best.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Loue is a &thorn;ou&yogh;t with greet desijr,</L>
<L>And also of a fair loouynge;</L>
<L>Loue y likne in-to a fier</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at slakeen may for no &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>&para; Loue clensi&thorn; us of oure synne,</L>
<L>loue oure blis schal bringe,</L>
<L>Loue &thorn;e kingis herte may wynne,</L>
<L N="16">loue of ioie euere may synge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e socour of loue is liftid hie,</L>
<L>For into heuene it ran;</L>
<L>Me &thorn;enki&thorn; in herte &thorn;at it is sli&yogh;e,</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at maki&thorn; &thorn;e peple bo&thorn;e pale &amp; wan.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e beed of blis it goi&thorn; ful ny&yogh;e,&mdash;<MILESTONE N="91" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>I telle &yogh;ou it as y can,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;erof us &thorn;enki&thorn; &thorn;e wey to drie,</L>
<L N="24">For euere loue coupli&thorn; god to man.
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="23"></L>
<L>&para; Loue is hetter &thorn;an &thorn;e cole</L>
<L>To hem &thorn;at of it is fayn &amp; frike,</L>
<L>&THORN;e flawme of loue, who my&yogh;te it &thorn;ole,</L>
<L N="28">If it were euermore lijke:</L>
<L>&para; Loue us heli&thorn;, &amp; maki&thorn; in qwart,</L>
<L>And lifti&thorn; us up in-to heuene-riche,</L>
<L>And loue rauischi&thorn; crist in-to oure herte,</L>
<L N="32">I woot nowhere no loue it is lijke.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Leerne to loue if &thorn;ou wolt lyue</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;ou schalt hens fare;</L>
<L>Al &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t to him &thorn;ou &yogh;eue</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at may &thorn;ee kepe from care;</L>
<L>&para; Loke &thorn;ou &thorn;in herte fro him not twynne</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou wandre euery where,</L>
<L>So &thorn;ou may weelde him with-inne,</L>
<L N="40">And loue him hertili euermore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu, &thorn;at me loue hast lende,<MILESTONE N="92" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>In-to &thorn;i loue &thorn;ou me bringe,</L>
<L>Take to &thorn;ee al<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>al</I> in margin.</NOTE> myn entente</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at &thorn;ou be to me myn &yogh;erninge,</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;at synne from me awei were went,</L>
<L>And loue come myn owne coueitynge,</L>
<L>&THORN;at my soule hadde herd &amp; hent</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;e songe of &thorn;i sweete louynge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;i loue is to us euerelastynge</L>
<L>Fro &thorn;at tyme &thorn;at we may it verrili fele,</L>
<L>&THORN;erinne make we euere brennynge,</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at no &thorn;ing may it uerrili keele.</L>
<L>&para; Mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t, take it into &thorn;in hand,</L>
<L>And stable &thorn;ou it ilke a dele,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y be no &thorn;ing hildande</L>
<L N="56">To loue uerrili &thorn;e worldis wele.
<PB REF="00000042.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>&para; If y loue ony er&thorn;eli &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at paie&thorn; to my wille,</L>
<L>And sette my ioie in foule likinge,</L>
<L N="60">Whanne it may come me tylle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>I</B> may drede at my departynge<MILESTONE N="93" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;at it wole be attir &amp; ille,</L>
<L>For alle my wel&thorn;is ben wepinge</L>
<L N="64">whanne peyne my soule wolde spille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e ioie &thorn;at men heere seen</L>
<L>Is ful likinge vnto &thorn;e i&yogh;ee;</L>
<L>&THORN;at now is fair, freische, and grene,</L>
<L N="68">And anoon aftir is welkid awey:</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is is &thorn;e world, alle men moun seen,</L>
<L>And wole be vnto domysday,</L>
<L>Ful greet traueile, &amp; myche tene;</L>
<L N="72">To flee &thorn;at is ful hard in fay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; If &thorn;ou leue yuel in al &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And hate &thorn;e filthe of synne,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue to him &thorn;at &thorn;ee dere bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at he weelde &thorn;ee with-inne,</L>
<L>&para; Al &thorn;i soule &thorn;i lord ha&thorn; sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erof he wolde not mynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;us schalt &thorn;ou to blis be brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="80">And wonye heuene wi&thorn;-ynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For-<MILESTONE N="94" UNIT="page">so&thorn;e &thorn;e kinde of loue is &thorn;is,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere it is trusty and trewe,&mdash;</L>
<L>To stoonde euere in stabilnes,</L>
<L N="84">And chaunge neuere for no newe.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at wi&yogh;t &thorn;at &thorn;at loue may finde,</L>
<L>Or euere in herte it knewe,</L>
<L>Fro care it turne&thorn; &thorn;at kinde:</L>
<L N="88">Such a mir&thorn;e fyndi&thorn; to fewe.
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="25"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For-&thorn;i, loue &thorn;ou as y &thorn;ee rede;</L>
<L>Crist is trewe loue, as y &thorn;e telle;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; aungilis take &thorn;ou &thorn;i stide;</L>
<L N="92">&THORN;at ioie loke &thorn;ou not felle.</L>
<L>&para; In er&thorn;e hate<NOTE PLACE="foot">? <I>loue</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;ou no maner qweed,</L>
<L>But loke &thorn;at &thorn;i loue may dwelle,</L>
<L>For loue is more strenger &thorn;an deed,</L>
<L N="96">Loue is more harder &thorn;an helle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Loue is li&yogh;t, &amp; a bir&thorn;un fyne;</L>
<L>Loue gladi&thorn; bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge and oolde;</L>
<L>Loue is wi&thorn;out ony pyne,</L>
<L N="100">As louers han me toolde.</L>
<L>&para; Loue is goostli deli-<MILESTONE N="95" UNIT="page"> ciouse as wijn</L>
<L>&THORN;at maki&thorn; men bo&thorn;e big &amp; bolde;</L>
<L>To &thorn;at loue y schal me so faste tyne,</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at y in herte it<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>it</I> in margin.</NOTE> euermore holde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Loue is &thorn;e swettiste &thorn;ing</L>
<L>&THORN;at heere in er&thorn;e men may han;</L>
<L>Loue is goddis owne derlinge;</L>
<L N="108">Loue byndi&thorn; bo&thorn;e blood &amp; baan.</L>
<L>&para; In loue, &thorn;erfore, be oure likinge;</L>
<L>I knowe no betere won;</L>
<L>For me oonli, &amp; my louynge,</L>
<L N="112">Loue maki&thorn; bo&thorn;e but oon.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; But al fleischli loue schal fare</L>
<L>As doo&thorn; &thorn;e flouris of may,</L>
<L>And schal be lastande na mare</L>
<L N="116">But as it were an hour of a day;</L>
<L>&para; And sorewen aftir &thorn;at ful sare</L>
<L>Hir lust, her pride, &amp; al her play,</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;ei aren cast in care,</L>
<L N="120">In-to pyne &thorn;at lasti&thorn; ay.
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="26"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whanne her bodies in &thorn;e fen liggen,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne schulen her soulis be in drede,<MILESTONE N="96" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And up a&yogh;en as men schulen risen,</L>
<L N="124">And answere for her mys dede.</L>
<L>&para; If &thorn;ei be seen &thorn;an in synne,</L>
<L>And now heere &thorn;er liif &thorn;ei ledde,</L>
<L>&THORN;an schulen &thorn;ei ligge helle wi&thorn;-inne,</L>
<L N="128">And derkenes haue to mede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Riche men her hondis schal wrynge,</L>
<L>And her wickid werkes abie</L>
<L>In flawmes of fier bitterli brennynge,</L>
<L N="132">Wi&thorn; care and sorewe schamefastli.</L>
<L>&para; If &thorn;ou wolt loue, &thorn;an may &thorn;ou synge</L>
<L>To &thorn;i lord crist in melodie:</L>
<L>&THORN;e loue of him ouercome&thorn; al &thorn;ing;</L>
<L N="136">In loue lyue we &amp; die.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu! god-is sone &thorn;ou art,</L>
<L>lord of moost hi&yogh; magiste,</L>
<L>Sende verrili loue in-to myn herte</L>
<L N="140">Oonly <MILESTONE N="97" UNIT="page">to coueite &thorn;ee!</L>
<L>&para; Reue me likinge of &thorn;is world,</L>
<L>Mi loue &thorn;at &thorn;ou may be;</L>
<L>Take myn herte in-to &thorn;i ward,</L>
<L N="144">And sette &thorn;ou me in stabilte!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu! &thorn;ou, &thorn;e maidens sone,</L>
<L>&THORN;at with &thorn;i blood me bou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;irle my soule with &thorn;i spere anoon,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;at myche loue in men hast wrou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; Me longi&thorn; &thorn;ou lede me into &thorn;i si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And fastne &thorn;ere in &thorn;ee my &thorn;ou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>In &thorn;i swetnes make myn herte li&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;at al my woo wexe to nou&yogh;t.
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="27"></L>
<L>&para; Ihesu, my god &amp; my loueli king!</L>
<L>Forsake &thorn;ou not my desijr;</L>
<L>Mi &thorn;ou&yogh;t make to be meekinge;</L>
<L N="156">I hate bo&thorn;e pride &amp; ire.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;i wil is al my desirynge;</L>
<L>Of loue kyndele &thorn;ou &thorn;e fier,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y with &thorn;i sweete louynge</L>
<L N="160">Wi&thorn; aungils take myn hire.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wounde &thorn;ou myn herte wi&thorn;-inne,</L>
<L>And weelde me at &thorn;i wille;</L>
<L>Of blis &thorn;at neuere schal blynne,</L>
<L N="164">&THORN;ou fastne me &thorn;at y not spille.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at y &thorn;i loue may wynne,<MILESTONE N="98" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Of grace my &thorn;ou&yogh;t &thorn;ou fille,</L>
<L>And make me cleene of synne</L>
<L N="168">&THORN;at y may come &thorn;ee tille.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu! putte in-to myn herte</L>
<L>&THORN;e memorie of &thorn;i pyne!</L>
<L>In sijknes,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. lijknes.</NOTE> and eek in qwarte,</L>
<L N="172">&THORN;i loue be euere myne!</L>
<L>Mi ioie is al of &thorn;ee;</L>
<L>My soule, take it as &thorn;ine;</L>
<L>Mi loue euere wexinge be,</L>
<L N="176">So &thorn;at y neuere dwynne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; My loue is euere in si&yogh;inge</L>
<L>While y dwelle in &thorn;is way;</L>
<L>Mi loue is in &thorn;ee longynge,</L>
<L N="180">&THORN;at bindi&thorn; me ni&yogh;t &amp; day</L>
<L>&para; Tille y come vnto my king,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere y wone with him may,</L>
<L>And se his fair schynynge</L>
<L N="184">In lijf &thorn;at lasti&thorn; ay.
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="28"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Longinge is in me so lent</L>
<L>For loue, &thorn;at y ne can lete;</L>
<L>His loue he ha&thorn; me now sent</L>
<L N="188">&THORN;at euery bale may bete;</L>
<L>&para; Si&thorn;en &thorn;at myn herte was brent</L>
<L>In cristis loue so sweete,</L>
<L>Al woo fro me awei is went</L>
<L N="192">And we neuere a&yogh;en schulen mete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I sitte and synge of loue longynge</L>
<L>&THORN;at in my<MILESTONE N="99" UNIT="page"> brest is now bred.</L>
<L>Ihesu, my king and my ioiynge!</L>
<L N="196">Whi ne were y to &thorn;ee led?</L>
<L>&para; Ful weel y woot in al my &yogh;ernynge,</L>
<L>In al ioie, y schulde be fed.</L>
<L>Ihesu! me brynge to &thorn;i woniynge,</L>
<L N="200">For &thorn;e blood &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast bleed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Demed he was on a crosse to heng,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fair aungelis foode;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; scourgis &thorn;ei gan him sore swing</L>
<L N="204">Whanne &thorn;at he bounden stoode;</L>
<L>&para; His brist was bloo in betyng,</L>
<L>Not spilt was his blood;</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;orn crowned &thorn;at king</L>
<L N="208">&THORN;at doon was on &thorn;e roode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>White was his nakid breest,</L>
<L>&amp; reed his bloodi side,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[See <I>Political R. and L. Poems</I>, p. 214.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wan was his face fairest,</L>
<L N="212">Hise woundis depe &amp; wide.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e iewis wolde not &thorn;an reste</L>
<L>To pyne him more in &thorn;at tide;</L>
<L>Al he suffride &thorn;at was wisest,</L>
<L N="216">His blood to lete doun glide.
<PB REF="00000047.tif" N="29"></L>
<L>&para; Blyndid were hise faire y&yogh;en,</L>
<L>And al his fleisch bloodi for-bete;</L>
<L>Hise <MILESTONE N="100" UNIT="page">louesum lijf &thorn;at alle men si&yogh;e[n],</L>
<L N="220">Ful myldeli he out gan lete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Deed &amp; lijf bigunne to striuen</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er my&yogh;t be maister &thorn;ere;</L>
<L>Liif was slayn, &amp; roos a-&yogh;en;</L>
<L N="224">In-to blis ful fair may we fare.</L>
<L>&para; He &thorn;at &thorn;ee bou&yogh;t haue al &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And lede he it in to his loore;</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue al &thorn;in herte to crist in qwarte,</L>
<L N="228">And so to loue him euermore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I si&yogh;e, y sobbe, bo&thorn;e day &amp; ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>For oon &thorn;at is so fair of hue;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere is no &thorn;ing myn herte may li&yogh;t</L>
<L N="232">But his loue &thorn;at is so true.</L>
<L>&para; Who so hadde him in his si&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Or in his herte him knewe,</L>
<L>His moornynge schulde turne into ioie bri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="236">His longynge into glewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In mir&thorn;e lyue&thorn; he ny&yogh;t &amp; day</L>
<L>&THORN;at loue&thorn; &thorn;at sweete childe;</L>
<L>Wra&thorn;&thorn;e wolde from him awey,</L>
<L N="240">Were he neuere so wielde.</L>
<L>&para; It is ihesu, forso&thorn;e to say,<MILESTONE N="101" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Of alle meekist &amp; myelde;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at in herte him loue&thorn; &thorn;at day,</L>
<L N="244">From yuel he wole him schielde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of ihesu &THORN;anne moost list me speke,</L>
<L>&THORN;at may of al my bale be bote;</L>
<L>Me &thorn;inke&thorn; myn herte wole al to-breke</L>
<L N="248">Whanne y &thorn;inke on &thorn;at soote.
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="30"></L>
<L>&para; In loue lau&yogh;t he ha&thorn; my &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at y schal neuere for-lete;</L>
<L>Ful dere me &thorn;inke&thorn; he ha&thorn; me bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="252">Wi&thorn; bloodi heed, hondis, &amp; feete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For loue myn herte wole to-berste</L>
<L>Whanne y &thorn;at fair loue biholde;</L>
<L>Loue is ful fair &thorn;ere it is fest,</L>
<L N="256">&THORN;at neuere wole be coolde.</L>
<L>&para; Loue us reue&thorn; &thorn;e ny&yogh;tis rest;</L>
<L>In grace it maki&thorn; us boolde;</L>
<L>Of alle werkis loue is &thorn;e beeste,</L>
<L N="260">As holi men me ha&thorn; tolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; No wondir if y si&yogh;hande be,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en in woo al bi-sett;</L>
<L>Ihesu was nailid upon &thorn;e tree;</L>
<L N="264">&YOGH;he, al bloody for-beet.</L>
<L>&para; To &thorn;inke on him is greet pitee,</L>
<L>To se how tenderli he gret;</L>
<L>&THORN;is ha&thorn; he suffride, man, for &thorn;ee,<MILESTONE N="102" UNIT="page"></L>
<L N="268">If &thorn;at &thorn;ou wolt &thorn;i synnes leett.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ere is no lijf in er&thorn;e may telle</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is loue &thorn;e swetnes:</L>
<L>&THORN;at stidefastli in loue can dwelle,</L>
<L N="272">His ioie is euere eendelees.</L>
<L>&para; God schielde &thorn;at he schulde to helle,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of loue longinge kan not ceesse,</L>
<L>Or euere hise enemyes schulde him qwelle,</L>
<L N="276">Or &thorn;at he so his loue schulde lese.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu is &thorn;e loue &thorn;at lasti&thorn; ay,</L>
<L>To him is oure longinge.</L>
<L>Ihesu &thorn;e ny&yogh;t turne&thorn; to day,</L>
<L N="280">And derknes in-to day spryng.
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="31"></L>
<L>&para; Ihesu! &thorn;inke on us now and ay,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ee we holde oure kyng!</L>
<L>Ihesu, &yogh;eue us grace &thorn;at weel may,</L>
<L N="284">To loue &thorn;e with oute eendynge!&mdash;<NOTE PLACE="end">["The good wijf," printed in <I>The Babees Book</I>, &amp;c., follows.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>A-M-E-N.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000050.tif" N="32">
<HEAD>Se what oure Lord Suffride for oure Sake.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Pages</I> 117-120, <I>written without breaks.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BOthe &yogh;onge &amp; oolde, whe&thorn;ir &yogh;e be,</L>
<L>in cristis name good cheer &yogh;e make,</L>
<L>and lifti&thorn; up &yogh;oure hertis, &amp; se</L>
<L N="4">What oure lord suffride for oure sake.</L>
<L>as meeke as ony lombe was he,</L>
<L>ensaumple of him weel mowe we take,</L>
<L>&amp; to suffre also in oure degre,</L>
<L N="8">&amp; in his seruice euere to wake.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And if oure freendis forsake us heere</L>
<L>so &thorn;at we be left al aloone,</L>
<L>&THORN;inke on ihesus &thorn;at bou&yogh;t us dere,</L>
<L N="12">&amp; to him make we al oure moone;</L>
<L>&para; For of &thorn;at lord weel may we leere</L>
<L>What wrong he suffride among hise foon;</L>
<L>Whanne hise disciplis fledden for feer,</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;er bood no mo but marie &amp; iohne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>If ony wrong to us be wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Be it in word ei&thorn;er in dede,</L>
<L>Be of good hope &yogh;it in &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="20">How god may us helpe alle at neede,<MILESTONE N="118" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And &thorn;inke we how ihesus crist us bou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&amp; for oure synnis hise blood wolde blede;</L>
<L>for his owne gilt was it nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="24">for he dide neuere synful dede.
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="33"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; If wickid men do us defame,</L>
<L>&thorn;inke how crist was bou&yogh;t &amp; solde;</L>
<L>to suffre for him is no schame,</L>
<L N="28">but him to serue loke we be boold.</L>
<L>And if men hurte us in oure name,</L>
<L>We must for&yogh;eue, bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge &amp; olde,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou&yogh; we suffre myche blame,</L>
<L N="32">crist suffride moore a &thorn;ousand foold.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And of pouert &thorn;ou&yogh; we wolde playne,</L>
<L>for &thorn;at we wanten worldli good,</L>
<L>&THORN;inke we on ihesu, &thorn;at lord souereyn,</L>
<L N="36">how pore he heng upon &thorn;e roode,</L>
<L>&para; And how he stryued not ageyn,</L>
<L>but euere was meeke &amp; mylde of mood.</L>
<L>to folewe &thorn;at lord we schulden be fayn,</L>
<L N="40">in what degre &thorn;at euere we stood.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&amp; &thorn;ou&yogh; we haue sorowe on ech side,</L>
<L>&amp; al aboute wrong &amp; woo,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it suffre meekeli, &amp; a-bide,</L>
<L N="44">And &thorn;inke on ihesu &thorn;at suffride also,<MILESTONE N="119" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>and how he was in ful greet drede,</L>
<L>Vnto hise peynis whanne he schulde go;</L>
<L>he suffride moore in hise manhede</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;an euere dide man, or euere schal do.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ou&yogh; we with wrong to dee&thorn; be brou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&yogh;it suffraunce is a sikir way</L>
<L>For &thorn;e loue of ihesu &thorn;at us dere bou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="52">&amp; deide for us on good friday;</L>
<L>Wherfore us &thorn;inki&thorn; in oure &thorn;ou&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at we oure lord schulde please &amp; pay,</L>
<L>And we to sette &thorn;is world at nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="56">And suffre we wickid men to say.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In ihesu crist was meekenes moost,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore he &thorn;e maistrie hadde,
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="34"></L>
<L>And boond &thorn;e feend for al his boost</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at he was neuere so sore adradde.</L>
<L>&para; Al a&yogh;ens his wil &amp; al his oost</L>
<L>Adam &amp; eue with him he ladde,</L>
<L>And many moo out of &thorn;at coost</L>
<L N="64">&thorn;at weren in prisoun ful hard bistadde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And if &thorn;ou in ihesu haue delite,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; al &thorn;e world do &thorn;ee assaile,</L>
<L>Do aftir &thorn;is, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt wite</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;at meekenes <MILESTONE N="120" UNIT="page">Wole &thorn;ee moost availe;</L>
<L>For who &thorn;at suffri&thorn; heere dispite,</L>
<L>And meekeli a-bidi&thorn; in &thorn;at bataile,</L>
<L>it wole turne hem to greet profite</L>
<L N="72">&amp; eendlees ioie for her trauaile.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; If ony man do to us a mys,</L>
<L>Or wole in ony wise to us offende,</L>
<L>for &thorn;e loue of ihesu haue mynde on &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="76">&amp; lete meekenes &thorn;i mood ameende</L>
<L>wi&thorn; ihesu crist, as oon of his,</L>
<L>And suffre meekeli what god wole sende,</L>
<L>&thorn;anne schal we be with him in blis</L>
<L N="80">&thorn;at euereschal laste wi&thorn;outen eende.<NOTE PLACE="end">["How mankinde doo&thorn; bigynne," pp. 58-78 of this Text, follows here.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>A-M-E-N.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000053.tif" N="35">
<HEAD>I wiyte my silf myn owne Woo.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS</I>. 853, <I>ab</I>. 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 226-33.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>I</I> goes to line 7.</NOTE>IN my &yogh;onge age ful wielde y was,</L>
<L>Mi silf &thorn;at tyme cowde y not knowe,</L>
<L>Y wolde haue my wil in euery place,</L>
<L N="4">And &thorn;at ha&thorn; now brou&yogh;t me ful lowe.</L>
<L>&THORN;inke, ihesu, how y am &thorn;in owe!</L>
<L>For me weere &thorn;i sidis bo&thorn;e pale &amp; bloo!</L>
<L>To chastise me &thorn;ou doist it, y trowe;</L>
<L N="8">Y wiyte my silf myne owne woo!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I made couenaunt, true to be,</L>
<L>Firste whanne y baptisid was;</L>
<L>Y took to &thorn;e world, &amp; wente from &thorn;ee,</L>
<L N="12">Y folewide &thorn;e feend al in his traas;</L>
<L>From wra&thorn;&thorn;e and enuye wolde y not pas;</L>
<L>Coueitise and auarise y usid also,</L>
<L>My fleische hadde his wille, alas!</L>
<L N="16">Y wiyte my silf myn owne woo!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now y woot y was ful wielde,</L>
<L>In &thorn;at my wil passid my witt;</L>
<L>Y was ful sturdy, &amp; &thorn;ou ful myelde;</L>
<L N="20">Ihesu, lord, y knowe weel it.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;i blis y were ful qwytt<MILESTONE N="227" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>If y hadde aftir &thorn;at y haue do;</L>
<L>But to &thorn;i merci y truste &yogh;itt,</L>
<L N="24">Y wiyte my silf myn owne woo!
<PB REF="00000054.tif" N="36"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I was hi&yogh; of herte and stowte,</L>
<L>And in my clo&thorn;ing wondre gay;</L>
<L>I lokide men schulde vn-to me lowte</L>
<L N="28">Where-so &thorn;at y wente bi &thorn;e wey.</L>
<L>Faire wommen, and good aray,</L>
<L>Al myn entent y took &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L>A&yogh;en &thorn;i techinge euere y seide nay;</L>
<L N="32">I wite my silf myn owne woo!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I trustide more to worldli good</L>
<L>&THORN;an to god &thorn;at it me sente;</L>
<L>Weel&thorn;e made me hi&yogh; of mood;</L>
<L N="36">Lust and likyng me ouer wente.</L>
<L>To gete good y wolde not stente,</L>
<L>Y ne rou&yogh;te how y come &thorn;er-to;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e poore y nei&thorn;er &yogh;af ne lente;</L>
<L N="40">Y wiyte my silf myn owne woo!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lord, y hadde no drede of &thorn;ee;<MILESTONE N="228" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Mi grace wente away &thorn;erfore;</L>
<L>But, lord, as &thorn;ou bou&yogh;tist me,</L>
<L N="44">So lete me neuere be for-lore.</L>
<L>For me &thorn;ou suffredist peines sore;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art my freend, and y &thorn;i foo;</L>
<L>Mercy, lord! y wole no more;</L>
<L N="48">Y wiyte my silf myn owne woo!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;er ben .iij. poyntis of myscheef</L>
<L>&THORN;at ben confusioun to many a man,</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at worchen to her soulis greet greef;</L>
<L N="52">Y schal hem rehersen as y can.</L>
<L>Poore men proud, &thorn;at litil han,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei wolen be a-raied as riche men goo;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei hindren hem silf &amp; o&thorn;ir &thorn;an,</L>
<L N="56">And mowe wiyte hem silf her owne woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; A riche man, &thorn;eef, is anothir,</L>
<L>&THORN;at of coueitise wole not slake;
<PB REF="00000055.tif" N="37"></L>
<L>If he with wrong bigile his bro&thorn;ir,</L>
<L N="60">Heuene blis he schal forsake;</L>
<L>Bifore god, for &thorn;eefte it is take,<MILESTONE N="229" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Al &thorn;at with wrong he wynne&thorn; so;</L>
<L>But if he here a-meendis make<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. <I>made</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="64">he schal wiyte him silf his owne woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; An oolde men lecchour, &thorn;e &thorn;ridde it is,</L>
<L>For his complexioun wexi&thorn; coolde;</L>
<L>It bringe&thorn; &thorn;e soule to peyne from blis,</L>
<L N="68">It stincke&thorn; on god so manye foolde.</L>
<L>Theise .iij. &thorn;at y haue of toold</L>
<L>Ben pleasinge to &thorn;e feend oure foo;</L>
<L>Hem to use, who is so boold,</L>
<L N="72">May wiyte him silf his owne woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Manye defautis god may fynde</L>
<L>In vs &thorn;at schulde hise seruauntis be;</L>
<L>He schewith us loue, &amp; we vnkinde,</L>
<L N="76">Certis &thorn;e more to blame be wee.</L>
<L>Summe staren broode &amp; moun not se,</L>
<L>Synne is &thorn;e cause it fari&thorn; soo;</L>
<L>Suche dreden not god, y seie to &thorn;ee,</L>
<L N="80">And may wiyte hem silf her owne woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In .iij. &thorn;ingis y dare weel sayn<MILESTONE N="230" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>god schulde be worschipide ouer al &thorn;ing;</L>
<L>do ri&yogh;twijsnes with merci with al &thorn;i mayn;</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;e &thorn;ridde is cleennesse in lyuynge:</L>
<L>To bischopis &amp; curatis &thorn;at han kepinge,</L>
<L>it is her charge, &amp; to lordis also.</L>
<L>and if &thorn;ei contrarie god-is biddinge,</L>
<L N="88">&thorn;ei may wiyte hem silf her owne woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; wrong is an hi&yogh; seete &thorn;ere ri&yogh;t schulde be,</L>
<L>merci for mys deede is putt away;
<PB REF="00000056.tif" N="38"></L>
<L>letcherie ha&thorn; made clennesse to flee,</L>
<L N="92">Loue may not abide nyght ne day.</L>
<L>&THORN;us &thorn;e feend, y dare weel say,</L>
<L>wole make oure freend oure moost foo:</L>
<L>man, amende &thorn;ee whilis &thorn;ou may,</L>
<L N="96">Or wiyte &thorn;i silf &thorn;in owne woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; It is no wondir &thorn;ou&yogh; y be woo</L>
<L>myn owne wil while y wole sewe,</L>
<L>&amp; my lordis bidding wole not doo:</L>
<L N="100">y am ful fals, but he is trewe,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it he fyndi&thorn; me with al &thorn;ing newe,<MILESTONE N="231" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And y serue &thorn;e feend, and go him froo;</L>
<L>But if y amende, it schal me rewe,</L>
<L N="104">And may wiyte my silf myn owne woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In &thorn;re degrees &thorn;e world kept is,</L>
<L>With preestis, kny&yogh;tis, and laborere,</L>
<L>And which of hem &thorn;at doon amys,</L>
<L N="108">&THORN;ei schulen it abie wondir deer.</L>
<L>Bi good ensaumplis &thorn;e preestis schuld lere</L>
<L>&THORN;e vnleerned how &thorn;ei schulden doo:</L>
<L>If her word &amp; werk coorde not in fere;</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;ei mowe wite hem silf her owne woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Kny&yogh;thode also, lordis, ne o&thorn;ir,</L>
<L>Schulden not be of conscience light,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei schulden helpe her poore suster or bro&thorn;er,</L>
<L N="116">And also streng&thorn;e hem in her ryght</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; pride &amp; coueitise summe leesen her my&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For letcherie, grace is kept hem froo;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ei biholde her owne in-syght,</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;ei mowe wiyte hem silf her owne woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e laborer schulde truly traueile &thorn;an,<MILESTONE N="232" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And be ri&yogh;tful bo&thorn;e in worde &amp; deede,
<PB REF="00000057.tif" N="39"></L>
<L>And what-euere werkis &thorn;at he can,</L>
<L N="124">And resonabli to take his meede.</L>
<L>Wrongfulli summe her lijf heere lede</L>
<L>Among leerned &amp; lewde it is founde so,</L>
<L>And in her laste eende it is to drede</L>
<L N="128">&thorn;ei mowe wiyte hem silf her owne wo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Man, take hede what &thorn;ou art:</L>
<L>But wormes meete! &thorn;ou woost weel &thorn;is;</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;at &thorn;e er&thorn;e ha&thorn; take his part,</L>
<L N="132">Heuene and helle schal haue his.</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou doist weel, &thorn;ou goist to blis;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou do yuel, &thorn;ou goost to &thorn;i foo;</L>
<L>Loue &thorn;i lord god, &amp; &thorn;inke on &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="136">Or &thorn;ou wite &thorn;i silf &thorn;in owne woo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now ihesu crist, oure sauyour:</L>
<L>From oure foos &thorn;ou vs defende;</L>
<L>In al oure nede be oure socour,</L>
<L N="140">Heere &amp; whanne we hens wende,</L>
<L>And sende us grace so to amende,<MILESTONE N="233" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>His blisse &thorn;at we may come vnto,</L>
<L>Heere to make so good an eende</L>
<L N="144">&THORN;at wee not cause oure owne woo.</L>
<L>Deo gracias.<NOTE PLACE="end">[End of the MS. In a later hand is "This is sir Hary myndes booke, Record<NOTE PLACE="foot">May be <I>Recevd.</I></NOTE> of John Dauis, &amp; of sir John George &amp; of Sir Robert george fines"(?).]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000058.tif" N="40">
<HEAD>The Virtues of the Name Jesus.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IF &thorn;ou wole be weel with god, And haue grace<MILESTONE N="88" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>to reule &thorn;i lijf, And come to &thorn;e ioie of loue, &THORN;is name</L>
<L>ihesu, fastne it so fast in &thorn;in herte &THORN;at it come neuere</L>
<L N="4">out of &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t. And whanne &thorn;ou spekist to him,</L>
<L>&amp; seist ihesu &thorn;oru&yogh; custum, It schal be in &thorn;in eere</L>
<L>ioie, And in &thorn;i mou&thorn; hony, And in &thorn;in herte melo|</L>
<L>die, For &thorn;ou schalt &thorn;inke ioie to heere &thorn;e name of</L>
<L N="8">ihesu be nempned<NOTE PLACE="foot">There is a curl of contraction as for <I>er</I> over the second <I>c.</I></NOTE>,<MILESTONE N="89" UNIT="page"> swetnes to speke it, Myir&thorn;e &amp;</L>
<L>song to &thorn;inke on it. If &thorn;ou &thorn;inke on ihesu con|</L>
<L>tynueli, And holde it stabli, It purgi&thorn; &thorn;i synne, it</L>
<L>kyndeli&thorn; &thorn;in herte, It clarifie&thorn; &thorn;i soule, It remeue&thorn;</L>
<L N="12">anger, it doi&thorn; a-way slownes, It wyndi&thorn; in loue</L>
<L>fulfillid of charite, It chasi&thorn; &thorn;e deuel, it putti&thorn;</L>
<L>out drede, It opene&thorn; heuene, it maki&thorn; contemplatijf</L>
<L>men haue in mynde ofte ihesu, For alle vicis &amp;</L>
<L N="16">fantums it putti&thorn; fro &thorn;e louer. Also &thorn;erto heile ofte</L>
<L>marie bo&thorn;e day &amp; ny&yogh;t, And &thorn;anne myche ioie &amp;</L>
<L>loue schalt &thorn;ou fele. And &thorn;ou do aftir &thorn;is lore, &THORN;e</L>
<L>needi&thorn; not greetli coueite many bookis. Holde loue</L>
<L N="20">in herte &amp; in werk, And &thorn;ou hast al &thorn;at we may</L>
<L>seie or write, For fulnes of lawe is charite: In &thorn;at</L>
<L>hongi&thorn; al.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000059.tif" N="41">
<HEAD>A Song Called &THORN;e Deuelis Perlament, OR Parlamentum of Feendis.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>(<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>Pages</I> 157-182.)</P></HEADNOTE>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="fit">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whanne marye was greet with gabriel,</L>
<L>And had conceyued &amp; boren a childe,</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e deuelis of &thorn;e eir, of er&thorn;e, &amp; of helle,</L>
<L N="4">helden &thorn;er paralament of &thorn;at maide mylde,</L>
<L>&para; What man had made her wombe to swelle.</L>
<L>"To tempten hir &yogh;e tenden to seelde;</L>
<L>her childis fadir who can telle,</L>
<L N="8">Who dide with hir &thorn;o werkis wielde?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In helle &thorn;e feendis &thorn;oo answeride,</L>
<L>"We knew neuere fadir &thorn;at he hadde,</L>
<L>But amongis prophetis we haue leerid</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at god with man ha&thorn; couenaunt maade:</L>
<L>&para; A serpent in deseert was rerid,</L>
<L>So schal god-is sone in man be had,</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule of him schal be vnsperid,</L>
<L N="16">his herte to-cloue, and he for-bleed.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ese prophetis speken so in myst,<MILESTONE N="158" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>What &thorn;ei mente we neuere knewe;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei spoken of oon schulde hote crist,</L>
<L N="20">But maries sone hi&yogh;te ihesu;
<PB REF="00000060.tif" N="42"></L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ei seiden &thorn;at crist with god schulde be a-twist,</L>
<L>But &thorn;is ihesu neuere in &thorn;e godhede grew;</L>
<L>We ben bigilid alle wi&thorn; oure lyst.</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;e cloo&thorn; is al of anothir hew;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And &thorn;ou&yogh; god make hise perlament</L>
<L>Of pees, mercy, trouthe, &amp; resoun,</L>
<L>And from heuen til er&thorn;e his sone be sent</L>
<L N="28">In mankinde to take a cesoun,</L>
<L>&para; We schulen ordeyne bi oon assent</L>
<L>A priuey councell al of tresoun,</L>
<L>And clayme ihesu for oure rent.</L>
<L N="32">For &thorn;at he is kinde of man, it is good chesoun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Write we his name, whe&thorn;er we spede,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en to us he is vnknowen,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou&yogh; he be come of straunge seed,</L>
<L N="36">&YOGH;it in adams grounde was he sowen.</L>
<L>&para; Whanne he is ripe, do we oure dede;<MILESTONE N="159" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Loke we &thorn;at we him bo&thorn;e repe &amp; mowen,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ou&yogh; god him silf oure rollis rede,</L>
<L N="40">Bi ri&yogh;t we chalenge ihesu for oure owne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"To me, maistir deuel, it lijs;</L>
<L>To ihesu wole y take hede,</L>
<L>To norische him in manye delijs,</L>
<L N="44">His freel fleische bo&thorn;e to clo&thorn;e &amp; fede;</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;at he be neuere so wijs,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it out of &thorn;e wey y wole him lede,</L>
<L>And make of him bo&thorn;e fool and nyce,</L>
<L N="48">And in helle his soule brede."<NOTE PLACE="foot">This line added at bottom.</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;us deuelis &thorn;er wilis caste</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; &thorn;er argumentis greete,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;ritti &yogh;eer &thorn;ei foondid faste
<PB REF="00000061.tif" N="43"></L>
<L N="52">To tempte ihesu in manye an hete.</L>
<L>&para; "In to a wildirnes with ihesus y paste,</L>
<L>Of him knowliche for to gete,</L>
<L>And fourty daies &thorn;ere he faste</L>
<L N="56">Wi&thorn;oute sleep, drinke, or meete."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e maistir deuel wondre &thorn;ou&yogh;te<MILESTONE N="160" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Of ihesus stalwor&thorn;e complexioun;</L>
<L>Bi mannys fode lyuede he nou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="60">But bi praiers and deuocioun.</L>
<L>&para; "But whanne he bigan to hunger, as me &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>To tempte him &thorn;anne y made me boun:</L>
<L>'Lo, heere be stoonys hard y-wrou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="64">Make herof breed, y seide, to mannis foisoun.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; 'Forso&thorn;e,' ihesu seide, 'not oonli in breed</L>
<L>is verrili mannis propir lyuyng,</L>
<L>But in euery worde of &thorn;e godhede</L>
<L N="68">To body and soule is coumfortynge.'</L>
<L>&para; Vpon an hi&yogh; pinnacle &thorn;anne y him brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And left him &thorn;ere, and leep a-downe,</L>
<L>And seide, 'saue &thorn;ee harmelees, lyme &amp; heed,</L>
<L N="72">And ki&thorn;e now maistries while &thorn;ou art &yogh;onge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; If &thorn;ou be god-is sone, lete se;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;ee is writen longe a-goon,</L>
<L>"Aungils in hondis schullen beere &thorn;ee</L>
<L N="76">Lest &thorn;ou spurne &thorn;i foot at a stoon." '</L>
<L>&para; Quod ihesu, 'in holi writt &thorn;ou maist se,<MILESTONE N="161" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Tempte not &thorn;i lord god lyuynge aloone;</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; al &thorn;i myght and &thorn;i pooste</L>
<L N="80">&THORN;ou schalt him serue, and o&thorn;ir noone.' "</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e deuel si&yogh; it myght not geyn;</L>
<L>Of ihesu his purpos he gan mys;</L>
<L>He brou&yogh;te him til an hi&yogh; mounteyn,
<PB REF="00000062.tif" N="44"></L>
<L N="84">And bad him do as he wolde wys.</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ere he schewide him upon &thorn;at pleyn,</L>
<L>Iewels, ritchesse, and worldli blisse;</L>
<L>"Worschipe me here, &amp; bicome my swayn</L>
<L N="88">And y schal &yogh;eue &thorn;ee al this."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; "Go, sathanas! from blis &thorn;ou flit,</L>
<L>From heuene riche, &thorn;at rial tour!</L>
<L>It is writen oonli in holi writt</L>
<L N="92">'&THORN;i lord god &thorn;ou schalt honour.' "</L>
<L>&para; "Alas," quod &thorn;e deuel, "where hast &thorn;ou &thorn;at witt?</L>
<L>&THORN;i wordis are bittir, &thorn;i werkis aren sour,</L>
<L>&THORN;i conclusioun so soore me knyt,</L>
<L N="96">I abood neuere so scharp a schour."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e deuelis gadriden &thorn;er greet frame,<MILESTONE N="162" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And heelden &thorn;er perlament in &thorn;e myst.</L>
<L>"Oon wolde riflee us at hame,</L>
<L N="100">And gadere &thorn;e flour out of oure gryst;</L>
<L>&para; Neewe gilours wolde waite us schame,</L>
<L>Oon[ys] men clepid him iohne &thorn;e baptist,</L>
<L>But now he ha&thorn; turned, ihesus is his name:</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at first hi&yogh;te ihesu, now is clepid cryst,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I si&yogh; him neuere rage ne plawe,</L>
<L>But euere in stabilnes he is ay,</L>
<L>And streitely kepi&thorn; god-is lawe,</L>
<L N="108">And stijfly wi&thorn;-stoondi&thorn; myn assay;</L>
<L>&para; To werkis of vice wole he not drawe;</L>
<L>A wondir worde y herde him say,</L>
<L>&THORN;e greet temple he wolde doun &thorn;rawe,</L>
<L N="112">And reise it a&yogh;en on &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whanne he was born, wondris bifel:</L>
<L>Ouer al was pees, bo&thorn;e eest and west,
<PB REF="00000063.tif" N="45"></L>
<L>In rome of oile &thorn;ere sprong a welle,</L>
<L N="116">From tristiuer<NOTE PLACE="foot">Is this <I>Trastevere.</I></NOTE> to tybre it ran prest.</L>
<L>&para; In rome &thorn;er templis doun felle,<MILESTONE N="163" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;er mawmetis diden al to-brest,</L>
<L>Aungils to scheperdis glorie gan telle&mdash;</L>
<L N="120">'In er&thorn;e, to al mankinde, bo&thorn;e pees &amp; rest.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e emperour in rome stood hi&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;re sunnis in oon he si&yogh; schyninge clere,</L>
<L>In &thorn;e myddis of hem a maiden he si&yogh;e</L>
<L N="124">A man childe in her armes beere.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e emperour &amp; eek sibile spoken prophesie,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ei acordiden bo&thorn;e in feere,</L>
<L>And seiden 'god-is sone mankinde schulde bie;</L>
<L N="128">It is &thorn;e tokene, &thorn;e tyme nei&yogh;e&thorn; neere.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Also &thorn;re kingis come fro fer,</L>
<L>To worschipe ihesu al &thorn;ei sou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&THORN;at reisid eroudis herte &thorn;ere</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;em to slee, for &thorn;ei so wrou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&para; Bi &thorn;e li&yogh;tnynge of a sterre,</L>
<L>To ihesu alle &thorn;re presentis &thorn;ei brou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Homeward an aungil tau&yogh;te hem nerre</L>
<L N="136">A-no&thorn;er wey &thorn;an &thorn;ei had &thorn;ou&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;anne y councellid eroud with-inne a while<MILESTONE N="164" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>To distroie &thorn;e former prophesie,</L>
<L>&THORN;at alle men children in towne &amp; pile</L>
<L N="140">to slee &thorn;em, &thorn;at ihesus myght with hem die.</L>
<L>&para; He ascapide in to egipt; in &thorn;at while</L>
<L>&thorn;er mawmetis fil doun from an hi&yogh;e;</L>
<L>he knew my &thorn;ou&yogh;te, &amp; si&yogh; my gilee,</L>
<L N="144">y myghte not hide me from his y&yogh;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To tempte ihesu it wole not availe;</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e worldis good ha&thorn; he no neede;
<PB REF="00000064.tif" N="46"></L>
<L>I leese on him so myche trauaile,</L>
<L N="148">&THORN;e more y so worche, &thorn;e worse y spede;</L>
<L>&para; With &thorn;e scharper a-sautis y him assaile,</L>
<L>&THORN;e lasse of me he stoondi&thorn; in drede,</L>
<L>&THORN;e bolder in bikir y bidde him bataile,</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;e lasse of me he taki&thorn; hede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For if y tempte him in wra&thorn;&thorn;e or pride,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; pacience and mekenes he sconfiti&thorn; me;</L>
<L>If y tempte him to letcherie, y muste me hide,</L>
<L N="156">He voidi&thorn; me of wi&thorn; chastitee.</L>
<L>&para; In glotenie &amp; enuye wole he not abide,<MILESTONE N="165" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>But is euere in mesure and in charitee;</L>
<L>In coueitise &amp; auarise wole he not ride,</L>
<L N="160">but is euere in largenes and in pouerte."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e deuel seide, "nei&thorn;er in hoot ne coolde<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? coole, scoole.]</NOTE></L>
<L>I may not make him stumble ne falle;</L>
<L>I nyste him neuere goo to scolee,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? coole, scoole.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="164">And &yogh;it oonis y si&yogh; him spute in &thorn;e scoole halle:</L>
<L>&para; He satte him silf on &thorn;e hi&yogh;est stoole,</L>
<L>And argued a&yogh;ens &thorn;e maistris alle;</L>
<L>Summe callid him wijs, summe callid him foole,</L>
<L N="168">But 'goddis sone' he him silf doo&thorn; calle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Hise werkis passen mannis kinde,</L>
<L>For crokid &amp; creplis he maki&thorn; ri&yogh;t;</L>
<L>For deef, &amp; dombe, &amp; boren blynde,</L>
<L N="172">he &yogh;eue&thorn; hem speche, heeryng, &amp; sight.</L>
<L>&para; Woode men, he &yogh;eue&thorn; hem &thorn;er mynde,</L>
<L>And maki&thorn; mesels hool and li&yogh;t;</L>
<L>A legioun of feendis in a man he dide finde,</L>
<L N="176">Alle he drofe out &thorn;oru&yogh; his myght.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Wiyn of watir he maki&thorn; blyue,<MILESTONE N="166" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And doo&thorn; manye a wondir dede,
<PB REF="00000065.tif" N="47"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; two fyschis, and loues fyue,</L>
<L N="180">fyue &thorn;ousand men y saw&yogh; him fede.</L>
<L>&para; Twelue leepis of releef &thorn;erof dide &thorn;riue</L>
<L>To men, women, &amp; children, &thorn;at hadden nede;</L>
<L>Deed men he reisid from dee&thorn; to lyue,</L>
<L N="184">And &yogh;it weri&thorn; he neuere but oo wede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; He handli&thorn; nei&thorn;er money ne knyf,</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er in synne desiri&thorn; he ony woman to kis;</L>
<L>But oonis he saued a weddid wijf,</L>
<L N="188">In spousebriche &thorn;at hadde doon mys.</L>
<L>&para; He is so wondirful in lijf,</L>
<L>I can not knowe weel what he is;</L>
<L>I wolde we hadde eendid oure striif;</L>
<L N="192">He is oute of oure bookis, &amp; we out of his.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="fit">
<HEAD>2.<NOTE PLACE="foot">Apparently <I>2</I> in red, partly cut, before "A fitte."</NOTE> A fitte.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Si&thorn;en y him first tempte bigan,</L>
<L>I si&yogh; him neuere chaunge hewe;</L>
<L>Oonys he bad me 'go, foule sathan!'</L>
<L N="196">Euere-more &thorn;at repreef y rewe.</L>
<L>&para; In werkis he is good, in persoone a man;<MILESTONE N="167" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Lijk to him y neuere noon knewe.</L>
<L>Where lerned he al &thorn;e witt &thorn;at he can?</L>
<L N="200">For euery day he doo&thorn; wondris neewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I folewide him oonys to a place,</L>
<L>To a mounteyne upon an hi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Petir, iames, &amp; iohn, &thorn;ere was,</L>
<L N="204">Ely &amp; moyses stood &thorn;ere up ri&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; I wolde haue seen ihesu-is face,</L>
<L>But y my&yogh;t not, it schoon so bri&yogh;t;</L>
<L>In &thorn;e soo&thorn;fast sunne closid it was,</L>
<L N="208">&THORN;e bri&yogh;t beemys blent my si&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; To lette &thorn;e prophesie soone y went,</L>
<L>&THORN;e iewis to slee ihesu y &yogh;af hem chois;
<PB REF="00000066.tif" N="48"></L>
<L>If he die on &thorn;e roode, we schul be schent:</L>
<L N="212">I wolde not &thorn;at &thorn;ei hadde &yogh;eue &thorn;at vois.</L>
<L>&para; Me was woo for &thorn;at iugement,</L>
<L>Of 'crucifuge' to heere &thorn;e noise;</L>
<L>Pilatis wijf y bad bisily &yogh;eue tent</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;at ihesu were not doon on &thorn;e crois.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &YOGH;it &thorn;e iewis, for hise dedis goode,<MILESTONE N="168" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Fals witnes vpon him &thorn;ei berid,</L>
<L>And nailid him upon &thorn;e roode,</L>
<L N="220">And peyned him &thorn;ere til &thorn;at he deied.</L>
<L>&para; Vndir his lift side y my silf stood,</L>
<L>And aftir his soule ful naru&yogh; a-spied;</L>
<L>I wist neuere whidir it &yogh;ode;</L>
<L N="224">Whanne he it up &yogh;af, so manly he cried;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e sunne &amp; moone losten &thorn;er light,</L>
<L>&thorn;e elementis fou&yogh;ten as leit of &thorn;undir,</L>
<L>&thorn;e er&thorn;e qwoke, and mounteynes an hight,</L>
<L N="228">Valeis, &amp; stoonys, bursten a-sundir;</L>
<L>&para; Dede men risen &thorn;oru&yogh; his my&yogh;t</L>
<L>To bere witnes of &thorn;at wondir;</L>
<L>My mynde failid, y loste my si&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="232">I nyste how soone y came &thorn;er vndir.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu is soule is wente, y woot not where,</L>
<L>So priuely it dide from me passe;</L>
<L>Whanne his herte was &thorn;irllid with a spere,</L>
<L N="236">&THORN;anne wyste y weel who he was.</L>
<L>&para; Ordeyne we us wi&thorn; al oure gere,<MILESTONE N="169" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>For hidir he &thorn;inki&thorn; to make a race;</L>
<L>Arise we alle &thorn;at ben bounden heere,</L>
<L N="240">And foond we to defende oure place,</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For if &thorn;at he wole hidir come,</L>
<L>We schulen foonde euery-choon,
<PB REF="00000067.tif" N="49"></L>
<L>Alle to-gidere, bo&thorn;e hool &amp; some,</L>
<L N="244">To teer him from &thorn;e top to &thorn;e toon."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;anne seide lucifer anoone,</L>
<L>"It is but waast to speken so;</L>
<L>&THORN;e spirit of him is now hidir come</L>
<L N="248">For to worchen us alle woo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ere as &thorn;e goode soulis diden in dwelle,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei cheyned &thorn;e &yogh;atis, and barred hem faste;</L>
<L>"A! now," ihesu seide, "&yogh;e princis felle,</L>
<L N="252">Opene&thorn; &thorn;e &yogh;atis &thorn;at euere schal laste,</L>
<L>&para; And leti&thorn; in &yogh;oure king of blis to helle."</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuelis axid him &thorn;anne in haste,</L>
<L>"Who is &thorn;e king of blis &thorn;ou doost of telle?</L>
<L N="256">Wenest &thorn;ou to make us alle a-gaste?"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; "Strong god and king of myght,<MILESTONE N="170" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>I am lord and king of blis,</L>
<L>Ouer-comer of dee&thorn;, myghti in fight!</L>
<L N="260">Euerlastynge &yogh;atis, opene&thorn; wight!</L>
<L>&para; Bo&thorn;e pees, mercy, trou&thorn;e, &amp; right,</L>
<L>I brou&yogh;t them at oon, &amp; made &thorn;em to kis;</L>
<L>Euerlastynge &yogh;atis, opene&thorn; on hight,</L>
<L N="264">And lete in &yogh;oure king to take out his!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For y, &thorn;e soule of ihesu crist, am come hider,</L>
<L>Witnes &thorn;erof, my body in er&thorn;e lie&thorn; deed,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e holi goost with &thorn;e soule togider</L>
<L N="268">&THORN;at neuere schal parte from &thorn;e godhede.</L>
<L>&para; In heuen blis &yogh;e stooden full slidir;</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; pride &yogh;e offendid my fadris bede;</L>
<L>Mannis soule for meeknes schal come &thorn;ider,</L>
<L N="272">&THORN;ere as &yogh;e feendis forfetid &thorn;at stide."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;anne seide lucifer, "god dide forbede</L>
<L>To adam in paradiis but oon tree,
<PB REF="00000068.tif" N="50"></L>
<L>And peyne of dee&thorn; to haue for &thorn;at dede,</L>
<L N="276">And aftir in helle euere for to be:</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ou art come of adam seed,<MILESTONE N="171" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;erfore bi right we chalenge &thorn;ee,</L>
<L>For in holi writt &thorn;ou made rede,</L>
<L N="280">'In helle is no remedie.' "</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Ihesu seide, "lucifer, soo&thorn; &thorn;ou tellist me;</L>
<L>But &thorn;ou woost not &thorn;i silf how</L>
<L>&THORN;ere is a boonde helle, but &thorn;is is free.</L>
<L N="284">&THORN;e boond helle was ordeyned for &yogh;ou;</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;at &thorn;at man forfetid &thorn;oru&yogh; a tree,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; a tree a&yogh;en bou&yogh;t is he now.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou madist him synne, &thorn;e peyne longi&thorn; to &thorn;ee,</L>
<L N="288">For &thorn;ou waitist neuere good to mannis prow&yogh;.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lucifer, &thorn;ou me vndir-nome,</L>
<L>And seidist y was of &thorn;e seed of adams kyn;</L>
<L>forso&thorn;e y out of &thorn;e godhede come,</L>
<L N="292">And took fleisch &amp; blood a maiden with-inne.</L>
<L>&para; for as of &thorn;e seed of er&thorn;e &thorn;er springi&thorn; blome,</L>
<L>So mette we, &amp; partid wi&thorn;oute synne:</L>
<L>&THORN;in argument is fals, so is &thorn;i doome;</L>
<L N="296">Bi what right woldist &thorn;ou me wynne?</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Who was cheef of &thorn;i councell<MILESTONE N="172" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>In heuen whanne &thorn;ou forfetidist &thorn;e blis?</L>
<L>In paradiis adam &thorn;ou dedist assaile,</L>
<L N="300">And temptidist him to forfete his;</L>
<L>&para; And y in his quarel took bataile</L>
<L>A&yogh;en my fadir to amende his mys,</L>
<L>Wherfor of &thorn;i purpos &thorn;ou schalt faile,</L>
<L N="304">forthi &thorn;i quarel nou&yogh;t it is."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;anne lucifer answeride ageyn,</L>
<L>"Whi spekist &thorn;ou so to me heere?
<PB REF="00000069.tif" N="51"></L>
<L>It is but wantowne wordis in veyn;</L>
<L N="308">I trowe &thorn;ou comest hidir us to fere.</L>
<L>&para; Sumtyme whanne y was in heuen an hi&yogh;,</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;at y &thorn;ere loste for my pride, certeyn,</L>
<L>Heere-aftir y hope ful sikirly</L>
<L N="312">For to come to &thorn;at blis ageyn."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Crist ihesu spak to sathan tho,</L>
<L>And seide to him in &thorn;is manere,</L>
<L>"It is but waast to speken so,</L>
<L N="316">Or ony suche wordis to seie now here.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at tyme while &thorn;ou in heuen were,<MILESTONE N="173" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Ful myche ioie haddist &thorn;ou tho;</L>
<L>For alle &thorn;i felawis, glad were &thorn;ei &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="320">But ri&yogh;t soone it was ouer-goo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lucifer spak to him ageyn,</L>
<L>And seide to him with wordis sere,</L>
<L>"In &thorn;is place y haue dwellid in woo &amp; peine</L>
<L N="324">Moore &thorn;an &thorn;is .iiij. &thorn;ousand &yogh;eere:</L>
<L>&para; Helpe me to &thorn;at blis ageyn</L>
<L>&THORN;e which y loste for my pride &thorn;ere,</L>
<L>for &thorn;ere it is myrie in certeyn</L>
<L N="328">To wonye wi&thorn; rial aungils clere."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; "I seie &thorn;ee, lucifer, y schal &thorn;ee telle,</L>
<L>Or euere ony &thorn;ing was wrought&mdash;</L>
<L>Heuene or er&thorn;e, eir or helle,&mdash;</L>
<L N="332">Forso&thorn;e &thorn;oo y made &thorn;ee of nought.</L>
<L>&para; In heuen whanne &thorn;ou stoodist in wele,</L>
<L>I made &thorn;ee aboue aungils alle,</L>
<L>But &thorn;erof rau&yogh;t &thorn;ou neuere a deel,</L>
<L N="336">Suche pride in &thorn;in herte gan falle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In heuen whanne &thorn;ou were at &thorn;i wille,<MILESTONE N="174" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;ou my&yogh;tist haue be in pees &amp; reste;
<PB REF="00000070.tif" N="52"></L>
<L>I took &thorn;ee my seete ful stille,</L>
<L N="340">It to &yogh;eme &thorn;ou were ful prest;</L>
<L>&para; And while y wente where me list,</L>
<L>And come a&yogh;en a-noon in hi&yogh;e,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou seidist &thorn;at &thorn;ou were wor&thorn;iest,</L>
<L N="344">And to sitte &thorn;ere as weel as y;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And &thorn;ou repentidist &thorn;ee neuermore,</L>
<L>But euere aggregidist &thorn;i trespas.</L>
<L>Adam wepte &amp; si&yogh;ede soore,</L>
<L N="348">And askid mercy &amp; oile of grace;</L>
<L>&para; My fadir sende me hidir &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L>Vpon a tree leete dee&thorn; me chase,</L>
<L>A spere &thorn;oru&yogh; myn herte gan boore,</L>
<L N="352">&amp; leete out &thorn;e derwor&thorn;iest oile &thorn;at euere was.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In my fadris name of heuene</L>
<L>Opene &thorn;e &yogh;atis a&yogh;ens me!"</L>
<L>As li&yogh;t of leite, and &thorn;undir leeme,</L>
<L N="356">&THORN;e &yogh;atis to-burste, and gan to flee;</L>
<L>&para; God took out adam and eue ful euene,<MILESTONE N="175" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And alle hise chosen companye.</L>
<L>&THORN;e prophetis seiden with mylde steuene,</L>
<L N="360">"A song of wondris now synge we."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; "A, ha!" seide <B>Adam,</B> "my god y se;</L>
<L>He &thorn;at made me wi&thorn; his hond!"</L>
<L>"I se," seide <B>noe,</B> "where come&thorn; hee</L>
<L N="364">&THORN;at sauede me bo&thorn;e on watir &amp; londe!"</L>
<L>&para; Quod <B>abraham,</B> "y se my god so free</L>
<L>&THORN;at sauede my sone fro bittir bande!"</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide <B>moyses,</B> "&thorn;ese tablis he bitook me</L>
<L N="368">His lawe to preche and vndirstande!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Quod <B>Dauid,</B> "we spoken of oon so grym</L>
<L>&THORN;at schulde breke &thorn;e brasen &yogh;atis."
<PB REF="00000071.tif" N="53"></L>
<L>Quod <B>Zacharie</B>, "&amp; his folk out nym,</L>
<L N="372">And leue &thorn;ere stille &thorn;o &thorn;at he hatis."</L>
<L>&para; Quod <B>symeon</B>, "he li&yogh;tne&thorn; his folk in dym,</L>
<L>Lo where derknes schendi&thorn; her statis.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seide iohne, "&thorn;is lomb, y spak of him,</L>
<L N="376">&THORN;at al &thorn;e worldis synne a-batys."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Oure lord them took bi &thorn;e hond,<MILESTONE N="176" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And brou&yogh;t &thorn;em to &thorn;e place of blis,</L>
<L>And seide to them, y vndir-stonde,</L>
<L N="380">"&THORN;is bargeyn y haue bou&yogh;t her, &thorn;is:</L>
<L>&para; For riche &amp; pore, free and bonde</L>
<L>&THORN;at wole axe grace and ameende &thorn;er mys,</L>
<L>Schulen be with &yogh;ou heere pleyande</L>
<L N="384">In my kingdom, heuene blis."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thus ihesus crist harewide helle,</L>
<L>And ledde hise louers to paradijs:</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e o&thorn;ere hellis wolde he not melle,</L>
<L N="388">Where feendis blake bounden lijs,</L>
<L>&para; And where dampned soulis euere schulen dwelle</L>
<L>&THORN;at wolen not do weel, but euere be nyce,</L>
<L>Turmentid with horible deuelis of helle</L>
<L N="392">&THORN;at sumtyme were aungils of prijs.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Helle repreued &thorn;o &thorn;e deuel sathan,</L>
<L>And horribli gan him dispice,</L>
<L>"To me &thorn;ou art a schrewide captayn,</L>
<L N="396">A combrid wretche in cowardise."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;o seide lucifer, "si&thorn;en &thorn;e world bigan<MILESTONE N="177" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>I haue brou&yogh;t hidir manye a greet price</L>
<L>Hidir into helle of al kinde of man,</L>
<L N="400">Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e false, foolis, and &thorn;e wise.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Helle, so worschipide neuere &thorn;ou were</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou cowdist haue kept &thorn;ee soo;
<PB REF="00000072.tif" N="54"></L>
<L>I brou&yogh;te &thorn;ee bo&thorn;e god &amp; man in fere;</L>
<L N="404">Whi were &thorn;ou so nyce to leete him go?"</L>
<L>&para; Quod helle, "not wi&thorn; &thorn;i poowere</L>
<L>I my&yogh;te not werne him oon of tho;</L>
<L>He took out alle &thorn;at were him dere;</L>
<L N="408">I my&yogh;te not lette him, &thorn;ou&yogh; he wolde mo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Quod belsabub, "y barrid ful faste</L>
<L>&THORN;e &yogh;atis with lok, cheyne, bolt, &amp; pyn;</L>
<L>And with oo word of his wyndis blaste</L>
<L N="412">&THORN;ei broken vp, and he came ynne.</L>
<L>&para; He boond me, and downe me caste;</L>
<L>it is to us no bote to stryue with him;</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;e dreedful doome is come &amp; paste,</L>
<L N="416">Oure eendelees peyne is &thorn;anne to bigynne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;e iewis dide ihesu to die,<MILESTONE N="178" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&YOGH;it on &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day he roos to liif a&yogh;en;</L>
<L>It was to him moore victorie</L>
<L N="420">&THORN;an &thorn;ow&yogh; he hadde alle &thorn;e iewis sleyn.</L>
<L>&para; Summe were glad whanne &thorn;ei him si&yogh;e,</L>
<L>Summe were sory, summe were fayne,</L>
<L>And sumtyme in oon companye</L>
<L N="424">Amonge .v. hundrid he was seyn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of oynement ful manye a drope,</L>
<L>Marie mawdeleyne to ihesu sche brou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Ihesu wente fro a litil a-slope,</L>
<L N="428">And seide, "mawdeleyn, towche me nou&yogh;t."</L>
<L>&para; Alle hise disciplis weren in wanhope;</L>
<L>For to coumforte them ihesu &thorn;ou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And bad hem hise woundis handle &amp; grope,</L>
<L N="432">"I haue fleisch &amp; blood! so spiritus haue nou&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Thomas was of right hard bileeue</L>
<L>Til he hadde spoke wi&thorn; ihesu tho:
<PB REF="00000073.tif" N="55"></L>
<L>Ihesu spak wi&thorn; wordis breue,</L>
<L N="436">"Come hidir, thomas, &amp; speke me to;</L>
<L>&para; For here &thorn;ou maist now &thorn;e soo&thorn;e preue,<MILESTONE N="179" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>How &thorn;at y on &thorn;e roode was y-doo;</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at wille not on it bileeue,</L>
<L N="440">Schal be dampned to peine for euermo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;anne seide ihesu wi&thorn; myelde speche</L>
<L>To hise disciplis, "y wole &yogh;e goo</L>
<L>To alle creaturis aboute, to preche</L>
<L N="444">Myn uprisynge, to freende &amp; foo;</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;o &thorn;at bileeuen &thorn;at &yogh;e teeche,</L>
<L>Bodies and soulis saued ben thoo;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at bileeuen not, y seie to eche,</L>
<L N="448">&THORN;o schulen for euere to peine goo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; From &yogh;ou, feendis schulen flee for my name;</L>
<L>Eddris &amp; venym schal from &yogh;ou steele;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &yogh;e drinke poisoun, it schal not &yogh;ou tame,</L>
<L N="452">Nei&thorn;er harme &yogh;ou, ne noo greef feele.</L>
<L>&para; I schal newe tungis in &yogh;ou frame</L>
<L>Alle maner of langagis for&thorn; to deele;</L>
<L>And &thorn;o &thorn;at &yogh;e touche, sike or lame,</L>
<L N="456">Body and soule y wole hem heele."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Oure lord, aftir his resurreccioun, here<MILESTONE N="180" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>In er&thorn;e he was forso&thorn;e dwellynge</L>
<L>Til hooly &thorn;ursday comen were,</L>
<L N="460">&THORN;at he sti&yogh; to heuene, where he is king.</L>
<L>&para; At &thorn;e dreedful doom, wi&thorn;-out lesing,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e quycke and deede &thorn;ere schal he deme.</L>
<L>God &yogh;eue us grace in oure lyuynge</L>
<L N="464">To serue oure god, &amp; marie to qweeme.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Of alle &thorn;e children &thorn;at euere were borun,</L>
<L>Saue oonli crist him silf a-loone,
<PB REF="00000074.tif" N="56"></L>
<L>Was no on so holi here biforn</L>
<L N="468">As was &thorn;is holi child seynt iohun</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at baptisid oure lord in flom iordon</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; ful deuout &amp; good deuocioun,</L>
<L>And after for ihesus loue to dee&thorn; gan goon,</L>
<L N="472">And suffride ful mykil passioun.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Now schal y telle with ful good cheere</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at holi assumpcioun</L>
<L>Of his blessid modir dere,</L>
<L N="476">How sche was taken up with greet deuocioun</L>
<L>&para; Vnto hir blessid sone, as his wil were,<MILESTONE N="181" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;erto sente hise aungils a-down,</L>
<L>&amp; vp &thorn;ei baren &thorn;at maiden cleere;</L>
<L N="480">Queene of heuen &thorn;ere &thorn;ei dide hir crowne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;anne alle aungils &thorn;at were in heuene</L>
<L>Were at &thorn;e crownyng of &thorn;at maide free,</L>
<L>And songen alle with mylde steuene</L>
<L N="484">"Gloria tibi domine."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at is a song of ioie and blisse!</L>
<L>God &yogh;eue us grace &thorn;at si&yogh;t to se,</L>
<L>Of his mercy &thorn;at we nou&yogh;t mysse,</L>
<L N="488">Qui natus es de virgine.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;is song &thorn;at y haue sunge &yogh;ou heere,</L>
<L>Is clepid '&thorn;e deuelis perlament:'</L>
<L>&THORN;erof is red in tyme of &yogh;eere</L>
<L N="492">On &thorn;e first sunday of clene lent.</L>
<L>&para; Who-so wole haue heuen to his hire,</L>
<L>Kepe he him from &thorn;e deuelis combirment;</L>
<L>In heuene his soule may &thorn;ere be sure</L>
<L N="496">Wi&thorn; aungils to pleie verament.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;is lessoun was made but late;<MILESTONE N="182" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;ere ben no triflis in &thorn;is tale;
<PB REF="00000075.tif" N="57"></L>
<L>&THORN;e deuelis boost &thorn;us gan he bate,</L>
<L N="500">Oure curteis crist, oure king riale.</L>
<L>&para; He helpe us in alle at heuene &yogh;ate,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; seintis to sitte &thorn;ere in sale!</L>
<L>Crist! kepe us out of harme and hate,</L>
<L N="504">For &thorn;in hooli spirit so special!<NOTE PLACE="end">[The <I>Diatorie</I> printed in <I>The Babees Book</I>, or <I>Manners &amp; Meals, &amp;c.</I>, follows here.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>Explicit parlamentum of feendis.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000076.tif" N="58">
<HEAD>The Mirror of the Periods of Man's Life. OR BIDS OF THE VIRTUES AND VICES FOR THE SOUL OF MAN.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[Lambeth MS. 853, ab. 1430 A.D., pages 120-150, written without breaks, till near the bottom of p. 131, as marked by the insetting of the even lines here.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>HOw mankinde doo&thorn; bigynne</L>
<L>is wondir for to scryue so;</L>
<L>In game he is bigoten in synne,</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e child is &thorn;e modris deedli foo;</L>
<L>Or &thorn;ei be fulli partide on tweyne,</L>
<L>In perelle of deed ben bo&thorn;e two.</L>
<L>Pore he come &thorn;e worlde with-ynne,</L>
<L N="8">Wi&thorn; sorewe &amp; pouert oute schal he goo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In wyntir ny&yogh;t or y wakid,</L>
<L>In my sleep y dreemed so;</L>
<L>I saw a child modir <MILESTONE N="121" UNIT="page">nakid,</L>
<L N="12">New born &thorn;e modir fro.</L>
<L>Al aloone, as god him makid,</L>
<L>In wildirnesse he dide goo,</L>
<L>Til two in gouernaunce it takid,</L>
<L N="16">An aungil freende, an aungil foo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod &thorn;e world to &thorn;e child, "how many foolde</L>
<L>Hast &thorn;ou brou&yogh;t richesse? now late se:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou schuldist deie for hunger and coolde</L>
<L N="20">But y lente meete &amp; clo&thorn;e to &thorn;ee:
<PB REF="00000077.tif" N="59"></L>
<L>I wole &thorn;ee fynde til &thorn;ou be oolde;</L>
<L>How wolt &thorn;ou quyte it me?"</L>
<L>Quod desteine, "he is bou&yogh;t &amp; soolde."</L>
<L N="24">Quod dee&thorn;, "his eende make schal we."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod &thorn;e child, "y come poore &thorn;e world with|inne</L>
<L>To pursue a wondirful eritage:</L>
<L>Nakid out of &thorn;e wyket of synne,</L>
<L N="28">Of the perellis of streite passage,</L>
<L>To seke dee&thorn; y dide bigynne,</L>
<L>&THORN;at ilke dredful pilgrymage,</L>
<L>Mi body &amp; soule to parte a tweyne,</L>
<L N="32">To make a deuourse of &thorn;at mariage.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Li&yogh;tnesse, stren&thorn;e, corage &amp; bewte,</L>
<L>&THORN;e comaundementis &thorn;at god bede;</L>
<L>Lust, liking, &amp; iolite,</L>
<L N="36">.vij. werkis of mercy <MILESTONE N="122" UNIT="page">and &thorn;e crede.</L>
<L>Veyn glorie, flaterynge, and vanyte,</L>
<L>Sowowe, si&yogh;ing, loue, &amp; drede,</L>
<L>To the child her seruice profren he,</L>
<L N="40">For helle peyne or heuene meede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thanne come oon &amp; stood ful stille,</L>
<L>And his seruice profride he:</L>
<L>"&THORN;ese folke wolde &thorn;i silfe spille</L>
<L N="44">To make &thorn;ee bonde; y wole make &thorn;ee free.</L>
<L>&THORN;ei han &thorn;ee tau&yogh;t bo&thorn;e good &amp; ille;</L>
<L>From her councel fast &thorn;ou flee,</L>
<L>For my name is freewille;</L>
<L N="48">Leue alle hem &amp; folowe me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The &yogh;onge childe in studie stood,</L>
<L>And in herte wittis sou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Conscience mengid his mood,</L>
<L N="52">"Mi fair childe, what hast &thorn;ou &thorn;ou&yogh;t?
<PB REF="00000078.tif" N="60"></L>
<L>I am Conscience, knowe yuel &amp; good,</L>
<L>We two to rekenynge must be brou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>Biwaare! free wille wole make &thorn;ee woode;</L>
<L N="56">Free wille withouten witte is nou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For my name is Conscience;</L>
<L>To knowe me &thorn;ou must bigynne;</L>
<L>Discrecioun is my science,</L>
<L N="60">Vicis &amp; Vertues <MILESTONE N="123" UNIT="page">to voide a twynne.</L>
<L>A-queynte &thorn;e weel with Prudence,</L>
<L>He ledi&thorn; alle vertues out &amp; inne;</L>
<L>Bi waar of richelees, for he wole make diffence,</L>
<L N="64">For he is leder of al synne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whanne &thorn;e child was .vij. &yogh;eer olde,</L>
<L>Passyng sowkyng of milke drewis,</L>
<L>&THORN;e good aungil &thorn;e childe dide weelde;</L>
<L N="68">Al vertu to him &thorn;an soone he schewis:</L>
<L>"To fadir &amp; modir honour &thorn;ou &yogh;eelde;</L>
<L>Loue god, &amp; drede, and be of good &thorn;ewis."</L>
<L>&THORN;e wickid aungil bad him be boold</L>
<L N="72">To calle bo&thorn;e fadir &amp; modir schrewis.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e good aungil badde him "be mylde</L>
<L>From al woo, it wole &thorn;ee werre:</L>
<L>&THORN;at man may hi&yogh;e housis bilde</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at his tunge can weel for-beerre."</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e wickid aungil, "while &thorn;ou art a child,</L>
<L>With &thorn;i tunge on folk &thorn;ou bleere;</L>
<L>Course of kynde is for &yogh;ou&thorn;e to be wilde,</L>
<L N="80">To beete alle children, and do hem deerre."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus at <MILESTONE N="124" UNIT="page">vij. &yogh;eer age childhood bigynnes,</L>
<L>And folowith folies many foold;</L>
<L>Aftirward his childhode blynnes;</L>
<L N="84">Whanne he is fourtene &yogh;eer oolde,
<PB REF="00000079.tif" N="61"></L>
<L>&THORN;anne knowliche of manhode he wynnes,</L>
<L>&THORN;e .vij. vertues wi&thorn; him wonne wolde;</L>
<L>&THORN;anne come&thorn; &thorn;e .vij. deedli synnes</L>
<L N="88">With &thorn;e wickid aungil housholde to holde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod resoun, "in age of .xx. &yogh;eer,</L>
<L>Goo to oxenford, or lerne lawe."</L>
<L>Quod lust, "harpe &amp; giterne &thorn;ere may y leere,</L>
<L N="92">And pickid staffe &amp; buckelere, &thorn;ere-wi&thorn; to plawe,</L>
<L>At tauerne to make wommen myrie cheere,</L>
<L>And wilde felawis to-gidere drawe,</L>
<L>And be to bemond<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>bemond</I> is the name of a dog:?poaching.</NOTE> A good squyer</L>
<L N="96">Al ny&yogh;t til &thorn;e day do dawe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod conscience, "&thorn;at axi&thorn; coost;</L>
<L>&THORN;e moore &thorn;ou spendist, &thorn;e lesse &thorn;ou hast;</L>
<L>&THORN;i tyme, &thorn;i leernynge bo&thorn;e ben loost,</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;i freendis good &thorn;ou spendist in waast."</L>
<L>Quod lust to conscience, "&yogh;ou&thorn;e so muste;</L>
<L>&YOGH;ou&thorn;e can not kepe him chast."<MILESTONE N="125" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>"Good conscience, goo preche to &thorn;e post,</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;i councel saueri&thorn; not my tast.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; Conscience bidde me be stille,</L>
<L>I wole holde for&thorn;e &thorn;at y bigan;</L>
<L>Al my lust y wole ful-fille,</L>
<L N="108">I wole spare no womman;</L>
<L>Conscience wolde binde me to skille,</L>
<L>And make me his bondman.</L>
<L>Fareweel Conscience! weelcome frewille!</L>
<L N="112">I wole lerne no more good &thorn;an y can."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now vicis &amp; vertues wole not slake,</L>
<L>Now man is .xx. wyntir in age:</L>
<L>Quod pride, "no man &thorn;ou forsake,</L>
<L N="116">I wole &thorn;ee sette in &thorn;e hi&yogh;est stage."
<PB REF="00000080.tif" N="62"></L>
<L>Quod glotenye, "ny&yogh;t &amp; day &thorn;ou wake;</L>
<L>Ete late &amp; eerli in outrage."</L>
<L>Quod leccherie, "&thorn;i seed richelees &thorn;ou schake,</L>
<L N="120">And make no force of no mariage."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod wra&thorn;&thorn;e, "loke &thorn;ou bere &thorn;ee bolde;</L>
<L>What man &thorn;ee teene, His heed &thorn;ou breest."</L>
<L>Quod enuie, "&thorn;i foote &thorn;ou holde,</L>
<L N="124">And pursue <MILESTONE N="126" UNIT="page">for to passe &thorn;e beest."</L>
<L>Quod slou&thorn;e, "in &yogh;ou&thorn;e, or &thorn;ou be oolde,</L>
<L>Leerne for to take &thorn;i reest."</L>
<L>Quod Coueitise, "wynnen y wolde."</L>
<L N="128">Quod auarise, "locke me in &thorn;i cheest."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Apparaile &thorn;e propirli," quod Pride,</L>
<L>"Loke &thorn;i pockettis passe &thorn;e lengist gise;</L>
<L>Slatre &thorn;i clothis bo&thorn;e schorte &amp; side</L>
<L N="132">Passinge alle o&thorn;ere mennis sise;</L>
<L>And where &thorn;at &thorn;ou goo ou&thorn;er ride,</L>
<L>Do no reuerence to foole ne wise;</L>
<L>Late no poore nei&yogh;bore &thorn;ryue &thorn;ee biside;</L>
<L N="136">Alle o&thorn;er mennis councel loke &thorn;ou dispise."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Bi waare," quod Meekenes, "how pride doo&thorn; wys;</L>
<L>He &yogh;eue&thorn; but woo &amp; wyssche to wage;</L>
<L>Of aungelis bewte &thorn;e prijs was his;</L>
<L N="140">In heuene on &thorn;e hi&yogh;est stage,</L>
<L>He wolde haue peerid with god of blis;</L>
<L>Now is he in helle moost loo&thorn;eli page.</L>
<L>&THORN;at feendis forfetid for her mys,</L>
<L N="144">Is now meeke mannis eritage."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod wra&thorn;&thorn;e, "From &thorn;at councel flee,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou art stalwor&thorn;e, &yogh;onge, and li&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Of all quarellis medle &thorn;ou &thorn;ee<MILESTONE N="127" UNIT="page"></L>
<L N="148">Bo&thorn;e of wronge &amp; of ri&yogh;te.
<PB REF="00000081.tif" N="63"></L>
<L>Who dar bete &thorn;ee, nay lete be,</L>
<L>Riche or poore, weike or wi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;ou bere &thorn;ee boolde on me,</L>
<L N="152">And y for &thorn;ee wole chide &amp; fli&yogh;te."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne up stood Paciens,</L>
<L>"As wra&thorn;&thorn;e biddi&thorn; do not soo,</L>
<L>For wra&thorn;&thorn;e ha&thorn; no Conscience,</L>
<L N="156">He maki&thorn; ech man o&thorn;eris foo;</L>
<L>&THORN;er-with he geti&thorn; his dispence,</L>
<L>&THORN;at schulde be freende, to make hem foo.</L>
<L>Praie god, he be &thorn;i diffence,</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;at &thorn;ou be not founde in &thorn;e noumbre of &thorn;oo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod enuie &thorn;anne, "y wole &thorn;ee leere</L>
<L>To make &thorn;i lord to &thorn;ee tame;</L>
<L>Be homeli, &amp; rowne in his eere,</L>
<L N="164">And bringe trewe folk in fals fame.</L>
<L>Make him &thorn;i suget, to &thorn;ee to swere</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schal not discure &thorn;i name;</L>
<L>So make him fals witnesse to bere,</L>
<L N="168">And gete &thorn;ee richesse wi&thorn; god-is grame."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne up roos a souereyn uertu</L>
<L>&THORN;at is clepid Charite:</L>
<L>"Loke &thorn;ou not hise maners sue,</L>
<L N="172">For god-is enemy so&thorn;eli is he.</L>
<L>Do &thorn;ou to euery man &thorn;at is due<MILESTONE N="128" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>As &thorn;ou woldist he dide to &thorn;ee."</L>
<L>Quod Coueitise "and alle folk were trewe,</L>
<L N="176">Manye a man schulde neuere &thorn;ee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Caste &thorn;ee faste to Coueitise,</L>
<L>Make sotil &thorn;i wittis, &amp; forge wilis,</L>
<L>And preue &thorn;at trewe men be nyce,</L>
<L N="180">For so &thorn;e fals &thorn;e trewe bigilis;
<PB REF="00000082.tif" N="64"></L>
<L>Such ben worschipid &amp; holden wise,</L>
<L>&THORN;ei purchasen hem townes, maners, &amp; pilis,</L>
<L>And tru&thorn;e wolde wite where &thorn;i lordschip lijs;</L>
<L N="184">Make heggis bi-twene &yogh;ou, and no stilis."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod largenes in almesse dede,</L>
<L>"Coueitise councelli&thorn; &thorn;ee amys.</L>
<L>&YOGH;eue to &thorn;e pore, &amp; &thorn;ou schalt spede</L>
<L N="188">&THORN;e bettir, &thorn;e gospel sei&thorn; &thorn;is;</L>
<L>For at &thorn;e doome &thorn;ere &thorn;ou schalt drede,</L>
<L>Crist wole reherse of &thorn;ee y-wys</L>
<L>&THORN;e werkis of merci, as clerkis reede:</L>
<L N="192">If &thorn;ou hast doon hem, &thorn;ou goost to blis."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Man, loue &thorn;i wombe," quod Gloteny,</L>
<L>"Leie mete upon meete, &amp; ete faste;</L>
<L>But leue not &thorn;i crummes drye,</L>
<L N="196">Drinke &thorn;ou til &thorn;e ful flood be paste.</L>
<L>Leue clennesse, &amp; use harlotrie,</L>
<L>But neuere a day loke &thorn;ou ne faste;<MILESTONE N="129" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>In &thorn;i wombe make &thorn;i tresorie,</L>
<L N="200">Of &thorn;eeuis &thorn;anne &thorn;ou schalt not be agast."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod Mesure, "man! haue me in mynde.</L>
<L>God made man suget to resoun:</L>
<L>Wat turne&thorn; a man to beestis kinde</L>
<L N="204">But etynge &amp; drynking out of sesoun?</L>
<L>Drunkelew folk ben goostli blinde;</L>
<L>For faute of witt her lijf is gesoun;</L>
<L>In ydil oo&thorn;is wasten &thorn;ei her wynde:</L>
<L N="208">To repreue suche, god fyndi&thorn; enchesoun.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod Slou&thorn;e, "bisynesse y &thorn;ee forbede;</L>
<L>To chirche nei&thorn;er goo ne renne;</L>
<L>Who techi&thorn; &thorn;ee good, take noon hede,</L>
<L N="212">A&yogh;ens oo worde &yogh;eue him ten:
<PB REF="00000083.tif" N="65"></L>
<L>Seie 'alle folk ben not sotil in dede;'</L>
<L>Excuse &thorn;ee so bi o&thorn;er men,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue hem myche maugre to mede</L>
<L N="216">&THORN;at ony good &thorn;ee wolde kenne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod Besinesse, "man! of Slou&thorn;e be waare;</L>
<L>He is assigned to helle for synne;</L>
<L>In good lyuynge &thorn;i wittis ware,</L>
<L N="220">To drede god &thorn;ou muste bigynne;</L>
<L>&THORN;i fleischeli lustis &thorn;ou muste spare,</L>
<L>For vicis and vertues wole voide atwynne;<MILESTONE N="130" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>In besinessis hous is good weelfare,</L>
<L N="224">And Slou&thorn;e ha&thorn; hunger and clo&thorn;is &thorn;inne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod leccherie to man, "loue &thorn;anne weel me,</L>
<L>&THORN;i lustis with wommen &thorn;ou fulfille,</L>
<L>For if &thorn;ou in &yogh;ou&thorn;e sparist &thorn;anne &thorn;ee,</L>
<L N="228">&THORN;ou maist falle in greet perille.</L>
<L>&YOGH;ou&thorn;e ful of corage wole be;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou muste haue helpe, or ellis spille;</L>
<L>Spare no womman, y councelle &thorn;e,</L>
<L N="232">&THORN;ou&yogh; summe cryen neuere so schille."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod Chastite to man, "loo,</L>
<L>Herken how leccherie doo&thorn; speke!</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;ou &thorn;i foule luste hast doo,</L>
<L N="236">Bi waare him &thorn;anne! he wole &thorn;ee &thorn;rete,</L>
<L>And seie 'for &thorn;ou hast so doo</L>
<L>&THORN;ou must suffre peynes greete;'</L>
<L>And but if god help &thorn;ee &thorn;o,</L>
<L N="240">Soone in wanhope he wole &thorn;ee lete.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod &thorn;e good aungil, "&yogh;it &thorn;ee avise;</L>
<L>Lerne witte while &thorn;ou art heere;</L>
<L>He is a foole &thorn;at may be wise,</L>
<L N="244">In heuene come&thorn; no foolis to &yogh;eere,<MILESTONE N="131" UNIT="page">
<PB REF="00000084.tif" N="66"></L>
<L>God doo&thorn; richelees foolis refuse</L>
<L>&THORN;at kunnen no good, ne noon wole lere;</L>
<L>If wordis excuse, werkis accuse,</L>
<L N="248">&THORN;at maki&thorn; hem worse &thorn;an &thorn;ei were."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"IN &thorn;ritti &yogh;eer now y abide;</L>
<L>In discrecioun I haue in-si&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Loueli to goo, and to ride,</L>
<L N="252">Ful of manhode &amp; of my&yogh;t."</L>
<L>Quod Conscience, "vertues &thorn;ou puttist aside,</L>
<L>And norischist vicis day &amp; ny&yogh;t."</L>
<L>Quod man in scorn, "lo, Conscience doo&thorn; chide!</L>
<L N="256">For losse of catel he dar not fi&yogh;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Man, kepe &thorn;i richesse," quod Conscience,</L>
<L>"To maynteine pride, it costi&thorn; greete;</L>
<L>It costi&thorn; nou&yogh;t, meekenesse ne pacience,</L>
<L N="260">But it axi&thorn; greet coost to chide &amp; to beete.</L>
<L>Leccherie axi&thorn; greet dispense,</L>
<L>It distroie&thorn; mannis kindeli heete;</L>
<L>And glotenie coosti&thorn; wi&thorn;outen diffence</L>
<L N="264">Bo&thorn;e in diuerse drinkis and meete.</L>
<L>"IT costi&thorn; greet to use a synne</L>
<L>&THORN;at is clepid foule Enuye,</L>
<L>For it freti&thorn; man with-inne;<MILESTONE N="132" UNIT="page"></L>
<L N="268">Bodi &amp; soule it doo&thorn; distroie.</L>
<L>Slou&thorn;is &thorn;rifte, it is ful &thorn;inne,</L>
<L>It costi&thorn; myche in slou&thorn;e to lie;</L>
<L>And Coueitise al &thorn;e world wolde wynne,</L>
<L N="272">And Auarise aftir more doith crie."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod man to Conscience, "&yogh;ou&thorn;e axi&thorn; delice;</L>
<L>For &yogh;ou&thorn;e &thorn;e course of kinde wole holde;</L>
<L>But &yogh;ou&thorn;e were a foole and nyce,</L>
<L N="276">How schulde wijsdom be founde in oolde.
<PB REF="00000085.tif" N="67"></L>
<L>&THORN;e corage of &yogh;ou&thorn;e, and oolde wise,</L>
<L>Maki&thorn; &yogh;onge men to be boolde;</L>
<L>In witt of oolde, worschipe lijs;</L>
<L N="280">In &thorn;e witte of wise, kingdom is holde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;ou wastist &thorn;i wynde &amp; spillist &thorn;i speche,</L>
<L>&THORN;i wordis me is loo&thorn; to heere;</L>
<L>And y dide as &thorn;ou doist me teche,</L>
<L N="284">I schulde neuere make myrie chere.</L>
<L>Wenest &thorn;ou with &thorn;in hond heuene to reche?</L>
<L>&THORN;in arme wole not be so longe to &yogh;eere;</L>
<L>Now, good Conscience, &amp; &thorn;ou wolt preche,</L>
<L N="288">Goo stele an abite, &amp; bicome a frere."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod man, "y pleie, y wrastile, y sprynge,<MILESTONE N="133" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;ese ioies wolen neuere wende me fro;</L>
<L>Now alle gamys hom y brynge;</L>
<L N="292">What such as y am, &thorn;er ben no moo:</L>
<L>I leepe, y daunce, y skippe, y synge,</L>
<L>I am so myrie y can not seie hoo."</L>
<L>Quod Conscience, "&thorn;ou schalt weepe &amp; wringe</L>
<L N="296">Whanne &thorn;ei take her leeue to goo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Myn i&yogh;en ben cleere &amp; bri&yogh;t as glas,</L>
<L>Mi lire as lillye and roose of hewe,</L>
<L>Of schappe &amp; streng&thorn;e alle folke y passe,</L>
<L N="300">And euere my uertu wexi&thorn; newe."</L>
<L>Quod Conscience, "y loue &thorn;ee weel &thorn;e lasse,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou usist ne werkis of good vertu."</L>
<L>"Goo, Conscience, &thorn;ou lewide asse,</L>
<L N="304">I kepe not &thorn;i maneris to sue."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod man, "Myne age is fourti &yogh;eere."</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e world, "y offre to &thorn;ee my weele."</L>
<L>Quod streng&thorn;e, "late no man be &thorn;i peere."</L>
<L N="308">Quod corage, "late no man with &thorn;ee deele."
<PB REF="00000086.tif" N="68"></L>
<L>Quod luste and liking, "make good cheere."<MILESTONE N="134" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>"I am al hool wi&thorn; &thorn;ee," quod heele.</L>
<L>Quod Conscience, "wistist &thorn;ou what &thorn;ese were?</L>
<L N="312">At nede wole faile &thorn;i fleische so freele."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod Conscience to man in &yogh;ou&thorn;e,</L>
<L>"Traueile in trou&thorn;e in tyme is beste."</L>
<L>Quod trou&thorn;e, "gete &thorn;ee richesse nou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="316">Wherwi&thorn; in oolde to haue &thorn;i reste;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; age can as he cowthe,</L>
<L>My&yogh;t &amp; corage he ha&thorn; looste,</L>
<L>He kepi&thorn; his soule &thorn;at kepi&thorn; his mou&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="320">For &thorn;e soule to &thorn;e fleisch is but a goost."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Now am I fifti &yogh;eere y-wis,</L>
<L>Myn heer bigynne&thorn; to change his hewe."</L>
<L>Quod Conscience, "flee from alle vice,</L>
<L N="324">And use werkis of good vertu,</L>
<L>Late not &thorn;i werkis preue &thorn;ee nyce,</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou euere be founden trewe."</L>
<L>"Fare weel Conscience, weelcome Coueitise!</L>
<L N="328">To be richee now y wole pursue."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod Conscience, "&thorn;at is idil bisynesse,<MILESTONE N="135" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Nedelees richesse to gadre soo;</L>
<L>Ouerhope is &thorn;e cause y-wisse,</L>
<L N="332">He wene&thorn; ameende al er he goo."</L>
<L>Wanhope sei&thorn;, "kepe weel &thorn;is,</L>
<L>For &thorn;e world wole faile us two."</L>
<L>Quod Conscience, "chaunge not heuen blis</L>
<L N="336">For helle peyne, sorowe, and woo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"IN sixti &yogh;eere myn age is pi&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Myn i&yogh;en daswen, myn heer is hoore;</L>
<L>In my werkis y haue febil in-si&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="340">I fynde no vertu in my stoore.
<PB REF="00000087.tif" N="69"></L>
<L>How schal y reckene with god almy&yogh;t?</L>
<L>I am aschamed wondir soore."</L>
<L>Quod Conscience, "certis it were ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="344">To be holi now or neuere moore."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod &yogh;outhe to age, "what doist &thorn;ou now&thorn;e?</L>
<L>Hange up &thorn;in hachet &amp; take &thorn;i reste;</L>
<L>&THORN;e sunne is past fer bi &thorn;e sowthe,</L>
<L N="348">And hi&yogh;eth swi&thorn;e in to &thorn;e weste."</L>
<L>Quod man, "y serued &thorn;ee in &yogh;oug&thorn;e<MILESTONE N="136" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And al &thorn;e tyme myne eruest leste,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sorowe of herte &amp; schrifte of mou&thorn;e</L>
<L N="352">To god &yogh;it haue y kepte &thorn;e beste."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Age, calle a&yogh;en &yogh;istirday to-morne;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. to-morowe]</NOTE></L>
<L>And alle &thorn;i werkis, bigynne hem newe."</L>
<L>Quod man, "&thorn;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou speke in scorne,</L>
<L N="356">&THORN;ou techist me good &thorn;at y neuere knewe;</L>
<L>I wole bi&thorn;inke me on my werkis biforn,</L>
<L>Do almes dede, praie, &amp; rewe,</L>
<L>And goddis mercy schal ynne my corn,</L>
<L N="360">And fede me wi&thorn; &thorn;at &thorn;at y neuere sewe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"IN &yogh;oug&thorn;e whanne y was wilde &amp; stronge,</L>
<L>&THORN;e fals world fair dide me wowe,</L>
<L>Me &thorn;ou&yogh;t ech worde a myrie songe,</L>
<L N="364">Wi&thorn; pipis, and dauncis, &amp; mir&thorn;is y-nowe.</L>
<L>Now sei&thorn; he, he loued me to longe,</L>
<L>For myn heer bigynne&thorn; to blowe;</L>
<L>To &thorn;i mercy, lord, me vndirfonge,</L>
<L N="368">&THORN;e tyde is ebbid, &amp; no more wole flowe."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;e candel of lijf &thorn;i soule dide tende:<MILESTONE N="137" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>To li&yogh;te &thorn;ee hom," resoun dide saye.</L>
<L>"Miche of my candel in waaste y spende,</L>
<L N="372">Manye wickid windis ha&thorn; wastid it away;
<PB REF="00000088.tif" N="70"></L>
<L>Vnne&thorn;e y holde my candelis eende,</L>
<L>It is past euensonge of my day;</L>
<L>To reepe myn heruest, whidir mai y winde?</L>
<L N="376">Mi londis of vertues liggen al lay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&para; Whanne &yogh;ou&thorn;e was maistir, y was page,</L>
<L>We lyueden myche in &thorn;e feendis seruice,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; rere souperis and wickid outrage,</L>
<L N="380">Ligge longe in bed, loo&thorn;e to arise.</L>
<L>Now haue y nou&yogh;t but wisschis to wage,</L>
<L>And myche repreef amonge &thorn;e wijse;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei &thorn;at loueden me in &yogh;ou&thorn;e, hatiden me in age,</L>
<L N="384">And vnkindeli me diden dispice.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"NOw haue y greet meruaile</L>
<L>&THORN;e world to man whi it was wrou&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Fele temptaciouns now me assaile,</L>
<L N="388">I haue no reste for chaunge of &thorn;ou&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Whanne y schulde reste y haue greet merueile;<MILESTONE N="138" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>In bed to sleepe whanne y am brou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>I se but drede and greet bataile</L>
<L N="392">Al mannys lijfe, and it be sou&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Thus &thorn;e fals world ha&thorn; forsaken me;</L>
<L>For waste of hise goodis he accusi&thorn; me;</L>
<L>&THORN;e synnes &thorn;at y loued, now haten me,</L>
<L N="396">To Conscience &thorn;ei adwiten me;</L>
<L>Feendis &thorn;reten faste to take me,</L>
<L>And steren helle houndis to bite me;</L>
<L>Dee&thorn; sei&thorn;, my breed he ha&thorn; baken me;</L>
<L N="400">Now schake&thorn; he his spere to smite me.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;us y am huntid as an herte to a-bay,</L>
<L>I not whidir y may me turne,</L>
<L>Myne enemyes my&yogh;tili me assay,</L>
<L N="404">I waxe feble and vnourne;
<PB REF="00000089.tif" N="71"></L>
<L>To flee to god is my beste way,</L>
<L>&THORN;ere schal y in no poynt spurne;</L>
<L>Lord! now socour me &thorn;at beste may,</L>
<L N="408">In &thorn;in herte blood, &thorn;at holi bourne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod &yogh;ou&thorn;e to age, "y &thorn;ee forsake,<MILESTONE N="139" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;i frendis deien, &thorn;i streng&thorn;e doo&thorn; faile,</L>
<L>&THORN;i si&yogh;te and heeryng bigynne&thorn; to slake,</L>
<L N="412">&THORN;ee needi&thorn; helpe and good counsaile;</L>
<L>God-is seruauntis in areest ha&thorn; &thorn;ee take</L>
<L>Til dee&thorn; on &thorn;ee haue doon bataile;</L>
<L>&THORN;i reckenyng bi tyme bisili &thorn;ou make,</L>
<L N="416">Or &thorn;e deuel bringe &thorn;e countirtaile."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;ou&yogh; dee&thorn; be eende of worldlis woo,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne dee&thorn; is euere mannys freende;</L>
<L>thou&yogh; soulis in helle be ponischid soo,</L>
<L N="420">Dee&thorn; come&thorn; not &thorn;ere to make noon eende;</L>
<L>Dee&thorn; maki&thorn; soulis to heuen to goo,</L>
<L>But in to heuen dee&thorn; may not wende,</L>
<L>For dee&thorn; is flemyd heuene froo,</L>
<L N="424">Dee&thorn; is sugett to god to bende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"NOw y am sixti &yogh;eere and ten,</L>
<L>&YOGH;onge folke Y fynde my foo,</L>
<L>Where euere &thorn;ei pleie, leepe, or renne,</L>
<L N="428">&THORN;ei &thorn;inken in her weie Y goo;</L>
<L>And whanne y mete with olde men,<MILESTONE N="140" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>I pleyne '&thorn;is world is chaungid soo;'</L>
<L>Noon o&thorn;er bote is but seelde when</L>
<L N="432">Ech man telli&thorn; o&thorn;ir his woo."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod &yogh;ou&thorn;e to age, "y &thorn;ee a-peele</L>
<L>And &thorn;at bifore oure god y-wis;</L>
<L>I lente &thorn;ee streng&thorn;e, bewte, &amp; heele,&mdash;</L>
<L N="436">&THORN;ese percellis ben of heuen blis,&mdash;
<PB REF="00000090.tif" N="72"></L>
<L>Corage, li&yogh;tnesse, freendis, &amp; weele;</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ese &thorn;ou hast wastide amys</L>
<L>From wijsdom in-to folies feele:</L>
<L N="440">God wole haue rekenyng of al &thorn;is.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&THORN;ine heerynge and &thorn;in i&yogh;e si&yogh;te</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou hast wastide in veynglory;</L>
<L>&THORN;i mou&thorn;e to wronge a&yogh;en ri&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="444">In fals oo&thorn;is and foule gloteny;</L>
<L>&THORN;in hondis to robbe and to fi&yogh;te;</L>
<L>&THORN;i streng&thorn;e &thorn;ou wastidist in tyrauntry;</L>
<L>&THORN;i feet in derknesse oute of li&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="448">&THORN;i bewte &thorn;ou wastidist in lecchery."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod man, "y was gouerned Bitwene two &thorn;euis,<MILESTONE N="141" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;ei stale on me: Y was stalwor&thorn;e &amp; white;</L>
<L>Whanne my leepis weren brou&yogh;t to preuis,</L>
<L N="452">I wondre on my silf Y was so li&yogh;te.</L>
<L>&YOGH;oug&thorn;e staale from me; &thorn;at soore me greuis;</L>
<L>Age steele&thorn; on me bo&thorn;e day and ny&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Mi &yogh;oug&thorn;e, my vertu, al from me meuis;</L>
<L N="456">Now wondre y on my silf where is my my&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"&para; &YOGH;oug&thorn;e staale from me, Y was stalwor&thorn;e &amp; li&yogh;te;</L>
<L>And age steele&thorn; on me Fil&thorn;is to weelde;</L>
<L>&YOGH;oug&thorn;e steeli&thorn; from me, Y &yogh;eede up ri&yogh;te;</L>
<L N="460">Age steele&thorn; on me, Y bowe and &yogh;eelde;</L>
<L>&YOGH;oug&thorn;e ha&thorn; stolen from me My leepis li&yogh;te;</L>
<L>Age steeli&thorn; on me, Y wexe on-mylde;</L>
<L>&YOGH;oug&thorn;e steele&thorn; my corage To pleie &amp; fi&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="464">Age is so on me stoolen &THORN;at y mote to god me &yogh;ilde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"NOw y am euene of &yogh;eeris fore scoure,</L>
<L>So manye wyntir Y am oolde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ere y was wonte To leepe bifore,</L>
<L N="468">Fer aboute now My wei y hoolde:
<PB REF="00000091.tif" N="73"></L>
<L>My backe bowi&thorn;, myn i&yogh;en ben soore,<MILESTONE N="142" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Myn hoote blood is kelid coolde:</L>
<L>Alas! Conscience! to litil y toke &thorn;i loore,</L>
<L N="472">&THORN;e talis &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast ofte me toolde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod Conscience, "where haddist &thorn;ou &thorn;at speche?</L>
<L>&THORN;i li&yogh;te leepis foonde to preue;</L>
<L>&THORN;e put of &thorn;e stoon &thorn;ou maist not reche,</L>
<L N="476">To litil my&yogh;te is in &thorn;i sleue.</L>
<L>In youg&thorn;e whanne y dide &thorn;ee teche,</L>
<L>Foule &thorn;ou me &thorn;anne dedist repreue;</L>
<L>I &thorn;anke god of &thorn;i good leeche."</L>
<L N="480">"&YOGH;he, Conscience, now to &thorn;i wordis y leeue."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"NOw foure score &yogh;eeris is past,</L>
<L>Mi lijf is but traueil &amp; woo,</L>
<L>Fer in to rereage y am cast,</L>
<L N="484">Into ten &yogh;eer and moo.</L>
<L>My lymes foulden &thorn;at weren fast,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; staffe in honde now y goo;</L>
<L>My redy speche may not last,</L>
<L N="488">So my tee&thorn; ben fallen me fro.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Ful of fleissche Y was to fele,<MILESTONE N="143" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Now may I nei&thorn;er stonde ne goon;</L>
<L>It ha&thorn; now lefte me euery dele,</L>
<L N="492">Me is lefte But skyn &amp; boon.</L>
<L>Now y am vndre Fortunes whele,</L>
<L>My frendis forsaken me Euerychoon,</L>
<L>And alle &thorn;e synnes Y loued so weel,</L>
<L N="496">Now wote y weel &thorn;ei been my foon."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod course of kinde, "What helpi&thorn;, y wende,</L>
<L>&THORN;i wissching And &thorn;in hadde-y-wist?</L>
<L>What maist &thorn;ou On &thorn;o wordis spende,</L>
<L N="500">It is ful febil In &thorn;i fist.
<PB REF="00000092.tif" N="74"></L>
<L>Now alle men waiten aftir &thorn;in eende;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou deye, &thorn;ou schalt not be myste;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou combrest bo&thorn;e foo &amp; frende,</L>
<L N="504">&THORN;i mylle ha&thorn; grounde &thorn;i laste griste."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;re deedli synnes maden her moone,</L>
<L>"We forsaken man in age."</L>
<L>Quod Pride, "y am from him goon,</L>
<L N="508">For Pride in age Doi&thorn; disperage."</L>
<L>Quod leccherie, "He loue&thorn; to lie a-loone;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; he wolde do, him wanti&thorn; corage."<MILESTONE N="144" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Quod Glotenie, "he is but felle &amp; boone,</L>
<L N="512">He loue&thorn; more mesure &thorn;an outrage."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod Envie, "age hath no my&yogh;te</L>
<L>Ne richesse, lenger me to fynde."</L>
<L>Quod wra&thorn;&thorn;e, "age may not fi&yogh;te</L>
<L N="516">&THORN;ou&yogh; he be angri, bi course of kynde."</L>
<L>Quod Slou&thorn;e, "age my chaumbre ha&thorn; di&yogh;te,</L>
<L>And calle&thorn; me ease in his mynde."</L>
<L>Quod Coueitise, "age ha&thorn; me hi&yogh;te;</L>
<L N="520">Suget to me he doo&thorn; him binde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"<B>I</B> knowe," quod ouerhope, "fleissch is freele,</L>
<L>Of oolde and &yogh;onge, of man, of childe;</L>
<L>In ouerhope &thorn;ei wasten her weele,</L>
<L N="524">And in diuerse werkis ful wylde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ei ouerhope euere to lyue in heele,</L>
<L>From age &amp; sijknesse &thorn;ei wene&thorn; hem schilde,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne come&thorn; sijknesse, &amp; printi&thorn; his seele."</L>
<L N="528">Quod wanhope "&thorn;an y make him mylde;</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"<B>I</B> bidde him horde, and richesse saue,<MILESTONE N="145" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>For wanhope after mischife doi&thorn; waite,</L>
<L>Whanne sijknesse come&thorn; men to craue,"</L>
<L N="532">Quod ouerhope, "&thorn;an y flatir, &amp; sumtyme flaite,
<PB REF="00000093.tif" N="75"></L>
<L>'&THORN;ou schalt lyue, and &thorn;i silf it haue.' "</L>
<L>"&YOGH;he," sei&thorn; wanhope, "kepe it straite,</L>
<L>Of good hope no councell &thorn;ou craue</L>
<L N="536">Til dee&thorn; &thorn;ee caste with a trippe of dissaite."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod wanhope, "a gospel y radde:</L>
<L>To telle it &thorn;ee y wole bigynne,</L>
<L>'If a man in synne be sadde</L>
<L N="540">Ech day newe, and lie&thorn; &thorn;er-inne,</L>
<L>Of such a man god is moore gladde</L>
<L>&THORN;an of a childe &thorn;at neuere dide synne.' "</L>
<L>Quod Conscience, "he wolde make &thorn;e madde</L>
<L N="544">To repente &thorn;ee not, ne neuere blynne."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod Conscience to wanhope, "I-wys</L>
<L>&THORN;ou liest, y hate &thorn;e &thorn;erfore;</L>
<L>I knowe &thorn;e gospel, it sei&thorn; &thorn;is,</L>
<L N="548">'If a man haue synned longe bifore,</L>
<L>And axe mercy And a-mende his mys,</L>
<L>Repente, and wilne to synne no more,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at man god gladder is<MILESTONE N="146" UNIT="page"></L>
<L N="552">&THORN;an of a child synlees y-bore.' "</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod wanhope, "a gospel y radde;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? redde:537]</NOTE></L>
<L>What it mene&thorn; y can expownde,</L>
<L>Ech man schal haue peine or meede,</L>
<L N="556">In &thorn;ou&yogh;te or dede as he is founde;</L>
<L>He ha&thorn; not &yogh;it repentid his dede,</L>
<L>He si&yogh;ke&thorn; for synnes ben not vnbounde;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; mercy come, he schal not spede,</L>
<L N="560">For in daunger of wanhope he is bounde."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod Conscience, "&thorn;ou dotid hoore!</L>
<L>God-is mercy &thorn;ou woldist distroie;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou wenest &thorn;i wickidnesse were moore</L>
<L N="564">&thorn;an god-is goodnesse &amp; his mercie.
<PB REF="00000094.tif" N="76"></L>
<L>For if a man be woundid soore,</L>
<L>And axe no medicine, him liste te deie;</L>
<L>God ha&thorn; mercies y-now in stoore</L>
<L N="568">For a &thorn;ousand worldis &thorn;at mercie wole crie."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"MEkenes, Pacience, and Charitee,</L>
<L>&YOGH;e &thorn;at weren my frendis dere,</L>
<L>Mesure, Bisinesse, and Chastitee,</L>
<L N="572">At &thorn;is mystire come&thorn; me neere."</L>
<L>Quod Conscience, "&thorn;ou flemed us from &thorn;ee;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou woldist not oure loore leere."<MILESTONE N="147" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Quod richelees, "loo, heere my meynee!</L>
<L N="576">&THORN;e synnes &thorn;at &thorn;ou louedist &amp; seruedist, lo hem here!"</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Myne age is now an hundrid &yogh;eere;</L>
<L>Litil y drinke, and lesse y ete,</L>
<L>On my backe I bere my beere,</L>
<L N="580">And alle my frendis me for&yogh;ete,</L>
<L>Fayn &thorn;ei wolde &thorn;at y deed were,</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; sorewful wordis &thorn;ei doon me &thorn;retee,</L>
<L>And seyn, 'for y am so longe heere,</L>
<L N="584">Whanne y come hoome y schal be beete.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>NOw mote y leie for&thorn; my necke,</L>
<L>For dee&thorn; his swerd out ha&thorn; lau&yogh;te;</L>
<L>But I deliuere weel &thorn;is checke,</L>
<L N="588">I leese my game at &thorn;is drau&yogh;te.</L>
<L>Ful of synne is my secke;</L>
<L>To &thorn;e preest y wole schewe &thorn;at frau&yogh;te,</L>
<L>Mi schip is chargid, al goo&thorn; to wrecke</L>
<L N="592">But if god of merci be wi&thorn; me sau&yogh;te.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This worlde ha&thorn; me in awaite,</L>
<L>And biddi&thorn; me quite &thorn;at is past;</L>
<L>My fleissche in ouerhope wolde me faite,</L>
<L N="596">And into wanhope it wolde me caste.
<PB REF="00000095.tif" N="77"></L>
<L>Helle houndis berken and baite,<MILESTONE N="148" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&THORN;e feendis writi&thorn; my synnes faste,</L>
<L>And dee&thorn; me waiti&thorn; with a trippe of dissaite;</L>
<L N="600">These sixe maken me soore agaste."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;anne come&thorn; for&thorn; good hope:</L>
<L>To saue man he wolde fonde;</L>
<L>"&THORN;ou wronge weuere ouerhope!</L>
<L N="604">I make him free, &thorn;ou woldist make him bonde;</L>
<L>I schal conclude &thorn;ee, &thorn;ou wanhope,</L>
<L>Wile good fei&thorn; wole with me stoonde;</L>
<L>Hooli writte sei&thorn;, 'in god y hoope,</L>
<L N="608">His merci is ouer &thorn;e werkis of his honde.' "</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod good fei&thorn;, "for &thorn;e litil while</L>
<L>&THORN;at now heere [&thorn;ou] hast serued me,</L>
<L>I wole &thorn;ee kepe from al perile,</L>
<L N="612">And make pees bitwene god &amp; &thorn;ee;</L>
<L>And ouerhope, for al his gile,</L>
<L>From &thorn;in herte y schal do him flee;</L>
<L>And wanhope also y wole exile,</L>
<L N="616">For he is not of oure fraternitee."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Quod &thorn;e worlde, "Y wole hise dettis quyte,</L>
<L>And oute of his daunger me hy&yogh;e;</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; my fleissche berke, he schal not bitee,</L>
<L N="620">From his lustis y wole him tye;</L>
<L>I wole waissche a-Wey<MILESTONE N="149" UNIT="page"> &thorn;at feendis write</L>
<L>With sorowe of herte and teer of y&yogh;e,</L>
<L>But with dee&thorn; y wole not dispuite,</L>
<L N="624">But make me cleene, and leerne to deie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God! sowe &thorn;i merci amonge my seede,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne schal it growe &thorn;ou&yogh; y sowe late,</L>
<L>And Repentaunce my corne schal weede,</L>
<L N="628">And make good pees &thorn;ere was hate.
<PB REF="00000096.tif" N="78"></L>
<L>&THORN;e comaundementis &thorn;at god bede,</L>
<L>&THORN;at is &thorn;e locke of heuen &yogh;ate;</L>
<L>Seuene werkis of mercy, and &thorn;e crede,</L>
<L N="632">&THORN;ese keies schullen late me in &thorn;erate."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now haue &yogh;e herde of &yogh;oug&thorn;is delice;</L>
<L>And age in kynde, sijke, &amp; woo;</L>
<L>Knowing of uertu &amp; of vice;</L>
<L N="636">Good aungil, &amp; wickid sreende, &amp; foo;</L>
<L>And vndirstondinge to be wijs.</L>
<L>Now in &thorn;is mirrour loke &yogh;ou soo;</L>
<L>In &yogh;oure free wille &thorn;e choice lijs,</L>
<L N="640">To heuen or helle whi&thorn;ir &yogh;e wille goo.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The worlde, &thorn;e fleissche, &amp; &thorn;e feende,</L>
<L>In temptacioun doi&thorn; us chase;</L>
<L>Bid repentaunce to merci beende,</L>
<L N="644">And waissche us at &thorn;e welle of grace.</L>
<L>Praie we to god graunte us good eende,<MILESTONE N="150" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>And in heuen to haue a place,</L>
<L>&THORN;at after oure dee&thorn; we mowen &thorn;idir wende,</L>
<L N="648">And in perfi&yogh;t loue se his fair face.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now, leeue freendis, greete and smale,</L>
<L>&THORN;at haue herde &thorn;is trete,</L>
<L>Praie for &thorn;e soule &thorn;at wroot &thorn;is tale</L>
<L N="652">A Pater noster, &amp; an aue</L>
<L>To marie modir, maiden free,</L>
<L>As sche bare a childe Coumforte to us,</L>
<L>On &thorn;at soule haue pitee</L>
<L N="656">If &thorn;e will be of crist ihesus.<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Stans Puer</I>, printed in <I>Babees Boke, &amp;c.</I>, p. 27 follows here.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>amen.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000097.tif" N="79">
<HEAD>God send us Paciens in oure Oolde Age!</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Pages</I> 113-17, <I>written without breaks. Rymes abababab, bcbc.</I>]</P><P>[<I>Stans Puer</I>, printed in <I>Babees Boke, &amp;c.</I>, p. 27 follows here.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>FRom &thorn;e tyme &thorn;at we were bore<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. born]</NOTE></L>
<L>oure &yogh;ou&thorn;e passi&thorn; from day to day,</L>
<L>And age encreesi&thorn; moore &amp; moore,</L>
<L N="4">&amp; so doi&thorn; it now, &thorn;e sothe to say:</L>
<L>At euery hour a poynt is y-loore,</L>
<L>So fast goo&thorn; oure &yogh;ou&thorn;e away,</L>
<L>And &yogh;ou&thorn;e wole come a&yogh;en no moore,</L>
<L N="8">But age wole make us bo&thorn;e blak &amp; gray.</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore take hede bo&thorn;e ny&yogh;t &amp; day</L>
<L>How fast &yogh;oure &yogh;ou&thorn;e doo&thorn; asswage;</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e &yogh;onge &amp; oolde, lete us praie</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;at god send us paciens in oure oolde age.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Age wole take from us oure my&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at in oure &yogh;ou&thorn;e to us was lent;</L>
<L>And also &thorn;e cleernesse of oure syght</L>
<L N="16">And oure heerynge schal be faynt.</L>
<L>&THORN;anne schulen we be heuy &thorn;at eer were li&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Bicause &thorn;at &yogh;ou&thorn;e is from us went,</L>
<L>And &thorn;anne wole men do us no ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="20">But al contrarie to oure entent,</L>
<L>And sikenes wole do us greet turment</L>
<L>Whom dee&thorn; wole sende on his message;</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e &thorn;e best ameendement</L>
<L N="24">is &thorn;anne pacience in oure olde age.<MILESTONE N="114" UNIT="page">
<PB REF="00000098.tif" N="80"></L>
<L>Oure body wole icche, oure bonis wole ake,</L>
<L>oure owne fleisch wole ben oure foo;</L>
<L>Oure heed, oure hondis, &thorn;o wolen schake,</L>
<L N="28">And oure leggis wole tremble where we go;</L>
<L>Oure bonis wole drie as doo&thorn; a stake,</L>
<L>And in oure bodi we schulen be woo,</L>
<L>Oure nose, oure chekis, wolen wexe al blake,</L>
<L N="32">&amp; oure glad chere wole sade us fro;</L>
<L>And whanne oure tee&thorn; ben goon also,</L>
<L>Oure tunge schal lese his fair langage:</L>
<L>Praie we for us silf &amp; o&thorn;er moo</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at god sende us paciens in oure olde age!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Oure freendis &thorn;at schulden loue us best,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne wole &thorn;ei haue us but in hate,</L>
<L>In freendschip is &thorn;er noon o&thorn;er trust,</L>
<L N="40">&amp; &thorn;erof be we waare to late.</L>
<L>&THORN;an may we synge of had y wist,</L>
<L>Oure feynt freendis han us forsake,</L>
<L>And also we schulen go vnkist</L>
<L N="44">bo&thorn;e at &thorn;e dore &amp; at &thorn;e gate;</L>
<L>And for al &thorn;e cheer &thorn;at we can make,</L>
<L>&THORN;an is <MILESTONE N="115" UNIT="page">no ioie of oure visage:</L>
<L>Whanne oure bewte schal aslake,</L>
<L N="48">god send us paciens in oure olde age!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; we schulen be so angri euermore,</L>
<L>we wolden ben awreke of euery wrong,</L>
<L>&THORN;anne summe wolen scorne us &thorn;erfore,</L>
<L N="52">&amp; summe wole seie we lyue to long;</L>
<L>Oure sorowe wole &thorn;an sitte us so soore</L>
<L>Oure stomak wole no mete fonge;</L>
<L>&amp; eueri day more &amp; more</L>
<L N="56">Of sorewe &amp; care schal be oure song.</L>
<L>whanne we were bo&thorn;e hool &amp; strong</L>
<L>we were to wie[l]de, &amp; wold out rage,
<PB REF="00000099.tif" N="81"></L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore lete us praie among</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at god send us paciens in oure olde age.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For &thorn;an wole no &thorn;ing us availe</L>
<L>but oure bedis and oure crucche,</L>
<L>for wordli wel&thorn;e wole fade &amp; faile,</L>
<L N="64">And &thorn;erfore truste we it not to myche;</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an wole sijknes us assaile</L>
<L>Til it ha&thorn; made us lijk a wrecche,</L>
<L>&amp; &thorn;an may we do no greet traueile</L>
<L N="68">But<MILESTONE N="116" UNIT="page"> summtyme grone, &amp; sumtyme grucche,</L>
<L>And sumtyme clawe for scabbe &amp; icche</L>
<L>Whanne age ha&thorn; us at his auauntage:</L>
<L>Who-so lyue&thorn; long schal be such;</L>
<L N="72">God sende us paciens in oure olde age!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Al &thorn;at we haue lyued heere,</L>
<L>It is but as a dreem y-met,</L>
<L>For now it is as it neuere were,</L>
<L N="76">And so is it &thorn;at is comyng &yogh;it.</L>
<L>Ful fast we drawen to oure beere,</L>
<L>In sorewe &amp; drede we schulen be sett.</L>
<L>Of oolde men &thorn;e &yogh;onge may lere,</L>
<L N="80">And fewe &thorn;er ben &thorn;at doon &thorn;e bett;</L>
<L>For &thorn;e feend ha&thorn; cau&yogh;t hem in his nett,</L>
<L>And holdi&thorn; hem fast in bondage</L>
<L>For &thorn;ei schulden not dispose her witt</L>
<L N="84">To haue pacience in her oolde age.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;anne schulen we se &thorn;at worldli blis</L>
<L>Is but a &thorn;ing of vanite,</L>
<L>And it maki&thorn; men to do amys</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at ben in weel&thorn;e &amp; greet bewte;</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfor, lord, good ri&yogh;t it is</L>
<L>With oure owne staf chastisid to be:</L>
<L>Lord! &yogh;eue us grace to &thorn;inke on &thorn;is,<MILESTONE N="117" UNIT="page"></L>
<L N="92">As &thorn;ou bou&yogh;t us alle upon a tree,
<PB REF="00000100.tif" N="82"></L>
<L>And &thorn;at we may in charite</L>
<L>Weel passe ouer &thorn;is passage</L>
<L>In-to &thorn;e blis &thorn;at euere schal be,</L>
<L N="96">Whanne we ben passid oure oolde age.<NOTE PLACE="end">["Bothe &yogh;onge &amp; oolde," or "Se what oure lord suffride for oure sake," printed above, pp. 32-4, follows here.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000101.tif" N="83">
<HEAD>This World is but a Vanyte. AN OLD MAN'S LAMENT.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab</I>. 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 58; <I>written without breaks.</I></P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AS Y GAn wandre in my walkinge</L>
<L>Bisidis an holt vndir an hille,</L>
<L>Y say an oolde man sitte wepinge:</L>
<L N="4">With si&yogh;ynge sore he seide me tille,</L>
<L>&para; "Sumtime y hadde &thorn;e world at wille,</L>
<L>With ricchesse &amp; with rialte,</L>
<L>And now it is turned al to ille;</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e worlde is but a vanyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>My silf I likne vnto &thorn;e morewe:</L>
<L>Whanne y was child, &amp; bor[e]n bare,</L>
<L>Mi modir for me suffride sorewe</L>
<L N="12">With gruntyngis gril &amp; si&yogh;inge sare;</L>
<L>&para; On me was nie&thorn;er wem ne hore;</L>
<L>But si&thorn;en in synne y haue be;</L>
<L>Now y am oolde y wepe &thorn;erfore;</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;is world is but a vanyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At mydmore y lerned to go,</L>
<L>And plaied as children doon in <MILESTONE N="59" UNIT="page">strete;</L>
<L>&THORN;e kinde of childhode y dide also,</L>
<L N="20">Wi&thorn; my felawis to fi&yogh;te and &thorn;rete.</L>
<L>&para; Al &thorn;at y dide, it &thorn;ou&yogh;te me swete,</L>
<L>For al &thorn;is childhode tau&yogh;te me;</L>
<L>Now y am oolde, &thorn;erfore y wepe;</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;is worlde is but a vanite.
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="84"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At vndren to scole y was sett</L>
<L>To lerne lore, as o&thorn;ir doo&thorn;;</L>
<L>Whanne my maistir wolde me bet,</L>
<L N="28">I wolde him curse, y was ful wroo&thorn;.</L>
<L>&para; To lerne good y was ful loo&thorn;,</L>
<L>I &thorn;ou&yogh;te on ioie &amp; ioilite;</L>
<L>Now certis, for to seie &thorn;e soo&thorn;,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;is world is but a vanyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At mydday y was dubbid kny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In route y lerned for to ryde;</L>
<L>Was &thorn;er noon so hardi a wi&yogh;t</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;at in bataile durste me abide.</L>
<L>&para; Where is bicome now al my pride,</L>
<L>Mi booldnes, &amp; my fair bewte?</L>
<L>Now from dee&thorn; may y me not hide;</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;is world is but a vanyte.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At hi&yogh; noon y was crowned king,</L>
<L>&THORN;is world was oonli at my wille;</L>
<L>Euere to <MILESTONE N="60" UNIT="page">lyue was my liking,</L>
<L N="44">And alle my lustis to fulfille.</L>
<L>&para; Now age is cropen on me ful stille,</L>
<L>And maki&thorn; me oold &amp; blac of ble,</L>
<L>And y go downeward wi&thorn; &thorn;e hille;</L>
<L N="48">&THORN;is World is but a vanite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At mydouernoon y droupid faste,</L>
<L>Mi lust &amp; liking wente away;</L>
<L>From iolite myn hert is paste</L>
<L N="52">From rialte &amp; riche aray.</L>
<L>&para; Mannis lijf here is but a day</L>
<L>A&yogh;ens &thorn;e lijf &thorn;at euere schal be;</L>
<L>And oo &thorn;ing y dare weel say,</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at &thorn;is world is but a vanyte.
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="85"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>At euensong tyme y wax ful coold,</L>
<L>And bigan to go bi staue;</L>
<L>Now is dee&thorn; on me ful boold,</L>
<L N="60">And for his rent he wole me craue.</L>
<L>&para; Whanne y am deed &amp; leid in graue,</L>
<L>&THORN;er is no &thorn;ing &thorn;anne &thorn;at saue&thorn; me</L>
<L>But good or yuel &thorn;at y do haue;</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;is world is but a vanite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thus is &thorn;e day come to ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at me lo&thorn;ith of my lyuynge,</L>
<L>And doolful dee&thorn; to me is di&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="68">And in coold <MILESTONE N="61" UNIT="page">clay now schal y clinge."</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;us an oold man y herde mornynge</L>
<L>Biside an holte vndir a tree.</L>
<L>God graunte us his blis euerlastinge!</L>
<L N="72">&THORN;is world is but a vanite.<NOTE PLACE="end">["In a noon tijd," or "<I>Reuertere</I>," pp. 91-4 of this volume, follows here in the MS.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000104.tif" N="86">
<HEAD>This World is False and Vain.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>page</I> 32, <I>written without breaks.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whi is &thorn;is world biloued &thorn;at fals is &amp; veyn,</L>
<L>Si&thorn;en &thorn;at hise wel&thorn;is ben so vnserteyn?</L>
<L>&para; Al so soone hee passi&thorn; his power away</L>
<L N="4">As doo&thorn; a brokil poot &thorn;at freisch is and gay.</L>
<L>&para; Truste &yogh;e ra&thorn;er to lettris written withinne &thorn;is</L>
<L>&THORN;an to &thorn;is wrecchid world &thorn;at ful of synne is.</L>
<L>&para; It is fals in his biheeste, &amp; ri&yogh;t disceyuable;</L>
<L N="8">It ha&thorn; bigilid many a man, it is so vnstable.</L>
<L>&para; It is ra&thorn;ir <MILESTONE N="33" UNIT="page">to bileeue &thorn;e wageringe wijnde</L>
<L>&THORN;an &thorn;e chaungeable world &thorn;at maki&thorn; men so blinde.</L>
<L>&para; For whe&thorn;er &thorn;ou slepe or wake, &thorn;ou schalt fynde it fals.</L>
<L N="12">Bothe in hise bisinessis &amp; in hise lustis als.</L>
<L>&para; Telle me where is Salamon, sumtyme a king richee,</L>
<L>Or Sampson &thorn;e stronge to whom was no man liche?</L>
<L>&para; Or &thorn;e fair man absolon, merueilose in cheere,</L>
<L N="16">Or &thorn;e duke ionatas, a weel biloued fere?</L>
<L>&para; Where is bicome cesar, &thorn;at lorde was of al,</L>
<L>Or &thorn;e riche man clo&thorn;id in purpur &amp; in pal?</L>
<L>&para; Telle me where ys tullius, in eloquence so sweete,</L>
<L N="20">Or aristotil &thorn;e Filosofre with his witt so greete?
<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>&para; Where ben &thorn;ese wor&thorn;i &thorn;at were heere-to-forn?</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e kingis &amp; bischopis, her power is al lorn.</L>
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;ese greete princis with her power so hi&yogh;e</L>
<L N="24">Ben vanischid now a-way in twynke<MILESTONE N="34" UNIT="page"> ling of an y&yogh;e.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;e ioie of &thorn;is wrecchid world is a schoorte feeste,</L>
<L>And it is likened to a schadewe &thorn;at may not longe leste,</L>
<L>&para; And &yogh;it it drawi&thorn; man from heuen riche blis,</L>
<L N="28">And ofte tyme it maki&thorn; him to synne &amp; do a-mys.</L>
<L>&para; Calle no &thorn;ing &thorn;ine owne, &thorn;erfore, &thorn;at &thorn;ou maist heere leese;</L>
<L>For &thorn;at &thorn;e world ha&thorn; lent &thorn;ee, efte he wole it cese.</L>
<L>&para; Sette &thorn;in herte in heuene a-boue, &amp; &thorn;enke what ioie is &thorn;ere,</L>
<L N="32">And &thorn;us to dispise &thorn;e world y rede &thorn;at &thorn;ou lere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &thorn;at art but wormes meete, poudre, &amp; dust,</L>
<L>To enhaunce &thorn;i silfe in pride sett not &thorn;i lust.</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;ou woost not to-day &thorn;at &thorn;ou schalt lyue to-morowe,</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;erfore do &thorn;ou euere weel, And &thorn;anne schalt &thorn;ou not sorowe.</L>
<L>&para; It were ful ioieful &amp; sweete, lordschipe to haue,</L>
<L>If so &thorn;at lordschip mi&yogh;te a man fro<MILESTONE N="35" UNIT="page"> dee&thorn; saue,</L>
<L>&para; But for as myche as a man schal deie at &thorn;e laste,</L>
<L N="40">It is noo worschip, but a charge, lordschip to taaste.</L>
<L><B>Omnia terrena</B></L>
<L><B>Per vices sunt aliena:</B></L>
<L><B>nescio sunt cuius;</B></L>
<L N="44"><B>mea nunc, cras huius et huius.</B></L>
<L><B>Dic, homo, quid speres,</B></L>
<L><B>si mundo totus adheres;</B></L>
<L><B>nulla tecum feres,</B></L>
<L N="48"><B>licet tu solus haberes.</B>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000106.tif" N="88">
<HEAD>Earth.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P><B>Whanne liif is moost loued, and dee&thorn; is moost hatid: &thorn;anne doo&thorn; dee&thorn; drawe his draw&yogh;t, and maki&thorn; man ful nakid. De terra plasmasti me, &amp;c.</B></P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ER&thorn;e out of er&thorn;e is wondirly wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Er&thorn;e of er&thorn;e ha&thorn; gete a dignyte of nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Er&thorn;e upon er&thorn;e ha&thorn; sett al his &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="4">How &thorn;at er&thorn;e upon er&thorn;e may be hi&yogh; brou&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Er&thorn;e upon er&thorn;e wold be a king;</L>
<L>But how er&thorn;e schal to er&thorn;e, &thorn;enki&thorn; he no <MILESTONE N="36" UNIT="page">&thorn;ing;</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;at er&thorn;e biddi&thorn; er&thorn;e hise rentis hom bring,</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;an schal er&thorn;e out of er&thorn;e haue a piteuous parting.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Er&thorn;e vpon er&thorn;e wynne&thorn; castels &amp; touris,</L>
<L>&THORN;an sei&thorn; er&thorn;e to er&thorn;e 'now is &thorn;is al houris:'</L>
<L>Whanne er&thorn;e upon er&thorn;e ha&thorn; biggid up hise boure[s],</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;anne schal er&thorn;e upon er&thorn;e suffir scharpe schouris.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Er&thorn;e goo&thorn; vpon er&thorn;e as molde upon molde,</L>
<L>So goo&thorn; er&thorn;e upon er&thorn;e al gliteringe in golde,</L>
<L>Like as er&thorn;e vnto er&thorn;e neuere go schulde;</L>
<L N="16">And &yogh;it schal er&thorn;e vn-to er&thorn;e ra&thorn;er &thorn;an he wolde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O &thorn;ou wrecchid er&thorn;e &thorn;at on er&thorn;e traueilist ny&yogh;t and day
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="89"></L>
<L>To florische &thorn;e er&thorn;e, to peynte &thorn;e er&thorn;e with wan|towne aray;</L>
<L>&YOGH;it schal &thorn;ou, er&thorn;e, for al &thorn;i er&thorn;e, make &thorn;ou it neuere so queynte &amp; gay,</L>
<L N="20">Out of &thorn;is er&thorn;e into &thorn;e er&thorn;e, &thorn;ere to clinge as a clot of clay.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; O wrecchid man, whi art &thorn;ou proud<MILESTONE N="37" UNIT="page"> &thorn;at art of &thorn;e er&thorn;e makid?</L>
<L>Hider brou&yogh;ttist &thorn;ou no schroud, But poore come &thorn;ou, and nakid;</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;i soule is went out, &amp; &thorn;i bodi in er&thorn;e rakid,</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;an &thorn;i bodi &thorn;at was rank &amp; Vndeuout, Of alle men is bihatid.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Out of &thorn;is er&thorn;e cam to &thorn;is er&thorn;e &thorn;is wrecchid garnement;</L>
<L>To hide &thorn;is er&thorn;e, to happe &thorn;is er&thorn;e, to him was clo&thorn;inge lente;</L>
<L>Now goo&thorn; er&thorn;e upon er&thorn;e, ruli, raggid, and rent,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;erfore schal er&thorn;e vndir &thorn;e er&thorn;e haue hidiose turment.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whi &thorn;at er&thorn;e to myche loue&thorn; er&thorn;e, wondir me &thorn;ink,</L>
<L>Or whi &thorn;at er&thorn;e for superflue er&thorn;e to sore sweete wole or swynk;</L>
<L>For whanne &thorn;at er&thorn;e upon er&thorn;e is brou&yogh;t with|inne &thorn;e brink,</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;an schal er&thorn;e of &thorn;e er&thorn;e haue a rewful swynk.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Lo, er&thorn;e upon er&thorn;e, considere &thorn;ou may</L>
<L>How er&thorn;e come&thorn; into er&thorn;e nakid al way,<MILESTONE N="38" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>&para; Whi schulde er&thorn;e upon er&thorn;e go now so stoute or gay
<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="90"></L>
<L N="36">Whanne er&thorn;e schal passe out of er&thorn;e in so poore aray?</L>
<L>&para; Wolde god, &thorn;erfore, &thorn;is er&thorn;e, While &thorn;at he is upon &thorn;is er&thorn;e, Vpon &thorn;is wolde hertili &thorn;inke,</L>
<L>And how &thorn;e er&thorn;e out of &thorn;e erthe schal haue his a&yogh;en-risynge,</L>
<L>And &thorn;is er&thorn;e for &thorn;is er&thorn;e schal &yogh;eelde streite rekenyng;</L>
<L N="40">Schulde neuere &thorn;an &thorn;is er&thorn;e for &thorn;is er&thorn;e mysplese heuene king.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;erfore, &thorn;ou er&thorn;e, vpon er&thorn;e &thorn;at so wickidli hast wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>While &thorn;at &thorn;ou, er&thorn;e, art upon er&thorn;e, turne a&yogh;en &thorn;i &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And praie to &thorn;at god upon er&thorn;e &thorn;at al &thorn;e er&thorn;e ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at &thorn;ou, er&thorn;e upon er&thorn;e, to blis may be brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; O &thorn;ou lord &thorn;at madist &thorn;is er&thorn;e for &thorn;is er&thorn;e, &amp; suffridist heere peynes ille,</L>
<L>Lete neuere &thorn;is er&thorn;e for &thorn;is er&thorn;e myscheue ne spille,</L>
<L>But &thorn;at &thorn;is er&thorn;e on &thorn;is<MILESTONE N="39" UNIT="page"> er&thorn;e be euere worchinge &thorn;i wille,</L>
<L N="48">So &thorn;at &thorn;is er&thorn;e from &thorn;is er&thorn;e may stie up to &thorn;in hi&yogh; hille.<NOTE PLACE="end"><P>[See an earlier Poem on <I>Earth</I>, in alternate English and Latin stanzas, in my edition of <I>Early English Poems</I> for the Philological Society, 1862, p. 150-2; and in <I>Reliqui&aelig; Antiqu&aelig;</I>, vol. ii. p. 216.</P><P><I>Memento homo quod cinis es</I>, and the Creed (pp. 101-3 of this Text), follow here in the MS.]</P></NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>A-M-E-N.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000109.tif" N="91">
<HEAD>Reuertere! (IN ENGLISCH TUNGE, TURNE A&yogh;EN!)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 61, <I>written without breaks.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN a noon tijd of a somers day</L>
<L>&THORN;e sunne schoon ful myrie &thorn;at tide,</L>
<L>I took myn hauk al for to play,</L>
<L N="4">Mi spaynel rennyng bi my side.</L>
<L>&para; A feisaunt hen soone gan y se,</L>
<L>Myn hound put up ful fair to fli&yogh;t,</L>
<L>I sente my faukun, y leet him flee:</L>
<L N="8">It was to me a deinteuose si&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; My faukun fli&yogh; faste to his pray,</L>
<L>I ran &thorn;o with a ful glad chere,</L>
<L>I spurned ful soone on my way,</L>
<L N="12">Mi leg was hent al with a brere.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is brere forso&thorn;e dide me grijf,</L>
<L>And soone it made me to turne a&yogh;e,</L>
<L>For he bare written in euery leef</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;is word in latyn, reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>I</B> knelid &amp; pullid &thorn;e brere me fro,</L>
<L>And redde &thorn;is word ful hendeli;</L>
<L>Myn herte fil doun vnto my too<MILESTONE N="62" UNIT="page"></L>
<L N="20">&THORN;at was woont sitten ful likingly.</L>
<L>&para; I leete myn hauke &amp; feysaunt fare,</L>
<L>Mi spaynel fil doun to my knee,
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="92"></L>
<L>&THORN;anne took y me wi&thorn; si&yogh;ynge sare</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;is new lessoun, reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Reuertere is as myche to say</L>
<L>In englisch tunge as, turne a&yogh;en:</L>
<L>Turne a&yogh;en, man, y &thorn;ee pray,</L>
<L N="28">And &thorn;inke hertili what &thorn;ou hast ben;</L>
<L>&para; Of &thorn;i liuynge be-&thorn;inke &thorn;ee rijfe,</L>
<L>In open &amp; in priuite.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ou may come to euerlastinge lijf,</L>
<L N="32">Take to &thorn;i mynde reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;is word made me to studie sore,</L>
<L>And binam me al my list;</L>
<L>How y hadde ledde my lijf so &yogh;ore,</L>
<L N="36">I putt it freischli in-to my brist.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;anne foond y me ful fer y-flet</L>
<L>Al from god in maieste;</L>
<L>Forso&thorn;e &thorn;ere schal no &thorn;ing me leett</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;at y ne wole synge reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This noon hete of &thorn;e someris day,</L>
<L>Whanne &thorn;e sunne moost<MILESTONE N="63" UNIT="page"> hi&yogh;est is,</L>
<L>It may be likened in good fay,</L>
<L N="44">For gregorie witnessi&thorn; weel &thorn;is;</L>
<L>&para; For in &yogh;onge age men wide doon walke</L>
<L>To dyuers synnis in fele degre:</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; a &yogh;ong man make a balke,</L>
<L N="48">&YOGH;it take to &thorn;i mynde reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For likinge blindi&thorn; many oon</L>
<L>&THORN;at he see&thorn; not him-silf y-wis,</L>
<L>And maki&thorn; his herte as hard as stoon;</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;anne &thorn;enki&thorn; he not on heuen blis;</L>
<L>&para; For danyel preue&thorn; it weel ri&yogh;tfulli,</L>
<L>As susannis storie telli&thorn; me,
<PB REF="00000111.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>Two preestis were deemed wor&thorn;ili;</L>
<L N="56">For likinge &thorn;ei knew not reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;ou&thorn;e beri&thorn; &thorn;e hauke upon his hond</L>
<L>Whanne ioilite for&yogh;eti&thorn; age:</L>
<L>This hauke is mannis herte, y vndirstonde,</L>
<L N="60">For it is &yogh;ong &amp; of hi&yogh; romage.</L>
<L>&para; He putti&thorn; his hauke fro his fist,</L>
<L>He &thorn;at schulde to god be free;</L>
<L>He melti&thorn; and wexi&thorn; a weel poore gist</L>
<L N="64">Whanne <MILESTONE N="64" UNIT="page">he come&thorn; to reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>For ful of corage is &yogh;ouge&thorn;e in herte,</L>
<L>And waitynge euere on his pray,</L>
<L>He ne spari&thorn; ryuer ne &thorn;ornes smerte</L>
<L N="68">To gete his myr&thorn;e &thorn;ere he beest may.</L>
<L>&para; He &thorn;at enserchi&thorn; &thorn;e derknes of ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And &thorn;e myst of &thorn;e morowtide may se,</L>
<L>He schal know bi cristis my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="72">If &yogh;ou&thorn;e kunne synge reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This hauk of herte in &yogh;ou&thorn;e y-wys,</L>
<L>Pursue&thorn; euere &thorn;is feisaunt hen;</L>
<L>&THORN;is feisaunt hen is likingnes,</L>
<L N="76">And euere folewi&thorn; hir &thorn;ese &yogh;onge men.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is is likinge in euery synne,</L>
<L>Venial &amp; deedli whe&thorn;er it be,</L>
<L>With greet likinge he wole bigynne,</L>
<L N="80">But sorewe bringe for&thorn; reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Liking is modir of synnis alle,</L>
<L>And norischi&thorn; euery wickid dede,</L>
<L>In feele myscheues sche maki&thorn; to falle,</L>
<L N="84">Of al sorowe sche doo&thorn; &thorn;e daunce leede.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;is herte of &yogh;ou&thorn;e is hie<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>MS.</I> his.]</NOTE> of port,</L>
<L>And wildenes maki&thorn; him ofte to fle,<MILESTONE N="65" UNIT="page">
<PB REF="00000112.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>And ofte to falle in wickid sort;</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;anne is it &thorn;e beste, reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But be waar of wel&thorn;e or &thorn;ou be woo;</L>
<L>In iolite whan &thorn;ou art pi&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;inke &thorn;at &yogh;onge wole go &thorn;e fro,</L>
<L N="92">Be &thorn;ou neuere so greet of mi&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Whanne age ha&thorn; take &thorn;ee bi &thorn;e brest,</L>
<L>And for febilnes &thorn;ou my&yogh;t not se,</L>
<L>&THORN;in herte sei&thorn; &thorn;anne &thorn;at it is best</L>
<L N="96">For to seie &amp; synge reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But in holi writt we fynde</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou &thorn;i lord schulde ou&yogh;t aske a &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>For &thorn;i longe beinge bihinde,</L>
<L N="100">A&yogh;enseid art &thorn;ou of &thorn;in askinge.</L>
<L>&para; While &thorn;ou were &yogh;onge, in tendre age,</L>
<L>Of &thorn;in askinge &thorn;ou were ful free</L>
<L>In ydilnes &amp; wilde outrage;</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;anne was for&yogh;ete reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;erfore euery man bi&thorn;inke him weel</L>
<L>How litil while is his dwellynge;</L>
<L>As holy writt yt doo&thorn; telle,</L>
<L N="108">He schal not <MILESTONE N="66" UNIT="page">knowe with-oute lesinge.</L>
<L>&para; A cok can crowe his tyme mydny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Which he knowith weel in his degre:</L>
<L>But his tyme he knowith not ari&yogh;t</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at can weel neuere seie reuertere.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Therfore be &thorn;ou in certein, man,</L>
<L>While &thorn;ou muste knowe how;</L>
<L>Bi&thorn;inke &thorn;i silf how &thorn;ou art &thorn;an;</L>
<L N="116">Noon so poore a wrecche as &thorn;ou!</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;erfore praye we to heuene king,</L>
<L>Euery man in his degree,</L>
<L>To graunte them &thorn;e blis euerlastinge</L>
<L N="120">&THORN;at &thorn;is word weel kan seie, reuertere.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000113.tif" N="95">
<HEAD>Merci Passith Ri&yogh;twisnes. (A DIALOGUE BETWEEN A SINNER AND MERCY.)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>pages</I> 66 <I>to</I> 73; <I>written without breaks.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>BI a forest as y gan walke</L>
<L>With-out a paleys in a leye,</L>
<L>I herde two men togidre talke;</L>
<L N="4">I &thorn;ou&yogh;te to wite what &thorn;ei wolde seie.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at oon stood in a doolful aray,</L>
<L>Hise deedli synnis he gan to defie,</L>
<L>"Alas," he seide, "me dreedi&thorn; to-day</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at ri&yogh;t wole for&thorn;, &amp; no mercye."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;anne answeride merci with sobir<MILESTONE N="67" UNIT="page"> cheer,</L>
<L>"Man, me &thorn;inki&thorn; &thorn;i witt is bare;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou wolt, y schal &thorn;ee leer,</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;ee needi&thorn; not to moorne so sare.</L>
<L>&para; I rede &thorn;ee to foonde to ameende &thorn;i fare;</L>
<L>Go euery day &amp; heere a messe,</L>
<L>And schryue &thorn;ee clene, &amp; haue noo care,</L>
<L N="16">For mercy passi&thorn; ri&yogh;twisnes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;anne seide &thorn;e synner with angri mood,</L>
<L>"Man, me &thorn;enkist<SUP>6</SUP> &thorn;ou doost raue;</L>
<L>I woot weel &thorn;ou canst no good,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>for</I> &thorn;enki&thorn;.]</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">&THORN;ou barist neuere staat but as a knawe.
<PB REF="00000114.tif" N="96"></L>
<L>&para; As y deserue, so schal y haue;</L>
<L>Weel bittirli y schal a-bie;</L>
<L>I knowe noon helpe &thorn;at me schulde haue,</L>
<L N="24">But &thorn;at ri&yogh;t schal for&thorn;, and no mercie."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;anne seide mercye meeke &amp; mylde,</L>
<L>"If &thorn;ou wolt fro &thorn;i synnes drawe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou speke &thorn;ese wordis wilde,</L>
<L N="28">To helpe &thorn;ee &yogh;it I wolde be fawe.</L>
<L>&para; Loue weel god, &thorn;at is my sawe,</L>
<L>Repente &thorn;ee blyue of<MILESTONE N="68" UNIT="page"> al &thorn;i mys;</L>
<L>Almy&yogh;ti god is ouer &thorn;e lawe,</L>
<L N="32">His merci passi&thorn; his ri&yogh;twisnes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Seie me," quod &thorn;e synner, "&thorn;ou foonued<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> fonoued.]</NOTE> clerk.</L>
<L>&thorn;ou coudist neuere rede in no spel;</L>
<L>I wrou&yogh;te wilfulli neuere good werk;</L>
<L N="36">What ri&yogh;t haue y in heuen to dwelle?</L>
<L>&para; I haue deserued to go to helle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore ofte sore sike y;</L>
<L>My wickid dedis wole me quelle,</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;ere ri&yogh;t schal for&thorn;, and no mercye."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Merci seide "&thorn;ou canst no good;</L>
<L>God schewi&thorn; &thorn;ee kyndenes many foolde,</L>
<L>For &thorn;ee &amp; me he schedde his blood,</L>
<L N="44">And suffride woundis bittir &amp; colde.</L>
<L>&para; His fair body to &thorn;e iewis was solde</L>
<L>To bie oure synful soulis to blis;</L>
<L>&THORN;i soule is his, y my&yogh;t be bolde;</L>
<L N="48">His merci passi&thorn; his ry&yogh;twisnes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; "Forso&thorn;e," quod &thorn;e synner, "&thorn;at leue y weel,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he is bo&thorn;e good &amp; kynde,</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto trewer &thorn;an ony steel;</L>
<L N="52">&THORN;at he loue&thorn; tru&thorn;e weel schal y fynde.
<PB REF="00000115.tif" N="97"></L>
<L>&para; How my&yogh;t god me of care vnbinde<MILESTONE N="69" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Si&thorn;en god loue&thorn; trou&thorn;e so verrili?</L>
<L>Do way, mercy, &thorn;ou spillist myche winde,</L>
<L N="56">For ri&yogh;t schal for&thorn;, &amp; no mercy.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Merci seide, "woldist &thorn;ou god knowe,</L>
<L>And wi&thorn; good entent mercy calle,</L>
<L>And to him meekeli &thorn;ee abowe,</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;an schal neuere myscheef in &thorn;ee falle.</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;ou&yogh; &thorn;ou haddist do &thorn;e synnis alle,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou crie mercy for al &thorn;i mys,</L>
<L>And with good herte on him to calle,</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;an wole his mercy passe ri&yogh;twisnes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; "What," quod &thorn;e synner, "y trowe &thorn;ou raue;</L>
<L>Canst &thorn;ou neuere of &thorn;i pletinge blynne?</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel bad me neuere mercy craue,</L>
<L N="68">And he can more clergie &thorn;an al &thorn;i kynne;</L>
<L>&para; And he him silf is ful of synne,</L>
<L>And &yogh;it wole he neuere mercy crie:</L>
<L>I coueite neuere heuen to wynne</L>
<L N="72">While ri&yogh;t schal for&thorn;, &amp; no mercie."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Merci seide "y preue bi skile,</L>
<L>Witt is nou&yogh;t wor&thorn;, but grace be sou&yogh;t;</L>
<L>&THORN;e deuel <MILESTONE N="70" UNIT="page">Ha&thorn; clergie &amp; witt at wille,</L>
<L N="76">And euere he setti&thorn; it foule at nou&yogh;t:</L>
<L>&para; He fil in wanhope as him neuere rou&yogh;te,</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; pride in heuen he loste his blis;</L>
<L>Hadde he oonys grace bisou&yogh;te,</L>
<L N="80">Merci hadde passid ri&yogh;twijsnes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Whanne &thorn;e synner herd &thorn;is, he si&yogh;ed sore,</L>
<L>With rewful cheer greet dool he made,</L>
<L>And seide, "of &thorn;ee wole y lerne more;</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;an is the deuel fals and bad,</L>
<L>&para; For if he my&yogh;te merci haue had,
<PB REF="00000116.tif" N="98"></L>
<L>A &thorn;ousand si&thorn;is y him defie;</L>
<L>He may be sory &amp; no-&thorn;ing glad</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at schal haue <NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. <I>transposes</I> ri&yogh;twisnes <I>and</I> mercy.</NOTE>ri&yogh;twisnes &amp; no mercy."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mercy biheeld &thorn;at semeli goost.</L>
<L>And seide, "leue bro&thorn;er, forsake &thorn;e feend,</L>
<L>For he wolde fayn &thorn;i soule were lost,</L>
<L N="92">To dwelle in helle without eend.</L>
<L>&para; Biseche now grace, &amp; god wole sende</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou wolt do as y &thorn;ee wijs,</L>
<L>And &thorn;an &thorn;i soule to heuen schal wende,</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;ere merci passi&thorn; ri&yogh;twisnes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Alas," quod &thorn;e synner, "al my lijf y rue,<MILESTONE N="71" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>For it is no &thorn;ing as y wende;</L>
<L>To serue god y wole be trewe</L>
<L N="100">If ony grace he wole me sende.</L>
<L>&para; Of al wickidnes he me defende!</L>
<L>&THORN;e fals feend, y him defie;</L>
<L>He wolde no &thorn;ing &thorn;at y dide meende,</L>
<L N="104">&THORN;at biheet me ri&yogh;t no mercie."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Merci seide "if &thorn;ou wolt so,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou my&yogh;t be glad al &thorn;i lijf,</L>
<L>And for &thorn;i synne &thorn;ou maist be woo,</L>
<L N="108">And to a preest cleene &thorn;ee schriue,</L>
<L>&para; And take penaunce without strijf,</L>
<L>Repentynge &thorn;ee of al &thorn;i mys,</L>
<L>&THORN;an bi &thorn;i witt &thorn;ou maist knowe rijf</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;at merci passi&thorn; ri&yogh;twisnes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Alas," quod the synner, "y haue lyued wrong!</L>
<L>What penaunce were y wor&thorn;i to haue?</L>
<L>&THORN;er may no man sette me to strong</L>
<L N="116">&THORN;ou&yogh; y were quicke doluen on graue.
<PB REF="00000117.tif" N="99"></L>
<L>&para; A! almi&yogh;ty god, mercy I craue,</L>
<L>Now lete my flesche my synnis abie!</L>
<L>Graciose crist! my soule &thorn;ou haue,</L>
<L N="120">For ri&yogh;t is nou&yogh;t wi&thorn;out mercie."<MILESTONE N="72" UNIT="page"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mercy seide, "ful weel &thorn;ou woost,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou hast often herd sayen,</L>
<L>What man is founde &thorn;at was lost,</L>
<L N="124">Wi&thorn; him is crist plesid &amp; fayn.</L>
<L>&para; What nede had crist to suffre payne</L>
<L>But for to bie oure soulis to blis?</L>
<L>Telle me &thorn;i lijf heere al playn,</L>
<L N="128">&THORN;at mercy may passe ri&yogh;twisnes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"My fyue wittis y haue mys spende</L>
<L>&THORN;oru&yogh; pride, enuie, &amp; leccherie:</L>
<L>To &thorn;e ten heestis y haue not tende</L>
<L N="132">&THORN;oru&yogh; slou&thorn;e, wra&thorn;&thorn;e, &amp; glotenie.</L>
<L>&para; In coueitise lyued haue y,</L>
<L>And neuere dide werkis of mercyes;</L>
<L>God! &yogh;eue me grace or &thorn;at y die!</L>
<L N="136">&THORN;i merci may passe ri&yogh;twisnes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Merci &yogh;af him penaunce stronge,</L>
<L>And seide "man, wolt &thorn;ou &thorn;is take?</L>
<L>&THORN;ou muste suffre bo&thorn;e ri&yogh;t and wrong</L>
<L N="140">If &thorn;ou &thorn;i synne wolt forsake</L>
<L>&para; In good praiers &thorn;ou muste wake,</L>
<L>And neuere <MILESTONE N="73" UNIT="page">wilne to do a-mys;</L>
<L>And for &thorn;i sorewe &thorn;at &thorn;ou doost make,</L>
<L N="144">Merci schal passe ri&yogh;twisnes."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;e synner took penaunce wi&thorn; good entent,</L>
<L>And lefte al his wickid synne;</L>
<L>Whanne he hadde leeue, away he went
<PB REF="00000118.tif" N="100"></L>
<L N="148">From alle his freendis, ki&thorn; &amp; kynne.</L>
<L>&para; In greet penaunce he putte him inne,</L>
<L>And neuere aftir wilfulli dide mys;</L>
<L>He truste on god heuen to wynne,</L>
<L N="152">&THORN;ere mercy passi&thorn; ri&yogh;twijsnes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Almi&yogh;ti god! now make us stable,</L>
<L>And &yogh;eue us grace weel to spede,</L>
<L>And to us alle bee merciable,</L>
<L N="156">And for&yogh;eue us alle oure mysdede.</L>
<L>&para; And helpe us, ladi, att oure moost nede,</L>
<L>To &thorn;i sone oure soulis &thorn;ou wys,</L>
<L>And with his mercy fulli us fede</L>
<L N="160">&THORN;ere mercy passi&thorn; ri&yogh;wijsnes.<NOTE PLACE="end">["As resoun rewlid," or "Filius Regis Mortuus est," follows. It is printed in <I>Political, Religious, and Love Poems</I>, p. 205, &amp;c.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>A-M-E-N.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000119.tif" N="101">
<HEAD>The Relief.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 39; <I>written without breaks.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; <B>Memento homo quod cinis es, et</B> in cinerem reuerteris.</L>
<L>&para; <B>Fac bene dum viuis. Post mortem</B> viuere <B>si uis.</B></L>
<L>&para; <B>Tangere qui gaudet. meretricem qualiter audet.</B></L>
<L><B>Palmis pollutis. regem tractare salutis.</B></L>
<L><B>Credo in deum patrem omnipotentem.</B></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &thorn;ee, god fadir, I bileeue,</L>
<L>&THORN;e firste persoone ful of my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>&THORN;at al of nou&yogh;t hast maad to meeue,</L>
<L N="4">bo&thorn;e heuen &amp; er&thorn;e, day &amp; ny&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And in &thorn;in oonly goten sone,</L>
<L>Born of &thorn;i silf bifor al &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Oure lord ihesus, &thorn;e secunde persoone,</L>
<L N="8">Bothe oo god in heuen beinge.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e same god &thorn;at euere ha&thorn; ben,</L>
<L>And si&thorn;en conceyued bi &thorn;e holi goost,</L>
<L>And born of a mayden cleene,</L>
<L N="12">Bicause a man in meekenes moost.<MILESTONE N="40" UNIT="page"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And ri&yogh;t as in &thorn;e trynyte</L>
<L>Ben persoones &thorn;re, substauncis but oon,</L>
<L>Ri&yogh;t so in &thorn;ee ben substauncis &thorn;re,</L>
<L N="16">God, soule, bodi, &amp; al oon persoone.
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="102"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Undir pilate &thorn;ou suffridist peyne</L>
<L>Bi fre wil, mankinde to saue,</L>
<L>Nailid on a croos, &amp; &thorn;eron slain,</L>
<L N="20">And taken doun &amp; biried in graue.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In soule oonli &thorn;ou wente to helle,</L>
<L>&amp; took &thorn;ens &thorn;i part, it was good ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But up &thorn;ou roos in fleisch and in felle</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;e &thorn;rid day bi godli my&yogh;t.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ou sti&yogh; to heuen in &thorn;i manhede,</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere &thorn;ou sittist on &thorn;i fadir ri&yogh;t side,</L>
<L>But ouer al-where is &thorn;i godhede,</L>
<L N="28">&THORN;ere is noon &thorn;at from &thorn;ee him may hide.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ens schalt &thorn;ou come us alle to deeme,</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e quik and dede of adams seed.</L>
<L>With opene woundis &amp; visage breme;</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;is bileeue maki&thorn; true men drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; I bileeue in &thorn;e holi <MILESTONE N="41" UNIT="page">goost,</L>
<L>&THORN;e &thorn;ridde persoone in trynyte,</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;re noon is more ne moost,</L>
<L N="36">But al oon god in persoones &thorn;re.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e holi goost maki&thorn; holi chirche</L>
<L>Of fei&thorn;ful men, bi comynynge</L>
<L>Ech oon to o&thorn;ir what &thorn;ei kunne worche</L>
<L N="40">In holines and good lyuyng.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; For&yogh;eeuenes y bileeue of synne</L>
<L>Bi &thorn;e holi goost and &thorn;e sacrament,</L>
<L>If y maye goostli to hem wynne,</L>
<L N="44">Or ellis him silfe is euere present.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ou&yogh; he neuere so present be,</L>
<L>&YOGH;it he wole for ful meekenes
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="103"></L>
<L>&THORN;at y do &thorn;erto &thorn;at is in me,</L>
<L N="48">Lest contempt lette me of for&yogh;euenes.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Also y bileeue in hool mynde,</L>
<L>&THORN;e holi goost schalle knytte a&yogh;en</L>
<L>&THORN;e soule to &thorn;e fleische of al mankinde;</L>
<L N="52">For al fleish schal ryse &thorn;at dee&thorn; hath slayn.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;e holi goost schal &yogh;eue also</L>
<L>Euerlastynge lijf to alle true men.</L>
<L>&THORN;at we may heere serue &thorn;er-to,</L>
<L N="56">&para; Y rede we seie alle, amen.<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>The Sixteen Points of Charity</I>, or "Man, among &thorn;i myr&thorn;is," printed p. 114, below, follows here in the MS.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000122.tif" N="104">
<HEAD>The Ten Commandments.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 47; <I>written without breaks.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>EUery man schulde teche &thorn;is lore</L>
<L>To hise children with good entent,</L>
<L>And do it him-silf euermore,</L>
<L N="4">To kepe weel goddis comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Fals goddis &thorn;ou schalt noon haue,</L>
<L>But worschipe god omnipotent;</L>
<L>Make not &thorn;i god &thorn;at man ha&thorn; graue:</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;is is &thorn;e firste comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Goddis name in ydil take &thorn;ou not,</L>
<L>For if &thorn;ou do &thorn;ou schalt be scheent;</L>
<L>Swere bi no &thorn;ing &thorn;at god ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t:</L>
<L N="12">&THORN;is is &thorn;e secunde comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Haue mynde to helewe &thorn;in holi day,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou &amp; alle &thorn;ine with good entent;</L>
<L>Leue seruile werkis &amp; nyce aray:</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;is is &thorn;e &thorn;ridde comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Worschipe &thorn;i fadir &amp; &thorn;i modir bo&thorn;e,&mdash;</L>
<L>&THORN;at longe lijf to &thorn;ee be lent,&mdash;</L>
<L>With meete <MILESTONE N="41" UNIT="page">and drink, coumfort &amp; clo&thorn;e:</L>
<L N="20">&THORN;is is &thorn;e iiij<SUP>e</SUP> comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sle no man with yuel wille,</L>
<L>Ensaumple, or tunge, or strokis dent;
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="105"></L>
<L>But euermore do good for ille:</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;is is &thorn;e fifthe comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Do no leccherie in al &thorn;i lijf;</L>
<L>Lete fleischeli knowynge from &thorn;ee be lent</L>
<L>Saue oonli bi-twene man &amp; wijf:</L>
<L N="28">&thorn;is is &thorn;e sixte comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ou schalt not stele no maner of &thorn;ing,</L>
<L>Ne helpe &thorn;erto bi no consent.</L>
<L>Leue alle fals mesuris &amp; al gilinge:</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;is is &thorn;e .vij. comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ou schalt beere no fals witnes</L>
<L>For no mater &thorn;at may be ment;</L>
<L>Seie euere &thorn;e so&thorn;e, or holde &thorn;i pees:</L>
<L N="36">&THORN;is is &thorn;e .viij. comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ou schalt not coueite &thorn;i nei&yogh;boris good,</L>
<L>As hous, lond, catel, ne rent,</L>
<L>In hindringe of him &amp; of his blood:</L>
<L N="40">&THORN;is is &thorn;e .ix. comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ou schalt not desire &thorn;i nei&yogh;boris feere,</L>
<L>Ne falsli his seruaunt from him hent,</L>
<L>Ne no good &thorn;at <MILESTONE N="49" UNIT="page">he hath heere:</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;is is &thorn;e .x. comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;ese ten to kepe, &thorn;ou &yogh;eue us grace</L>
<L>&THORN;at on &thorn;e roode was al to-rent,</L>
<L>In-to his blis &thorn;at we mowe passe</L>
<L N="48">At &thorn;e laste day of Iugement.<NOTE PLACE="end">["I Warne eche lijf," p. 107, &amp;c., of this print, follows here in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem">
<DIV2 TYPE="version">

<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="106">
<HEAD>Kepe Wel Cristes Comaundement.</HEAD>
<HEAD>[<I>Vernon MS., ab.</I> 1370 A.D., <I>fol.</I> 408 <I>b., col.</I> 1. <I>Printed here for comparison' sake, with the metrical points, but no stops.</I>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>I</B> warne vche leod. &thorn;at liue&thorn; in londe.</L>
<L>And do hem dredles. out of were.</L>
<L>&THORN;at &thorn;ei most studie. and vnderstonde.</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e lawe of crist. to loue and lere.</L>
<L>&THORN;er nis no mon. fer ne nere.</L>
<L>&THORN;at may him seluen. saue vn schent.</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at caste&thorn;. wi&thorn; concience clere.</L>
<L N="8">To kepe. wel. Cristes Comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;ow most haue o God. and no mo.</L>
<L>And serue him bo&thorn;e. with mayn and miht.</L>
<L>And ouer alle &thorn;inges. loue him also.</L>
<L N="12">For he ha&thorn; lant &thorn;e. lyf and liht.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou beo nuy&yogh;ed. day or niht.</L>
<L>In peyne be meke. and pacient.</L>
<L>And rule &thorn;e ay. be reson riht.</L>
<L N="16">And kep wel. Cristes Comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; And let &thorn;i nei&yogh;hebor. frend and fo.</L>
<L>Riht frely. of &thorn;i frendschupe fele.</L>
<L>In herte. &thorn;at &thorn;ou wilne hem so.</L>
<L N="20">Riht as &thorn;ou woldest. &thorn;i self weore wele.</L>
<L>And help to sauen hem. from vncele.</L>
<L>So &thorn;at heore soules. beo not schent.</L>
<L>And also heore care. &thorn;ou helpe to kele.</L>
<L N="24">And kepe wel. Cristes comaundement.
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="108"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In Idel. Godes nome tak &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>But cese. and saue &thorn;e from &thorn;at synne.</L>
<L>Swere bi no &thorn;ing. &thorn;at God ha&thorn; wrouht.</L>
<L N="28">Be war. his wra&thorn;&thorn;e. lest &thorn;ou hit wynne.</L>
<L>But bisy &thorn;e her. bale to blynne.</L>
<L>&THORN;at blaberyng are wi&thorn; o&thorn;es blent.</L>
<L>Vncou&thorn;e and knowen. and of &thorn;i kynne.</L>
<L N="32">And kep wel. cristes comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; In clannes and in cristes werk.</L>
<L>Haue mynde. to holden &thorn;in haly day.</L>
<L>And drauh &thorn;e &thorn;enne. from dedes derk.</L>
<L N="36">Wi&thorn; al &thorn;i meyne. Mon and may.</L>
<L>And men vnsau&yogh;te. loke &thorn;ou assay.</L>
<L>To sau&yogh;ten hem &thorn;enne. at on assent.</L>
<L>And pore and seke. &thorn;ou plese and pay.</L>
<L N="40">And kepe wel cristes Comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;i Fader &thorn;i Moder. &thorn;ou worschupe bo&thorn;e.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou wolt boteles. bale escheuwe.</L>
<L>With counseil cum-forte hem. with mete and clo&thorn;e.</L>
<L N="44">As &thorn;ou sest. hem neode&thorn; newe.</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ei talke of tales vn-trewe.</L>
<L>&THORN;ou torn hem out. of &thorn;at entent.</L>
<L>And cristes lawe. help &thorn;at &thorn;ei knewe.</L>
<L N="48">And kep wel cristes. Comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sle no mon. wi&thorn; wikked wille.</L>
<L>Be war. and vengeaunce tak &thorn;ou non.</L>
<L>In word. ne dede. loude. ne stille.</L>
<L N="52">Bakbyte &thorn;ou no mon. blod ny bon.</L>
<L>But ay let gabbynges. glyde and gon.</L>
<L>A-wey wher &thorn;ei wol. glace. or glent.</L>
<L>And help &thorn;at alle men ben aton.</L>
<L N="56">And kep wel cristes comaundement.
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="110"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Stele &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t. &thorn;i nei&yogh;ebors &thorn;ing.</L>
<L>Nou&thorn;ur wi&thorn; stillenes. ne wi&thorn; strif.</L>
<L>Nor with no maner. wrong getyng.</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;i self &thorn;i seruaunt. child. ne wyf.</L>
<L>To sulle and buye. &yogh;if &thorn;ou be ryf.</L>
<L>Wayte al way. &thorn;at wrong be went.</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou wolt lyue. &thorn;e lastyng lyf.</L>
<L N="64">&THORN;ou kepe wel. cristes comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fals witnesse. loke &thorn;ow non bere.<MILESTONE N="408b:2" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ow wolt. in blisse a-byde.</L>
<L>&THORN;i nei&yogh;ebore. wityngly to dere.</L>
<L N="68">Ne no mon nou&thorn;er. in no syde.</L>
<L>But loke &thorn;at no mon. be a nuy&yogh;ed.</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou may him. from harmes hent.</L>
<L>And help &thorn;at falshede. beo distruiet.</L>
<L N="72">And kep wel. cristes comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Sunge &thorn;ou not. in lecherie.</L>
<L>Such lust vn leueful. let hit pas.</L>
<L>Consente &thorn;ou not. to such folye.</L>
<L N="76">&THORN;at founden is so foul trespas.</L>
<L>And loke. &thorn;at nou&thorn;er more ne las.</L>
<L>&THORN;i lykyng. on &thorn;at lust be lent.</L>
<L>Leste &thorn;ou synge. &thorn;is songe allas.</L>
<L N="80">For brekyng. of cristes comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;i nei&yogh;hebors wyf. coueyte &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>Vnleuefully. a-&yogh;eynes &thorn;e lawe.</L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hire to sunge. in word ne &thorn;ou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="84">And from &thorn;at deede. euer &thorn;ou &thorn;e drawe.</L>
<L>And neuer sey. to hire no sawe.</L>
<L>To make hire. to synne assent.</L>
<L>Ne plese hire not. with no mis plawe.</L>
<L N="88">But kep wel. cristes comaundement.
<PB REF="00000130.tif" N="112"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; &THORN;i nei&yogh;hebors hous. wenche ne knaue.</L>
<L>Vnskilfully. coueyte &thorn;ou nouht.</L>
<L>Ne &yogh;it his good. with wrong to haue.</L>
<L N="92">For hit. lest &thorn;ou to bale be brouht.</L>
<L>For whon &thorn;e so&thorn;e. schal vp be souht.</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;ou in to &thorn;is sunnes assent.</L>
<L>Ful bitterly. hit mot be bou&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="96">For brekyng of cristes. Comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&para; Vche mon &thorn;at wol. &thorn;is lessun lere.</L>
<L>And loue&thorn;. a laweful lyf. to lede.</L>
<L>He may not misse. on none manere.</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;e mer&thorn;e of heuene. to his mede.</L>
<L>For crist him here. wol helpe and hede.</L>
<L>And he&thorn;ene. in to heuene hent.</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i I. preye. &thorn;at crist vs spede.</L>
<L N="104">Kuyndely to kepe. his comaundement.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="version">

<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="107">
<HEAD>Kepe Weel Cristis Comaundement.</HEAD>
<HEAD>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 49; <I>written without breaks.</I>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L><B>I</B> Warne eche lijf &thorn;at liue&thorn; in lond</L>
<L>And do him dredlees out of were,</L>
<L>&THORN;at he must studie &amp; vndirstonde</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;e lawe of god to loue &amp; lere.</L>
<L>&para; For &thorn;ere is no man feer ne neer</L>
<L>&THORN;at may him sillfe saue vnschent</L>
<L>But he &thorn;at casti&thorn; him with conscience clere</L>
<L N="8">To kepe weel cristis comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thou schalt haue oon god &amp; no mo,</L>
<L>And serue him bo&thorn;e wi&thorn; mayn &amp; my&yogh;t,</L>
<L>And ouer al &thorn;ing loue him also,</L>
<L N="12">For he ha&thorn; lent &thorn;ee lijf &amp; li&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; If &thorn;ou be noied bi day or ny&yogh;t,</L>
<L>In peyne be meeke &amp; pacient,</L>
<L>And rewle &thorn;ee ay bi resoun ri&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="16">And kepe weel cristis comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lete &thorn;i nei&yogh;e<MILESTONE N="50" UNIT="page"> boris, bo&thorn;e freend &amp; fo,</L>
<L>Freli of &thorn;i freendschip feele;</L>
<L>In herte wilne &thorn;ou hem also</L>
<L N="20">Ri&yogh;t as &thorn;ou woldist &thorn;i silf were wele.</L>
<L>&para; Helpe to saue hem from vnsele</L>
<L>So &thorn;at her soulis ben not schent,</L>
<L>And her care &thorn;ou helpe to kele,</L>
<L N="24">And kepe weel cristis comaundement.
<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="109"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Goddis name in ydil take &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>But ceesse &amp; saue &thorn;ee from &thorn;at synne;</L>
<L>Swere bi no &thorn;ing &thorn;at god ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="28">Be waar his wra&thorn;&thorn;e lest &thorn;ou so wynne.</L>
<L>&para; But bisie &thorn;ee euere her bale to blinne</L>
<L>&THORN;at wi&thorn; blaberinge oo&thorn;is ben blent,</L>
<L>Vncou&thorn;e &amp; knowen of &thorn;i kynne;</L>
<L N="32">And kepe weel cristis comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In clennes and in cristis werk</L>
<L>Haue mynde to halowe &thorn;in holi daye,</L>
<L>And drawe &thorn;ee &thorn;anne from dedis derk</L>
<L N="36">Wi&thorn; al &thorn;i meyne, man &amp; may.</L>
<L>&para; Men vnsoft, loke &thorn;ou asay</L>
<L>To soften<MILESTONE N="51" UNIT="page"> them to good assent,</L>
<L>Helpe poore and sike to please &amp; pay,</L>
<L N="40">And kepe weel cristis comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i fadir &amp; modir worschipe bo&thorn;e&mdash;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou wolt botelees bale eschewe&mdash;</L>
<L>With councelle, coumforte, meete &amp; clo&thorn;e,</L>
<L N="44">As &thorn;ou seest &thorn;at hem nedi&thorn; newe.</L>
<L>&para; And if &thorn;ei talke of wordis vntrewe,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou turne hem out of &thorn;at entent,</L>
<L>And cristis lawe helpe &thorn;at &thorn;ei knew,</L>
<L N="48">And kepe weel cristis comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sle no man with wickid wille;</L>
<L>Be waar, of veniaunce take &thorn;ou noon;</L>
<L>Eerli ne late, lowde ne stille,</L>
<L N="52">Bacbite no man, blood ne boon,</L>
<L>&para; But lete euere gabbing glide &amp; goon</L>
<L>Away, whe&thorn;er it wole glase or glent;</L>
<L>And helpe &thorn;at alle men were at oone,</L>
<L N="56">And kepe weel cristis comaundement.
<PB REF="00000129.tif" N="111"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Synne &thorn;ou not in leccherie;</L>
<L>Such lust vnleefful, lete it passe</L>
<L>Consente &thorn;ou not to &thorn;at folie</L>
<L N="60">&THORN;at founden it is so<MILESTONE N="52" UNIT="page"> foule a trespase.</L>
<L>&para; And loke &thorn;ou, nei&thorn;er more ne lasse</L>
<L>&THORN;i likinge on &thorn;at lust be lent,</L>
<L>Lest &thorn;ou singe &thorn;is song 'alas</L>
<L N="64">For brekinge of cristis comaundement.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Stele &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t of &thorn;i nei&yogh;boris &thorn;ing</L>
<L>Nei&thorn;er wi&thorn; stilnes ne with strijf,</L>
<L>Ne with no maner of wrong geetynge,</L>
<L N="68">&THORN;i silf, &thorn;i seruaunt, child, ne wijf.</L>
<L>&para; To bie &amp; sille if &thorn;ou be rijfe,</L>
<L>Loke euere &thorn;at wrong away be went:</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou wolt han euerlastinge lijf,</L>
<L N="72">Kepe weel cristis comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Fals witnes, loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou noon bare;</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou wolt in blis a-bide,</L>
<L>&thorn;i nei&yogh;bore wilfulli &thorn;ou ne dere,</L>
<L N="76">Ne noon &thorn;at wone&thorn; &thorn;ee biside;</L>
<L>&para; But loke &thorn;at no man be anoied</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou may him from harmes hent,</L>
<L>And helpe &thorn;at falshede were distroied,</L>
<L N="80">And kepe weel cristis comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;i nei&yogh;boris wijf, coueite &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Vnleeffulli, a&yogh;ens &thorn;e lawe,<MILESTONE N="53" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Wi&thorn; hir to synne in dede or &thorn;ou&yogh;t,</L>
<L N="84">But from &thorn;e dede euere &thorn;ou drawe,</L>
<L>&para; And ceesse, &amp; seie to hir no sawe</L>
<L>To make hir for to synne assent,</L>
<L>Ne please hir not with no nyce plawe,</L>
<L N="88">But kepe weel cristis comaundement.
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="113"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thi nei&yogh;boris hous, wenche, ne knawe,</L>
<L>Vnleeffulli coueite &thorn;ou nou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>Ne o&thorn;ir good, wrong to haue,</L>
<L N="92">Lest &thorn;ou for it to bale be brou&yogh;t.</L>
<L>&para; For whanne &thorn;e soo&thorn;e schal be up sou&yogh;t,</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou to &thorn;is synne assent,</L>
<L>Ful bittirli it schal be bou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="96">For brekinge of cristis comaundement.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ech man &thorn;at wole &thorn;is lessoun lere,</L>
<L>And loue&thorn; a lawful lijf to lede,</L>
<L>He ne may mys on no manere</L>
<L N="100">&THORN;e myr&thorn;is of heuen to haue to meede;</L>
<L>&para; For crist wole him heere helpe at nede,</L>
<L>For from hens to heuene be wole him hent,</L>
<L>For-&thorn;i praie we &thorn;at crist us spede</L>
<L N="104">Kindeli to kepe his comaundement.<NOTE PLACE="end">["There is no creatour but oon," printed pp. 18-21, follows here in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>Amen.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem">

<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="114">
<HEAD>The Sixtene Poyntis of Charite.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Lambeth MS.</I> 853, <I>ab.</I> 1430 A.D., <I>page</I> 42; <I>written without breaks, except lines</I> 6-12, 21-4.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>MAn, among &thorn;i myr&thorn;is haue in mynde</L>
<L>From whens &thorn;ou come &amp; whidir &thorn;ou teendis,</L>
<L>How freeli &thorn;ou fallist &amp; filist &thorn;i kinde!</L>
<L N="4">Arise &amp; make of<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>of</I> in margin.</NOTE> &thorn;i mys ameendis,</L>
<L>&para; &THORN;at of &thorn;is world whanne &thorn;ou out wendis,</L>
<L>&THORN;ou maist in heuene &thorn;i lord god se</L>
<L>Among hise apostolis &amp; dere freendis</L>
<L N="8">As a chosen child in charitee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The hi&yogh;est lessoun &thorn;at man may lere</L>
<L>Is to lyue iust lijf, if &thorn;ou wolt loke,</L>
<L>Yf &thorn;ou haue grace to holde &amp; heere,</L>
<L N="12">Is playnli printid in poulis booke.</L>
<L>&para; For god to poul &thorn;is lessoun tooke</L>
<L>in &thorn;e &thorn;ridde heuen, hi&yogh;est of &thorn;re,</L>
<L>Euery man to cunne &amp; looke</L>
<L N="16">&THORN;e sixtene propirtees of charitee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Thou&yogh; y speke,' sei&thorn; seint poule,</L>
<L>'As aungils doon, or with mennis tunge,</L>
<L>If charite be not in &thorn;i soule,</L>
<L N="20">I am but as a brasen symbal song.</L>
<L>&para; And &thorn;ou&yogh; my bileeue be neuere so strong<MILESTONE N="43" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>So &thorn;at mounteyns be meued bi fei&thorn; of me,</L>
<L>I am not worthi to god so longe</L>
<L N="24">As me wanti&thorn; charite.
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="115"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thou&yogh; y to poore men &yogh;eue al my good,</L>
<L>And my bodi to brenne &thorn;ere hoot fier ys,</L>
<L>And charite be not in my mood,</L>
<L N="28">It profiti&thorn; me not to heuen blis.'</L>
<L>&para; But for god wolde it schulde not mys</L>
<L>To knowe in charite whanne we be,</L>
<L>He tau&yogh;te poul to teche al his</L>
<L N="32">&THORN;e .xvj. Poyntis of charite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>'Charite,' he sei&thorn;, 'is pacient,</L>
<L>Alle disesis meekli suffringe,</L>
<L>Benigne also in hir entent,</L>
<L N="36">Kindelid with fier of good lyuyng;</L>
<L>&para; Neuere enuyose for ony &thorn;ing</L>
<L>To freend ne foo, whe&thorn;ir it be,</L>
<L>But euere glad to goddis plesing</L>
<L N="40">To cherische alle men in charitee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Charite doo&thorn; neuere wickidli</L>
<L>Bi purpos of wil, ne wickid dede,</L>
<L>Ne blowen<MILESTONE N="44" UNIT="page"> is with pride &thorn;ou&yogh; sche be wel&thorn;i,</L>
<L N="44">For to greue god is hir moost drede;</L>
<L>&para; For in helle depe schal be her meede,</L>
<L>A low wi&thorn; lucifir for to be</L>
<L>&THORN;at for blynde pride wole take noon hede</L>
<L N="48">lowli to lyue in charite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Charite is not coueitose toold</L>
<L>Of worschipe ne of wronge wynnynge,</L>
<L>For wi&thorn; ypocritis sche may not holde,</L>
<L N="52">Ne consente with wrong getyng.</L>
<L>&para; Sche sechi&thorn; not hir owne &thorn;ing</L>
<L>For hindringe of nei&yogh;boris &thorn;at my&yogh;te be,</L>
<L>For manye perels ben in pletynge</L>
<L N="56">&THORN;at acorden not with charitee.
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="116"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Charite wole no &thorn;ing be wroo&thorn;</L>
<L>For harmes &thorn;at hir silf may hent,</L>
<L>But for to synne, al oonli is hir loo&thorn;,</L>
<L N="60">A&yogh;ens goddis comaundement.</L>
<L>&para; Charitee &thorn;enki&thorn; noon yuel in hir entent,</L>
<L>But stinti&thorn; strijf, &amp; stoondi&thorn; free;</L>
<L>Al yuel wil, it wolde were went,</L>
<L N="64">And chaungid al for charite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of wickidnes charite is not glad,<MILESTONE N="45" UNIT="page"></L>
<L>Bi lau&yogh;ter ne bi no likinge,</L>
<L>But euere sobre, soft, &amp; sad,</L>
<L N="68">In &thorn;ou&yogh;t, in word, &amp; in worching.</L>
<L>&para; To ri&yogh;t &amp; troupe is her ioiyng,</L>
<L>To maynteine tru&thorn;e where-euere sche be,</L>
<L>With fei&thorn;ful and true folk Is hir dwelling,</L>
<L N="72">For suche ben chosen in charite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;ingis sche beri&thorn; vp meekeli,</L>
<L>For al hir wronge schal turne to game;</L>
<L>Sche falli&thorn; not vnder for vilonye,</L>
<L N="76">For los, for sijknes, ne for schame.</L>
<L>&para; Alle &thorn;ingis sche trowi&thorn; wi&thorn;-out fame</L>
<L>&THORN;at goddis lawe techi&thorn; tru&thorn;e to be,</L>
<L>And bidi&thorn; &thorn;erbi for ony blame,</L>
<L N="80">For suche ben children of charitee.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle &thorn;ingis sche hopi&thorn; to haue in blis;</L>
<L>For suche sche suffri&thorn; &amp; serue&thorn; heere;</L>
<L>For of mercy sche may not mys</L>
<L N="84">&THORN;at &thorn;is lesson wole loue &amp; lere.</L>
<L>&para; Sche abidi&thorn; alle &thorn;ingis with good chere</L>
<L>&THORN;ou&yogh; sche &thorn;inke longe &thorn;e eende to se,</L>
<L>For of reward sche ha&thorn;<MILESTONE N="46" UNIT="page"> no were</L>
<L N="88">&THORN;at &thorn;us abidi&thorn; in charite.
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="117"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Charite falli&thorn; neuere a-way</L>
<L>From him &thorn;at it in charite wole holde,</L>
<L>Bifore ne aftir domys day,</L>
<L N="92">But encressi&thorn; in blis an hundrid folde.</L>
<L>&para; Whanne al tresour is tried &amp; tolde,</L>
<L>Al help to blis is in &thorn;ese &thorn;re,</L>
<L>Fei&thorn;, hope, &amp; charite, no&thorn;ing colde;</L>
<L N="96">&THORN;e mooste of hem is charite.'</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bi charite, man, &thorn;ou must loue more</L>
<L>God &thorn;an silf, &thorn;e soo&thorn; to say,</L>
<L>For &thorn;is is &thorn;e lord-is owne lore,</L>
<L N="100">With al &thorn;i power him please &amp; pay;</L>
<L>&para; Thi nei&yogh;bore also, wi&thorn;-oute nay,</L>
<L>Loue as &thorn;i silf saaf to bee;</L>
<L>To freend &amp; fo holde faste &thorn;i fay,</L>
<L N="104">And chaunge &thorn;ou neuere fro charite.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>If we &thorn;is lessoun we loue &amp; leere,</L>
<L>And take it truli to oure entent,</L>
<L>We schulen haue knowinge good &amp; cleere</L>
<L N="108">Who ben blamelees &amp; who ben schent.</L>
<L>God, &thorn;at hast us oure lijf lent,</L>
<L>Graunte &thorn;at we may oure <MILESTONE N="47" UNIT="page">silf to enserche &amp; se,</L>
<L>As &thorn;ou for us on roode were rent,</L>
<L N="112">&THORN;ou chese us to &thorn;ee for charite.<NOTE PLACE="end">["Euery man schulde teche &thorn;is lore," printed pp. 104-5, follows here in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
<TRAILER>A-M-E-N.
</TRAILER>

</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000136.tif" N="118">
<HEAD>Quindecim Signa ante diem Judicij.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>MS. B</I>. 11. 24, <I>Trinity College, Cambridge; ab</I>. 1450, A.D.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Kynge of grace, &amp; ful of pyte,</L>
<L>Lord of heuyn, I-blyssyd &thorn;ou be!</L>
<L>Haue mercy on vs, we the beseche,</L>
<L N="4">Or we lese our wytt &amp; speche!</L>
<L>xv. tokenys telle I may</L>
<L>That shal come before doomys day,</L>
<L>As it is seyde yn the prophecye,</L>
<L N="8">In the book of Jeremye.</L>
<L>Herkenyth now &thorn;e tokenynge</L>
<L>That &thorn;e firste day shal brynge:</L>
<L>Fro heuyn shal a rayne falle,</L>
<L N="12">Hit shal be byttyr as eny galle,</L>
<L>Hytt shall be as red as any blod,</L>
<L>Ouyr all &thorn;e worlle a grymly flod;</L>
<L>Hytt schalle ouergo wyth large mett</L>
<L N="16">Alle that ys in erth I-sett:</L>
<L>The chylderyn vn-born Aferd shall be</L>
<L>Of thys tokenynge, as I telle the,</L>
<L>And meue hem tyll our Syth</L>
<L N="20">Ryth as &thorn;ey speke myth.</L>
<L>The secunde day ys stronge with alle:</L>
<L>The sterrys shal fro heuyn falle,</L>
<L>So dredfulle and so breyth</L>
<L N="24">As the fyre off &thorn;e dondyr lyth.
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>Men schalle say, "welle-away!</L>
<L>Thys ben the tokenys off domys day!"</L>
<L>They schall cry &amp; syke sore,</L>
<L N="28">And say, "lord, mercy, thyn ore<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. thynore]</NOTE>!"</L>
<L>The iij<SUP>de</SUP> day ys off syche:</L>
<L>In erthe and in heuyn-ryche</L>
<L>The hye son thatt ys so bryth,</L>
<L N="32">So fayr, and so full off lyth,</L>
<L>Hitt shalle be swarte as any pyche:</L>
<L>Alle thatt shall be rewlyche.</L>
<L>Men schalle &thorn;en sone se</L>
<L N="36">Att mydday hytt shalle swarte be;</L>
<L>All thatt ben on lyve</L>
<L>Schalle thys wordys dryve,</L>
<L>"Alas thatt we scholle Abyde</L>
<L N="40">To se &thorn;is sorowe in Euery syde!"</L>
<L>The iiij<SUP>te</SUP> day ys swythe longe,</L>
<L>With wepynge &amp; wyth sorow Amonge:</L>
<L>All &thorn;at in erthe stonde</L>
<L N="44">Schall to red blod wende;</L>
<L>They schalle drawe hem to &thorn;e grownde,</L>
<L>Ther schalle they dwelle butt no stownde,</L>
<L>To the see &thorn;ey schalle for drede,</L>
<L N="48">Ryth as moyses the prophytt sayde,</L>
<L>Thatt the mone schalle rewly falle</L>
<L>And wynd outt of hys reche stalle.</L>
<L>The man schalle say to hys wyff</L>
<L N="52">"Alas &thorn;att we be nowe Alyve!"</L>
<L>The v<SUP>te</SUP> day comyth swythe;</L>
<L>For euery best &thorn;att ys on lyve,</L>
<L>Toward heuyn her hedd schall holde.</L>
<L N="56">For thatt won&thorn;er As y yowe tollde,</L>
<L>Men schalle say, "lord, thyn ore</L>
<L>Off our sorowe &amp; off our sore!"</L>
<L>Thys tellyth the prophecy</L>
<L N="60">In &thorn;e booke of Jeromy.
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>Welle we schalle vndyrstonde</L>
<L>Thatt cristyndom hatt vn&thorn;erfonge.</L>
<L>"Thatt day, Ihesus to vs se</L>
<L N="64">As &thorn;ou<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Omitted, and inserted in Margin.]</NOTE> vs bowtyst vppon a tre,</L>
<L>Thatt we may com to &thorn;y blysse</L>
<L>Lord, when &thorn;y wille ys!"</L>
<L>The vj day schall down Falle</L>
<L N="68">The treys with &thorn;e croppys alle,</L>
<L>And toward &thorn;e erthe the croppys schalle be.</L>
<L>For fere the man schalle lese hys wyff,</L>
<L>The wyff her chyld, &thorn;e chylld his lyff;</L>
<L N="72">Alle thatt leve schall lese here wytte;</L>
<L>Wo they be thatt schalle a-byde hytte,</L>
<L>Bettyr they were to be oute off lyve</L>
<L>Than soche payne for to dryve.</L>
<L N="76">The vij day schalle fall down</L>
<L>Chyrche and castelle and euery town<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS. <I>down</I>]</NOTE>;</L>
<L>All schall to-breke; and euery hylle</L>
<L>Shalle lowe, valeys For to Fylle;</L>
<L N="80">The erthe schalle [be] shene and clene;</L>
<L>In &thorn;is worlle alle schalle be evyn;</L>
<L>Than schalle &thorn;e worlle evyn be:</L>
<L>Wo ys he &thorn;at thatt schalle se!</L>
<L N="84">The viij day ys a day off drede,</L>
<L>Ryth as moyses &thorn;e prophytt seyde</L>
<L>Thatt the see woll ryse &amp; fle,</L>
<L>Thatt euery best aferd schall be;</L>
<L N="88">Than for drede hytt woll ryse &amp; flowe</L>
<L>With wawys grete, &amp; stormys towe:</L>
<L>Thorowe the strength off &thorn;e wynd</L>
<L>Into the Welken hitt schall slynge;</L>
<L N="92">All thatt leuyth &thorn;att day</L>
<L>Wold fle away, but &thorn;ey ne may;</L>
<L>Vndyr erthe I-hydd they wold be</L>
<L>Thatt Ihesu cryst scholl nott hem Ase.</L>
<L N="96">Then wolle the see wytdrawe,
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>And wend to hys owyn hawe.</L>
<L>Godd of heuyn, &thorn;at best may,</L>
<L>Haue mercy on vs vppon &thorn;att day!</L>
<L N="100">The ix day, wondyr hytt ys,</L>
<L>As the prophecy tellyth hytt I-wys:</L>
<L>Thatt all &thorn;ynge schall speke &thorn;an,</L>
<L>And cry in erthe aftyr &thorn;e steuyn off man,</L>
<L N="104">And be-mone hem self in owr sy&yogh;th</L>
<L>Ryth as &thorn;ey speke myth.</L>
<L>Lord Ihesu, thy myth &thorn;ou fullfelle!</L>
<L>We be sorry &thorn;att we dede agayn &thorn;i wille</L>
<L N="108">Or with towyth or with dede.</L>
<L>Lord Ihesu! brenge vs oute of &thorn;is drede</L>
<L>Thatt we may com to rest!</L>
<L>Ther bale ys most, &amp; bote ys nexte.</L>
<L N="112">The .x. day ys day of welaway</L>
<L>As gregory sayth, and Jeromy:</L>
<L>Than schalle knele &thorn;e angelys bryth</L>
<L>Before &thorn;e face of godd allmyth.</L>
<L N="116">Seynt peter, no&thorn;er his felow-redde,</L>
<L>Dar nott speke A word for drede;</L>
<L>They schalle se heuyn vngo,<NOTE PLACE="marg">[O.H.G. <I>intg&acirc;n</I>, to perish.&mdash;Bradley.]</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;e erthe schall Also,</L>
<L N="120">They schalle schryke &amp; crye lome</L>
<L>For &thorn;e drede of &thorn;e grett dome.</L>
<L>Develyn schall com oute off helle</L>
<L>As seynt Johan doyth vs tell,</L>
<L N="124">They schalle kry, "lord, thyn ore</L>
<L>Off our sorowe &amp; of our sore!</L>
<L>Lett vs to heuyn com!</L>
<L>Longe &thorn;ou hast hytt vs be-nome</L>
<L N="128">For our gylt, and our mysdede,</L>
<L>And for our awyn wykkyd rede!"</L>
<L>Thys ys a day of moche sorowe;</L>
<L>A strongyr comyth on the morrowe,</L>
<L N="132">The xi day comyth lyche,
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>With stronge stormys sykyrlyche,</L>
<L>And alle the stonys moche &amp; lyte</L>
<L>Scholle to-gedyr sore smyte;</L>
<L N="136">Alle the worlle schalle to-dryve;</L>
<L>Wo be &thorn;ey &thorn;att ben on lyve!</L>
<L>The rayn bowe Iwryyd schalle be,</L>
<L>Grymlyche In sy&yogh;th for to see.</L>
<L N="140">Than the deuelyn schalle swyde ren,</L>
<L>And for fere to helle torn;</L>
<L>God wille say, "ther schull ye be,</L>
<L>Ther schall ye wone &amp; be war<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? war be]</NOTE>:"</L>
<L N="144">God grownte so to be-tyde</L>
<L>Thatt we may be on bettyr syde!</L>
<L>The xij day ys dredfulle than;</L>
<L>For than was neuer schappe of man</L>
<L N="148">That wolle &thorn;att god dyd hym ryth,</L>
<L>Yff he dyrst, &amp; most of myth.</L>
<L>Angelys thatt hym seruyn alle,</L>
<L>Scholl for vs vppon kneys falle,</L>
<L N="152">To goddys feett for our syn;</L>
<L>And for the loue of all man kyn.</L>
<L>Lord we be-seche the</L>
<L>In &thorn;i mercy for to be!</L>
<L N="156">Dredfully comyth the xiij day</L>
<L>To all &thorn;att Abyde hytt may.</L>
<L>Fro the begynnynge of Adamys com</L>
<L>Tylle the end of &thorn;e day of doome,</L>
<L N="160">Ne myth no man in booke rede</L>
<L>Half the sorow, no&thorn;er half &thorn;e drede,</L>
<L>That god schalle say than</L>
<L>When he comyth down yn schappe of man;</L>
<L N="164">For alle the stonys grett and smale</L>
<L>Thatt byth in erthe withoutyn tale,</L>
<L>All they schalle to-gedyr drynge,</L>
<L>And euerychon to o&thorn;er dynge;</L>
<L N="168">They schall ryse &amp; grynd so
<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>Thatt &thorn;e fyr fro hem schalle go;</L>
<L>They schall bren also bryth</L>
<L>As &thorn;e fyr of &thorn;e dondyr lyth.</L>
<L N="172">The xiiij day ys A day of sorowe;</L>
<L>Stronge fyr schalle com on &thorn;e morow,</L>
<L>Ther schalle nothyng in &thorn;ys worlle leve</L>
<L>Butt schalle bren to morow tyll eve.</L>
<L N="176">Thys passyth nott swythe sone;</L>
<L>On the morow ys &thorn;e day of doome.</L>
<L>The xv day comyth swythe:</L>
<L>For euery man &thorn;at was on lyve</L>
<L N="180">Fro Adamys tyme, the fyrst man,</L>
<L>Alle to the dome schalle com than,</L>
<L>Euery man of xxx<SUP>ti</SUP> wynter olde,</L>
<L>All schall com &thorn;e dome to be-holde;</L>
<L N="184">Euery man schalle o&thorn;ere mete</L>
<L>Att the mownte of olevett.</L>
<L>Two angelys schall blowe her bemys;</L>
<L>The folke schall com alle attonys.</L>
<L N="188">Fulle sore than they may Agryse</L>
<L>Whan they shulle to &thorn;e dome aryse;</L>
<L>Two angelys schall com be-forne</L>
<L>With &thorn;e scorges, and with the crowne of thorn,</L>
<L N="192">With drewry cher and sory mode,</L>
<L>As hytt on hys hedd stode;</L>
<L>And the sper al so scharpe</L>
<L>As hytt stod on hys hertt.</L>
<L N="196">For no enuy, ne for no pryde,</L>
<L>Longeus hym stonge dorow &thorn;e syde:</L>
<L>Longeus then styll stode,</L>
<L>On hys fyngorys ran &thorn;e blod,</L>
<L N="200">He strokyd ther-with hys eyn ryth,</L>
<L>They be-coom as cler as candyll&yogh;th.</L>
<L>"Kynge and lord full of pyte,</L>
<L>Thys mys-gylt &thorn;ou for-yeue me!</L>
<L N="204">I dyd hyt for non evyll dede,
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>No&thorn;er for no covetyse of mede."</L>
<L>Angelys schall brenge &thorn;e rode bryth,</L>
<L>With blody naylys precyous of syth.</L>
<L N="208">Then comyth our lord with drewry mode,</L>
<L>Wyth armys I-spred all on blod:</L>
<L>"Man, now &thorn;e soth &thorn;ou mayst I-se,</L>
<L>Whatt I sufferd her for the.</L>
<L N="212">Thys passyon I sufferd her for &thorn;e:</L>
<L>I-cronyd I was with thornys of a tre;</L>
<L>Thys was to the leff for to swere</L>
<L>Be my eyn &amp; be myn here,</L>
<L N="216">And be my paynys that wher stronge.</L>
<L>Man, hytt was &thorn;e fulle ryve</L>
<L>To swere be my wowndys fyve,</L>
<L>Be my tethe And my tonge,</L>
<L N="220">Be my hertt and be my longe,</L>
<L>Hytt thowyth the fulle grett pryde</L>
<L>For to swere be my syde,</L>
<L>Be my brayne &amp; be my hedd;<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? <I>heved</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="224">be my sowle I was ofte be-revyd.</L>
<L>Man, hytt was full grett dyspyte</L>
<L>So offte to make me edwyte!</L>
<L>Thou woldyst nott clothe me, ne fede,</L>
<L N="228">Thou woldyst nott helpe me att my nede!</L>
<L>Man offte &thorn;ou hast for-sworn me!</L>
<L>Man what sufferst &thorn;ou for me?"</L>
<L>Than comyth our lady hem be-fore&mdash;</L>
<L N="232">In blyssyd tyme was she I-bore&mdash;</L>
<L>With terys rennynge alle on blodd,</L>
<L>Sore wepynge with drewry modd;</L>
<L>"Fadyr, &amp; son, and holygost,</L>
<L N="236">Kynge and lord as &thorn;ou wost,</L>
<L>My swete son, I praye de<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>thee</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>My bone to day &thorn;ou grawnt me!</L>
<L>Thy honde warke &thorn;at &thorn;ou hast wrowyth,</L>
<L N="240">My dere son, for-lese hem nowhte!
<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="125"></L>
<L>Thou bowst hem wyth &thorn;y blodd</L>
<L>And with &thorn;y flessch vppon &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>My swete son, I pray the</L>
<L N="244">For all mankynd &thorn;at I may be;</L>
<L>Graw[n]te hem &thorn;y swete blysse,</L>
<L>None of hem &thorn;att &thorn;ou ne mysse."</L>
<L>"Modyr, thy wille I-fullfyllyd shall be,</L>
<L N="248">Thy bone to day I grawnt hytt &thorn;e;</L>
<L>The goode y wille lese nowth,</L>
<L>My hondwerke that I haue wrowth.</L>
<L>Thys &thorn;att wallde nott serue me,</L>
<L N="252">My blysse schalle they neuere se,</L>
<L>Into payne they schalle wende,</L>
<L>To haue<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>haue</I> repeated in MS.]</NOTE> hytt euere withoutyn ende.</L>
<L>My chyldryn &thorn;at haue seruyd me,</L>
<L N="256">In my blysse they schall euere be;</L>
<L>Ye scholl com with me to heuyn</L>
<L>With angelys songe and mery steuyn.</L>
<L>And he clepyth hym be-fore,&mdash;</L>
<L N="260">In blyssyd tyme wer they I-bore,&mdash;</L>
<L>He spekyth to hem myldelyche,</L>
<L>'Comyth with me to my kyngdome ryche.' "</L>
<L>Lord we be-seche &thorn;e</L>
<L N="264">Thy swete blysse &thorn;att we mott se;</L>
<L>When we com to oure lyvys ende,</L>
<L>Into thy blysse &thorn;at we mot wende,</L>
<L>And grawnt vs thatt hytt so be!</L>
<L N="268">Amen, Amen, lord, For charite!<NOTE PLACE="end"><P>[For the meaning of l. 182, see Hampole's <I>Pricke of Conscience</I>, ed. Morris, 1863, p. 135, ll. 4983-90: <Q><L>&THORN;an sal alle ryse in &thorn;e same eld &thorn;an</L><L>&THORN;at God had fully here als man . . . .</L><L>&THORN;an was he of threty yhere elde, and twa,</L><L>And of thre monethes &thorn;ar-with alswa;</L><L>In &thorn;at elde alle sal ryse at the last</L><L>When &thorn;ai here &thorn;e grete bemes blast.]</L></Q></P><P>[For <I>dorow</I> through, l. 197, and <I>de</I> thee, l. 237, compare <I>The English Conquest of Ireland</I>, E. E. T. Soc.]</P></NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000144.tif" N="126">
<HEAD>Who can not Wepe, com lerne of me. (THE VIRGIN'S SONG OVER HER DEAD SON.)</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>MS. O.</I> 9. 38, <I>Trin. Coll. Cambridge. Written mostly as prose.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sodenly A-frayd, halfe wakynge, halfe slepyng,</L>
<L N="2">and gretly dysmayd, A woman sate wepyng,</L>
<L>With fauour in here face far passynge my reson;</L>
<L>And of here sore wepyng &thorn;is was &thorn;e encheson:</L>
<L>Here sone yn here lappe layd, sche seyd, sleyn by treson:</L>
<L N="6">yf wepyng my&yogh;t rype be, hit semyd then yn seson.</L>
<L>Ihesus, so sche sobbed,</L>
<L>so here sone was bobbed</L>
<L N="9">And of hys lyue robbed;</L>
<L>Seynge thys wordys as y sey the,</L>
<L N="11">"Who can not wepe, com lerne of me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="12">y seyd y cowde not wepe, y was so hard hertyd.</L>
<L>Sche answerd me schortly with wordys &thorn;at smartyd,</L>
<L>"Lo, nature schall meve &thorn;e; &thorn;ow must be conuertyd,</L>
<L N="15">thyn owne fadyr thys ny&yogh;th ys dede:" thys schee twhertyd:</L>
<L>"Ihesus, so my sone ys bobbed,</L>
<L>and of hys lyue robbed.</L>
<L N="18">ffor soth then y sobbed
<PB REF="00000145.tif" N="127"></L>
<L>Veryfyyng thys wordys, seyng to the,</L>
<L N="20">Who can not wepe com lerne at me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="21">"Now, breke hert, y the praye! thys cord lyeth so rulye,</L>
<L>So betyn, so woundyd, Entretyd so fuly.</L>
<L>What wy&yogh;t may be-hold, and wepe not? none truly,</L>
<L N="24">to see my ded dyre sone bledynge, lo, thys newly!"</L>
<L>Euer stylle schee sobbed,</L>
<L>So here sone was bobbed,</L>
<L N="27">And of hys lyue robbed.</L>
<L>Newyng these wordys, as y sey the,</L>
<L N="29">"Who can not wepe, com lerne at me."</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="30">On me sche cast here yee, and seyd, "see, man, thy brother!"</L>
<L>Sche kyste hym, and seyd, "swete, am y not thy modyr?"</L>
<L>And swonynge schee fylle; ther hyt wold be no nothyr:</L>
<L N="33">y not whych more dedlye, the tone or the todyr.</L>
<L>yett sche reuyued, and sobbed</L>
<L>how here sone was bobbed,</L>
<L N="36">&amp; of hys lyue robbed.</L>
<L>"Who can not wepe," thys ys the lay,</L>
<L N="38">And with that wordys schee vanyschyd ffinis.</L>
<L>A-way.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="poem"><PB REF="00000146.tif" N="128">
<HEAD>The Death of Archbishop Scrope</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>(WHO WAS BEHEADED, 8 JUNE, 1405).[<I>From MS. R.</I> 4. 20, <I>Trin. Coll. Cambridge, on a blank leaf at the end of Ludgate's Siege of Thebes.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hay, hay, hay, hay, thynke on Whitsonmonday!</L>
<L>The bysshop Scrope that was so wyse,</L>
<L>Nowe is he dede, and lowe he lyse;</L>
<L>To hevyns blys yhit may he ryse,</L>
<L N="5">Thurghe helpe of Marie, that mylde may, hay!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>When he was broght vnto the hylle,</L>
<L>He held hym both mylde and stylle;</L>
<L>He toke his deth with fulle gode wylle,</L>
<L N="9">As I haue herde fulle trewe men say; hay!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He that shulde his dethe be,</L>
<L>He kneled downe vppon his kne:</L>
<L>"Lord, your deth, forgyffe it me,</L>
<L N="13">Fulle hertly here to yowe I pray;" hay!</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>"Here I wylle the commende:</L>
<L>thou gyff me fyve strokys with thy hende,</L>
<L>And then my wayes thou latt me wende,</L>
<L N="17">To hevyns blys that lastys ay;" hay!<NOTE PLACE="end">[Comp. Hall's Chronicle, <I>Hen. IV.</I> fol. xxv (ed. 1550). W. A. W.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
